{"name":"Rules","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Rules","type":"text","_id":"NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div class=\"chapter-heading\"><h1>Rules</h1><figure class=\"chapter-number\"><figcaption>Savage Eberron</figcaption></figure></div><p class=\"drop-cap\">S<em>avage Eberron</em> provides a simple framework for your tales of adventure and glory. In this chapter we show you how to make basic skill and attribute checks—and make your combats Fast, Furious, and Fun!</p><h2>Wild Cards &amp; Extras</h2><p>Your hero (a player character), and unique allies, villains, and monsters are collectively called “Wild Cards.” These beings have a better chance at doing things, are a little tougher to put down, and are generally more detailed than common guards, minions, or lackeys—collectively called “Extras.”</p><p>Wild Cards are noted with a design of some sort before their name.</p><h3 class=\"dragon-icon\">Goblin Warchanter</h3><p>In <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> the Wild Card symbol is a distinctive dragon head.</p><p>Player characters are always Wild Cards. The Dungeon Master must decide which of her nonplayer characters and monsters are Wild Cards. The sergeant of the City Watch probably isn’t a Wild Card, but Sergeant Grimlock of the City Watch may be. Skytch the Dragon is also a Wild Card, though his three young wyrms aren’t.</p><p>Wild Cards are those who have stepped up to do more than most. They dare, aspire, and risk it all to be a hero—or a villain!</p><p>They have two special abilities in the game:</p><ul><li>Wild Cards can take three @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounds} before they’re @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}.</li><li>Wild Cards roll a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Die]{Wild Die} (usually a d6) along with their skill or attribute die when making @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls} and take the highest of the two as their total.</li></ul><h2>Trait Rolls</h2><p>To make a skill or attribute “check” or “roll,” simply roll the die assigned to it. If the result is a 4 or better (the “Target Number” or TN), the action is successful. For example, if a character’s Strength is a d6, he rolls a six-sided die. On a 4 or better, he’s successful.</p><p><strong>Modifiers:</strong> Circumstances modify the die roll, such as shooting at something far away or finding a well-hidden clue. Some things, such as ranged attacks, have standard modifiers. It’s up to the DM to determine any modifiers for more subjective tasks, such as spotting an ambush or eavesdropping on a conversation through a door.</p><p>In general, an easy task, such as finding tracks in the mud, is made at +2. A difficult task, such as finding tracks by torchlight, is made at −2. A very difficult task, such as finding tracks in a rainstorm, is made at −4.</p><p><strong>Multiple Dice:</strong> When a character rolls multiple dice, such as when firing two arrows with the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Rapid Shot]{Rapid Shot} Edge, check each die separately.</p><h3>Wild Die</h3><p>Extras roll a single die when making a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll}. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} roll an extra d6 and take the highest of their Trait die or the “Wild Die.” Both of these dice can Ace (see below).</p><p><strong>One Wild Die Per Action:</strong> When Wild Cards roll multiple dice for a single action, they roll only one Wild Die. It may replace a Trait die or be ignored—it never adds another action or attack to the roll.</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A fighter has the <em><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy}</strong></em> Edge. He rolls an extra Fighting die when making a melee attack along with a Wild Die. Only two of his dice can cause hits since the Wild Die can only replace a die, not add another attack.</p><h3>Aces</h3><p>All @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Trait} and damage rolls in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> are open-ended. That means that when you roll the highest number possible on a die (a 6 on a d6, an 8 on a d8, and so on), you get to roll that die again and add it to the total. This is called an “Ace.” Any modifiers to the die roll should be tacked on after adding up an Aced roll.</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A rogue attempts to leap a dangerous ice chasm. She’s a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} with a d8 in @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, so she rolls a d8 and a d6 and takes the highest result. In this case, both dice Ace (8 on the d8 and 6 on the d6). She rolls the d8 again and gets a 4 for a total of 12 on the d8. She rolls the d6 again and gets another 6, followed by a 2—that’s a total of 14 on the Wild Die. The wily rogue leaps the chasm with ease!</p><h3>Raises</h3><p>Sometimes it’s important to know just how successful a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll} was. Every 4 points over the Target Number is called a “raise.” If your hero needs a 4 to shoot an opponent and rolls an 11, he hits with a raise. Figure raises after adjusting for any modifiers.</p><p>A raise always provides an additional effect of some sort, such as bonus damage when attacking or a benefit determined by the DM for other rolls.</p><h3>Opposed Rolls</h3><p>Sometimes rolls are “opposed” by an opponent. The attacker gets a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Trait} total, then the defender attempts to beat it.</p><p>The exact skills or attributes used in a contest are specified in each circumstance, or the DM can decide what makes the most sense. If two characters try to pull something from each other’s hands, for example, they make opposed Strength rolls. Sneaking up on someone is a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} roll opposed by @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}.</p><p>The acting character in an opposed roll always makes the Trait total first (including spending any <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies}</strong>), and must get at least a basic success (TN 4) or he fails. The defender rolls next and must <em>meet</em> or <em>exceed</em> the first character’s result or the attacker wins.</p><p>The winner also uses the opponent’s total for purposes of determining raise effects.</p><h3>Critical Failures</h3><p>A Critical Failure occurs when a Wild Card rolls a 1 on both the skill die and Wild Die of a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll}. The attempt automatically fails and something bad happens—a weapon is dropped or gets stuck, the attack hits a friend, the vehicle crashes, spells misfire (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Backlash]{Backlash}</strong>), and so on.</p><p>Critical Failures cannot be rerolled by any means, even with <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies}</strong>.</p><p><strong>Extras and Critical Failures:</strong> If an Extra rolls a 1 on a Trait check <em>and it’s important to know if it’s a Critical Failure</em>, such as when casting a spell, roll a d6. On a 1, it’s a Critical Failure. Otherwise it’s just a normal failure.</p><p><strong>Multiple Dice:</strong> Some abilities allow characters to roll multiple Trait dice, such as the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy} Edge or firing a weapon with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rate of Fire]{Rate of Fire} higher than 1. A Critical Failure with multiple dice occurs when more than half the die results are a natural 1. If the character is a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}, the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Die]{Wild Die} <em>must</em> be a 1 as well.</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A fighter with the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy} Edge rolls two @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} dice and one @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Die]{Wild Die}. If two or more of the dice come up 1s, including the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Die]{Wild Die}, it’s a Critical Failure.</p><h3>Unskilled Attempts</h3><p>If a character doesn’t have a skill for an action he’s attempting, he rolls a d4 for his skill die (and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Die]{Wild Die} if a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}) and subtracts 2 from the total.</p><p>The DM may decide certain tasks cannot be attempted unskilled, such as repairing a steam engine or piloting an airship.</p><h3>Reroll</h3><p>Some Edges or abilities allow a character to reroll @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Trait} (as long as they’re not a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). To do so, roll <em>all</em> the dice again and get a new total. You may keep any set you like <em>unless</em> you roll a Critical Failure. This ends all rerolls immediately and becomes the result of the attempt—that’s the risk one takes in pushing the limits!</p><p>Multiple rerolls may be granted from different @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edges}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies}, or other abilities.</p><h3>Group Rolls</h3><p>When the DM wants to make a Trait roll for a group of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} with like @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Traits}, roll one Trait die as usual along with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Die]{Wild Die} and treat this as the group’s result. This gives a decent average without making rolls for every individual.</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> A group of soldiers attempts to pass by an enemy encampment. The DM rolls their @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} die (a d6) and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Die]{Wild Die} and takes the best of the two as the soldiers’ total.</p><h2>Bennies</h2><p>Every now and then, dice rolls may not work in your favor. That’s why <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> gives players a little control over their hero’s fate.</p><h3>Player Character Bennies</h3><p>Players start each game session with three “@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies}” (American slang for “benefits”), represented by poker chips, gaming stones, the official @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies} we make for all of our games, or other tokens that signify a little bit of good luck or fate. @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies} are discarded at the end of each session—use them or lose them!</p><p><strong>Combat:</strong> If a session ends in the middle of combat or other dramatic event, wait until it’s resolved in the next session before giving out new @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies}.</p><p><strong>GM Rewards:</strong> @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies} are earned during the game in two ways:</p><ul><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">Awards:</span> The Dungeon Master should occasionally reward players for clever actions, roleplaying their character (especially any Hindrances), or great feats of heroism.<br />She can also award players a Benny for telling a great story in character, delivering a fantastic line that makes everyone laugh, or creating an emotional moment.</p></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Joker’s Wild:</span> When a player character draws a Joker during combat, <em>all</em> player characters receive a Benny! If the players get both Jokers everyone gets <em>two</em> Bennies!</li></ul><h3>Dungeon Master Bennies</h3><p>Dungeon Masters start each session with a pool of one Benny per player character. These may be used by any of her characters (including non-Wild Cards!).</p><p>The DM's Wild Cards also have Bennies of their own, a base of three modified by their Edges and Hindrances. They can use these or any of the Bennies in the common pool as the DM wishes.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Joker’s Wild:</span> Anytime the villains draw a Joker, put one Benny in their general pool and give another to each enemy @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card}.</li></ul><h3>Using Bennies</h3><p>Bennies may be spent at any appropriate time and don’t incur any sort of penalty. They may only be used for your own character.</p><p>Here are the ways players can use Bennies.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Reroll a Trait:</span> Bennies grant a hero a reroll on <em>any</em> Trait (see <strong>Rerolls,</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{here}).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Recover from @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}:</span> This is instant and may be done at any time, even interrupting another’s actions if desired.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Recover Power Points:</span> A character with an Arcane Background, Mystic Powers, or any other ability that grants @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} can spend a Benny as a free action to recover five Power Points.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Soak Rolls:</span> Bennies can be used to prevent @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounds} or recover from being Shaken.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Draw a New @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Card}:</span> When the game is in rounds, a character can spend a Benny to get a new <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Cards}</strong>. This occurs after all cards are dealt and Edges or Hindrances like @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Quick]{Quick}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Level Headed]{Level Headed}, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Hesitant]{Hesitant} are resolved. <em>Then</em> players or the DM may spend Bennies for an additional card as many times as they like and take their choice of all their draws. Edges like Quick or Level Headed <em>do not</em> apply to these additional cards drawn with Bennies. This continues until everyone (including the GM) passes. Then the round begins and no further cards may be drawn.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Reroll Damage:</span> You may spend a Benny to reroll damage. Include any additional dice you may have gained for a raise on the attack roll.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Influence the Story:</span> This one is entirely up to the Dungeon Master, who may allow a character to spend a Benny to find an additional clue if you’re stuck, come up with some mundane but needed item, or push a nonplayer character into being a bit more agreeable.</li></ul><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> The party is adrift on a storm-tossed sea. None of the characters purchased navigational equipment, but Harsk the ranger had been aiding their doomed captain through the previous encounters. Harsk's player asks the Dungeon Master if he might have been given his own compass and maps while aiding the captain, and might still have them in his bag. The DM agrees—for a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}. Harsk suddenly remembers the tools in his pack and turns the boat toward shore.</p><p> </p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h2>Awarding Bennies</h2><p>It takes a few games to figure out how many @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies} you should award players during a session. In general, we recommend you be fairly free with them, especially early in the game. If someone makes everyone laugh (and isn’t distracting the flow of the game), toss the player a Benny. When players roleplay a Hindrance, reward them. When someone does something clever or heroic or imaginative, acknowledge it with a Benny.</p><p>Some GMs worry the game will become too easy if Bennies are too common, but we find the opposite is true. When Bennies are plentiful, players often spend them on trivial things that are important to <em>them</em>. Maybe the rogue <em>really</em> wants to pick the lock on a chest. There’s nothing particularly valuable inside and the player probably knows it, but the character is the <em>rogue</em> and wants to prove it to the rest of the party.</p><p>When Bennies are scarce, however, players tend to save them for injuries, death, or taking out the big bads. That’s fine, but takes away from the fun and heroics that got them to this point. <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> is about big action and players should be encouraged to take chances. The “currency” of these chances are those Bennies.</p><p>Veteran <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> GMs might also notice Bennies tend to flow fairly fast early on in a session. The group is settling in, laughing, and are rewarded for roleplaying their Hindrances the first time or two. In the mid-to-late game, Bennies tend to be spent faster than they’re gained. That’s a fantastic pace. It gives the heroes opportunities to do big things in the early and mid-game then forces some critical resource management for the final showdown.</p><p>If you find yourself being stingy, go the other way the next time you run and see how it affects your group. Then you’ll know what’s right for you and your friends.</p></aside><h2>Conviction</h2><p>Conviction is a special award granted when a character experiences a great and meaningful victory; or a painful and catastrophic misfortune. Either drives the hero to increase her efforts, giving her inner strength she can draw on in the most desperate situations.</p><p>Like @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies}, players should receive a physical token of some sort to note their Conviction. The tokens can be spent at any time to add a d6 to all the character’s Trait and damage totals until the beginning of her next turn. This die can @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace}, and its result is added to the final total.</p><div><img style=\"padding:1%\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/sorrowful-regret.webp\" /></div><p>Conviction tokens don't stack, but the bonus may be maintained from round to round by spending a Benny at the start of the character's turn. Once Conviction lapses, however, the effect ends.</p><p>Conviction tokens aren’t Bennies and can’t be used as such. They <em>are</em> kept between sessions, however, and a hero can have more than one Conviction token at a time.</p><p><strong>Refresh:</strong> A hero may also spend Conviction to trigger or refresh abilities that are usually only usable once per session, day, encounter, and so on, even if they’ve already been used.</p><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Tragedy &amp; Triumph</h2><p>Seelah the paladin of Iomedae and her companions signed on to escort a caravan from Turtleback Ferry to Sandpoint. Over the course of the journey, they made friends with the caravanners. Seelah became particularly close with a young girl she thought of as a daughter, Julia.</p><p>Then tragedy struck. A savage and brutal band of ogres descended from the hills and attacked the caravan. Seelah and her friends tore into the ogres with savage ferocity, but when the dust settled, Julia was found dead.</p><p>Given her close relationship with the girl, the Dungeon Master decides Seelah's player gains @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Conviction]{Conviction}. The paladin burns with rage at the murderous ogres and chastises herself for failing to protect her friend.</p><p>Later on, the party corners the ogres' chief in his hilltop fortress. Seelah personally defeats the brute in single combat and avenges Julia's death. The Dungeon Master decides the paladin's triumph is also worthy of Conviction.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Combat","type":"text","_id":"5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div><h1 class=\"wide\">Combat</h1></div><p>Whether they’re the burning plains of the Cinderlands or the cursed battlefield of the Plain of Ten Thousand Swords—these are <cite>Savage Worlds</cite> and they are often violent.</p><p>The rest of this chapter tells you how great heroes and terrible monsters battle in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>. The combat rules are designed for use with miniatures or pawns by default, but it’s easy to use these concepts when you’re playing without them.</p><p><strong>Distance:</strong> Because the game assumes you are using terrain or a battlemat and standard 28mm miniatures, movement and weapon ranges are listed in inches. To translate that to regular distance, one inch equals two yards.</p><p>If you’re using miniatures and need to accommodate a larger battlefield, simply set each inch as five or 10 yards, for example, and adjust movement and ranges appropriately.</p><p><strong>Time:</strong> When a fight breaks out, game time breaks down into rounds of about six seconds each. Ten rounds equal one minute.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Round:</span> A “round” is an entire countdown of @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Cards}, from the Ace to the Deuce (Two).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Turn:</span> A character’s “turn” occurs when his Action Card comes up in the countdown. A hero with the Six of Diamonds, for example, takes his turn when that card comes up in the round.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Action:</span> A single attack, skill use, etc. Characters may perform multiple actions on their turn (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions}</strong>).</li></ul><h2>Action Cards (Initiative)</h2><p>The action in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> is fast and furious. To help the Dungeon Master keep track of who goes in what order and add a little randomness to the game, we use a single deck of playing cards with both Jokers left in to determine everyone’s initiative order. We call these “Action Cards.”</p><p>The DM can deal cards face up or face down as she sees fit. She might also deal the players’ cards face up and the villains face down to increase the players’ tension and uncertainty!</p><p>At the start of each round:</p><ul><li>Deal each @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} an Action Card (plus any extra cards for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edges}). @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Allies]{Allies} under a player’s control act on his Action Card.</li><li>Groups of nonplayer characters and creatures, such as all @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Zombie, Human]{zombies}, all @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Dog/wolf]{wolves}, and so on, should share an Action Card so they act together. This breaks each group up a bit for dramatic purposes and game balance and keeps things easy for the Dungeon Master to manage.</li></ul><p><strong>Shuffle:</strong> Shuffle the deck after any round in which a Joker was dealt.</p><p><strong>Large Groups:</strong> In very large groups or time-sensitive games, the Dungeon Master can deal a single card per side (heroes and villains). On the heroes’ turn, simply start at one end of the group and work quickly around. This speeds things up if that’s more important than varying initiative order. If one or more characters have @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Level Headed]{Level Headed} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Quick]{Quick}, let that apply to the draw (but only once).</p><h2>Actions</h2><p>Characters perform “actions” when their @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Card} comes up each round. This is their “turn.” A character can move (see <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{Movement}</strong>, below) and perform one regular action at any point in her movement, attacking, casting a spell, and so on, without penalty.</p><p>Characters can choose from a multitude of actions on their turn. Common actions include @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Supporting} allies, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Testing} foes, using a power, or attacking with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}. See <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions}</strong> to perform more than one action per turn (though only one of these can be a limited action).</p><p>More complex actions like lighting a torch or digging through a backpack might require more than a round to complete (DM's call).</p><h2>Movement</h2><p>Characters can move a number of tabletop inches equal to their Pace each turn, and may freely set their facing as they do so.</p><p>Each inch of movement spent climbing, crawling, or swimming uses 2″ of Pace.</p><p><strong>Running:</strong> A hero can “run” as a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action} once per turn, increasing her Pace for the round by her running die (a d6 by default) at the cost of a −2 penalty to all other actions that turn. Running dice never @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace}. (The running die is random to account for nuances of terrain not depicted on the tabletop and for the “risk to reward” decision players must make.)</p><p>Out of combat situations, a character can move twice the sum of her full Pace + maximum running die for a number of minutes equal to half her Vigor die type. Thus a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Fleet-Footed]{Fleet-Footed} character with Vigor d6 can sprint at a Pace of 32 for three minutes.</p><p><strong>Difficult Ground:</strong> Each inch a hero moves over rough terrain such as thick forest, up or down a steep incline, slippery ice, etc., counts as 2″ of her Pace. Crawling is unaffected by Difficult Ground.</p><p><strong>Hazards:</strong> If the DM feels movement is hazardous for some reason—climbing under duress, swimming a fast-moving river, walking a tightrope—she can require an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll to move. Success means she continues on normally. Failure means she can’t move. With a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} the character takes @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>, falls if climbing or in a precarious position (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Falling]{Falling}</strong>), or drowns if swimming (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Drowning]{Drowning}</strong>) both in @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}.</p><h2>Attacks</h2><p>The basics of fast, furious combat are discussed in @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Melee Attacks]{Melee Attacks} and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{Ranged Attacks}. Many additional options and situations are covered under <strong>Situational Rules</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Situational Rules]{here}.</p><h2>Damage</h2><p>After a successful melee or ranged hit, the attacker rolls damage. Ranged weapons do fixed damage as listed in the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.QKA6dagfLDYyCUh6.JournalEntryPage.kYcSTPeASQ45iHrC]{Gear} section. Most bows, for example, cause 2d6 damage.</p><p>Hand weapons cause damage equal to the attacker’s @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} die plus a second die, which depends on the weapon. A barbarian with a d12 Strength and a long sword (d8 damage) rolls d12+d8 damage. Add the rolls on the damage dice together to get the damage total.</p><p>Even though Strength is used to determine melee damage, this isn’t a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll} so @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} don’t add a Wild Die to the roll.</p><p>All damage rolls can @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace}.</p><p><strong>Unarmed Damage:</strong> An unarmed combatant rolls only his @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} die unless he has an @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edge} like <strong>\"@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Brawler]{Brawler}</strong> that grants him a damage die.</p><h2>Damage Effects</h2><p>Damage can result in three effects: Shaken, Woounds, and Incapacitation.</p><h3>Shaken</h3><p>Shaken characters are nicked, bruised, or otherwise rattled. They may only take free actions, such as moving (including running). At the start of their turn, Shaken characters must attempt to recover from being Shaken by making a Spirit roll. This is a free action.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Failure:</span> The character remains Shaken. She can only perform free actions.</li><li>Success: The character is no longer Shaken and may act normally.</li></ul><p><strong>Bennies:</strong> A player may spend a Benny at any time to remove her Shaken status (even when it’s not her turn).</p><h3>Wounds</h3><p>Every raise on the damage roll inflicts a Wound. Extras are Incapacitated if they take a single Wound (and aren’t <strong>Resilient</strong>). They’re dead, injured, or otherwise out of the fight.</p><p>Wild Cards can take three Wounds and still function (more with certain Edges or abilities). Further damage doesn’t cause additional Wounds but Incapacitates them instead.</p><p><strong>Wound Penalties:</strong> Each Wound a character suffers causes a −1 cumulative penalty to his Pace (minimum of 1″) and all Trait rolls--up to a maximum penalty of −3.</p><p><strong>Timing:</strong> Characters sometimes take multi­ple hits on the same Action Card. Resolve each damage roll separately before moving on to the next (including any Soak rolls).</p><h3>Wound Cap</h3><p>In <cite>Savage Pathfinder</cite>, characters can never suffer more than four Wounds in a single hit and therefore never have to Soak more than four wounds either. This rule keeps combat dangerous but reduces the chances of heroes (and villains!) dying from a single lucky blow. It can still happen, but it is far more rare.</p><p>Ignore the cap for catastrophic damage such as falls from great heights, extreme environments such as lava, and so on.</p><p><strong>Large Creatures:</strong> The Wound Cap still applies to large or Resilient creatures with more than three Wounds. A Huge dragon that can take five Wounds before being @UUID[Compendium.swpf-core-rules.swpf-rules.swpfcore03rules0.JournalEntryPage.03combat00000000]{Incapacitated}, for example, can’t take more than four from a single attack, so it can’t be killed with a single attack even if it fails to Soak.</p><h3>Incapacitation</h3><p>Incapacitated characters may not perform actions but are still dealt Action Cards for the remainder of the encounter in case they recover or must roll for other effects such as <strong>Bleeding Out</strong> (below). Edges or Hindrances that affect card draws, such as Quick, Level Headed, or Hesitant are ignored when the hero is Incapacitated.</p><p>If Incapacitated by damage or injury, he must make an immediate Vigor roll:</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Critical Failure:</span> The character dies.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Failure:</span> Roll on the <strong>Injury Table</strong>. The Injury is permanent and the character is <strong>Bleeding Out</strong>, see Bleeding Out below.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Success:</span> Roll on the <strong>Injury Table</strong>. The Injury goes away when all Wounds are healed.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Raise:</span> Roll on the <strong>Injury Table</strong>. The Injury goes away in 24 hours, or when all Wounds are healed (whichever is sooner).</li></ul><p>Characters cannot take actions of any kind and might be unconscious (GM’s call). The victim makes a Vigor roll each day thereafter and is no longer Incapacitated(or unconscious) if successful. They may also heal Wounds during this time (see <strong>Natural Healing</strong>).</p><p><strong>Bleeding Out:</strong> The injured character is dying and must make a Vigor roll at the start of his turn. Failure means he perishes. With success he survives but must roll again next turn (or every minute if not in combat). With a raise, he stabilizes and no further rolls are required.</p><p>Other characters may stop a victim’s bleeding by making a Healing roll (the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing}{skill} or the spell). This is an action, and if successful the patient is stabilized.</p><p>The <em>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing}{healing}</em> power can also stabilize Wounds, as can a successful “natural” healing roll by a being with regeneration of some sort.</p><p><strong>Incapacitation from @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.7LJ6PoYcYzg4lThm]{Fatigue}</strong></p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h2>More on Shaken</h2><p>Figuring out how Shaken and Wounds work together takes a little getting used to, but is worth it for the game play it provides. In essence, it means Shaking an Extra twice usually takes it off the table. It gets a bit more complicated with Wild Card or creatures that can take more than one Wound, so here’s a table that might help.</p><h3><span class=\"red-label\">Examples:</span></h3><ul><li>A character takes a Wound. She’s also Shaken.</li><li>A character is Shaken, then takes a Wound. She has one Wound and remains Shaken.</li><li>A character is already Shaken, then Shaken again (without a Wound). She now has one Wound and remains Shaken.</li><li>A character has two Wounds and is Shaken. She takes another Wound, so she has three Wounds and remains Shaken.</li></ul><table><tbody><tr><th><h4>Damage</h4></th><th><h4>Victim is Unshaken</h4></th><th><h4>Victim is Already Shaken</h4></th></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\"><p><strong>Success</strong> (0–3 points of damage over Toughness)</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>Shaken</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>1 Wound and remains Shaken</p></td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\"><p><strong>1 Raise</strong> (4–7 points of damage over Toughness)</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>1 Wound and Shaken</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>1 and remains Shaken</p></td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\"><p><strong>2 Raises</strong> (8–11 points of damage over Toughness)</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>2 Wounds and Shaken</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>2 Wounds and remains Shaken</p></td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\"><p><strong>3 Raises</strong> (12–15 points of damage over Toughness)</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>3 Wounds and Shaken</p></td><td class=\"centered\"><p>3 Wounds and remains Shaken</p></td></tr></tbody></table></aside><h2>Soak Rolls</h2><p>After taking damage but before applying any Wounds, the defender may spend a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies} to make a “Soak” roll. This is a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} check, with each success and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} reducing the number of @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounds} suffered from that attack by one.</p><img src=\"/modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/redemption.webp\" class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url(/modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/redemption.webp)\" /><p>If the character Soaks <em>all</em> of the @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounds} from an attack, he removes his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} condition too (even from a previous source). Don’t count the Wound modifiers he’s <em>about</em> to suffer when making this roll—that hasn’t happened yet.</p><p>Characters can’t Soak more than once per attack, but may spend @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies} as usual to reroll the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} check if they aren’t satisfied with the results.</p><p><strong>Shaken:</strong> A character can spend a Benny to immediately eliminate a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} condition. This is instant and can be done at any time.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Healing","type":"text","_id":"xxwdxRsojxeKXK6A","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div><h1 class=\"wide\">Healing</h1></div><p>The @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} skill is used to remove @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{wounds}. Each attempt requires 10 minutes per wound level of the patient. Subtract 1 from Healing rolls without a basic healer's kit or similar supplies.</p><p>A success removes one Wound, and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} removes two. Failure means no Wounds are removed. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} <em>increases</em> the victim’s Wound level by one.</p><p><strong>The Golden Hour:</strong> A character may only attempt to heal Wounds on a patient once within the hour they were sustained. Failing the roll means the healer isn’t able to treat those particular injuries. A <em>different</em> character may attempt a Healing roll on the same patient, however.</p><p>Once the Wounds are over an hour old, only @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Healing]{natural healing} or the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> power (using <em>greater healing</em>) can heal Wounds.</p><p><strong>Bleeding Out:</strong> The Healing skill can also be used to stabilize someone who’s <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bleeding Out]{Bleeding Out} </strong>. Each attempt is an action, and if successful the victim is stabilized.</p><p><strong>Incapacitation:</strong> Healing at least one Wound on an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} patient removes that state (and restores consciousness if he was knocked out).</p><div><img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/relief.webp')\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/relief.webp\" /></div><h2>Natural Healing</h2><p>Wounded characters make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll every five days. Success recovers one @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wound}, and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} recovers two.</p><p>A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} <em>increases</em> the victim’s Wound level by one—either from infection, blood loss, or aggravating the injuries. If this causes @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitation}, don’t use the usual rules for taking damage. Instead, the victim lapses in and out of consciousness and makes a Vigor roll every 12 hours. If the roll is failed, he expires. Success means he must roll again 12 hours later. With a raise he stabilizes and wakes. Allies may also attempt to stabilize the hero as explained under <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bleeding Out]{Bleeding Out}</strong>.</p><p><strong>Support:</strong> Don’t forget to use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} when your party has been beaten up a bit. Characters with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}, or other skills can make Support rolls to help allies make their Vigor rolls to heal!</p><h2>Aftermath &amp; Extras</h2><p>If it’s important to know what happens to Extras who were @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} during a fight, make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll for each. Those who succeed survive and must be cared for, taken prisoner, or released. This can present interesting challenges for your heroes in the aftermath of savage combat!</p><p> </p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h2>The Golden Hour</h2><p>Patients who survive their initial trauma have about an hour to survive most life-threatening injuries. If they receive medical attention during that time, they can generally be saved. The longer the wait, however, the more likely the @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounds} are to be fatal.</p><p>In <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>, we extend this concept to healing in general. Besides reflecting the real-world concept, it also provides good game balance and drama as the party has to decide whether to press on despite their injuries.</p></aside></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":250000,"name":"Combat Survival Guide","type":"text","_id":"gOvbhBhA1dnfbM27","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div><h1 class=\"wide\">Combat Survival Guide</h1></div><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"5\">Combat Survival Guide</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading center\" style=\"width:25%\" colspan=\"2\">And...</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\" style=\"width:25%\">Then Try to...</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\" style=\"width:40%\">Game Effect...</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\" style=\"width:10%\">Helps...</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><span class=\"no-class\">You are having trouble hitting your opponent because they have a high parry</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">Your team outnumbers the foe</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{GANG UP}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>+1 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} for each additional non-Stunned ally in melee with the target (max +4).</p><p>Lower this bonus by 1 point for every enemy adjacent to the target (min 0).</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Team</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You have a high Strength, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, and/or a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shields Table]{Shields}, you can move before acting and/or you have a shield</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{PUSH}</strong> to knock them  @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Opposed Strength or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (each one chooses) roll (+2 if moved 2\" before pushing, + Shield Parry Bonus): push 1\", 2\" with a raise.</p><p>The foe also rolls @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (-2 if the pusher raised) to avoid falling @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone}.</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Team</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You are OK with lowering your defense</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Do a <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Attack]{WILD ATTACK}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">+2 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, +2 damage, but you are now @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable} till the end of your next turn</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You are using a melee weapon</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Switch to <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{RANGED ATTACK}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>An enemy without @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} has a target number of 4 to be hit by a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{ranged attack}.</p><p>Change up to 2 weapons as a free action once per turn.</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><span class=\"no-class\">You are having trouble hitting your opponent with a ranged attack because of penalties</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You can miss a turn and you can stand still in your position</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Spend some time taking <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.aMKEcG5KZtdH143K]{AIM}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Spend the entire turn (movement included) to lower by up to 4 points of penalties (from @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0]{Called Shots}, Range…) OR add +2 to the first ranged attack of the next round.</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You are using a ranged weapon, and you can shorten the distance to engage in melee</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Switch to <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Melee Attacks]{MELEE ATTACK}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} is ignored with melee attacks and  @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone} are actually easier to hit.</p><p>Change up to 2 weapons as a free action once per turn.</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><span class=\"no-class\">Other options besides hitting your opponent</span></th></tr><tr><td class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><em>Many of these combat manuevers assist allies in your party in either hitting your opponents or damaging them. You can always assist the rest of yourparty in being better fighters through these manuevers.</em></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"><p>You can help an ally <br />(\"he has a weak spot there!\", trip the foe, \"JUST DO IT!\")</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{SUPPORT}</strong> an ally’s combat skill</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Describe how you help your ally’s Trait and roll your relevant Skill to give them +1 with a success, +2 with a raise (max +4).</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Ally, Team</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"><p>You can hinder your foe through a clever tactic <br />(throw sand in their eyes, a feint, \"look behind you\", provocations, war cries)</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{TEST}</strong> your foe to make them  @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted or Vulnerable}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Describe a TEST and roll a relevant Skill against the foe’s linked Attribute.</p><p><strong>Success:</strong> the foe is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted} or @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable}, your choice. <br /><strong>Raise:</strong> as with above plus roll on the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Creative Combat]{Creative Combat} table.</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Team</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You are OK with sacrificing your movement</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{GRAPPLE}</strong> your foe</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (or Strength -2) vs @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (or Strength -2) to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled} the target, or to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound} (the grappler is also VULNERABLE) with a raise.</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Team</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><span class=\"no-class\">You are having trouble dealing enough damage to your opponent</span></th></tr><tr><td class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><em>Many of the combat manuevers that assist in hitting a foe also help deal damage, as they increase the chance of getting a raise and adding @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bonus Damage]{Bonus Damage}.</em></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You aren't have problem hitting your opponent</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Do a <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0]{CALLED SHOT}</strong> against a week point</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p><strong>Limb:</strong> –2 (may @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.V6XYsi78mgZos4kc]{Disarm})<br /><strong>Hand:</strong> –4 (may @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.V6XYsi78mgZos4kc]{Disarm})<br /><strong>Head/Vitals:</strong> –4 (+4 damage)<br /><strong>Unarmored Area:</strong> –? (damage ignores @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor]{Armor}).</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You are ok with lowering your defenses</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Do a <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Attack]{WILD ATTACK}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">+2 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, +2 damage, but you are now @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable} till the end of your next turn</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><span class=\"no-class\">You are going to do soon if you keep standing there!</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You are engaged in melee with multiple opponents and dont want to get hit anymore</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Take the <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.ULJc5K7JHFp6hFnL]{DEFEND}</strong> action and then <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Withdrawing From Melee]{WITHDRAW FROM MELEE}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Each non-@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and non-@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned} adjacent enemy receives a free attack against the hero that flees from melee. You may use your turn to @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.ULJc5K7JHFp6hFnL]{Defend} in order to gain +4 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} and move your normal Pace (but not run).</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" rowspan=\"2\">You are engaged with a single enemy....</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">... and you have a high Strength, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, and/or a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shields Table]{Shields}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{PUSH}</strong> to make your foe non adjacent, then move</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Opposed Strength or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (each one chooses) roll (+2 if moved 2\" before pushing, + Shield Parry Bonus): push 1\", 2\" with a raise.</p><p>The foe also rolls @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (-2 if the pusher raised) to avoid falling @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone}.</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You, Team</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">... and you can hinder your opponent through a clever tactic</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{TEST}</strong> to make your foe @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted}, then move</td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Describe a TEST and roll a relevant Skill against the foe’s linked Attribute.</p><p><strong>Success:</strong> the foe is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted} or @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable}, your choice.<br /><strong>Raise:</strong> as with above plus roll on the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Creative Combat]{Creative Combat} table.</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You, Team</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\">You are being targeted by @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Attacks]{ranged attacks}.</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Find <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{COVER}</strong> or move then drop <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{PRONE}</strong></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Attackers subtract from –2 to –8 to their ranged attacks against you, depending on the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} you found, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone} is a –4 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} against ranged attacks from 3\"+.</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">You</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Combat Effects and/or States</h2><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}:</span> Cannot move, cannot do other physical actions except trying to break free, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{DISTRACTED} and @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{VULNERABLE} as long as they remain @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}. Use an action to roll @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (or Strength –2) and become @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{ENTANGLED} with a success, or break free with a raise.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted}:</span> –2 to the character’s roll until the end of their next turn.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled}:</span> Cannot move and is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{DISTRACTED} as long as they remain @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled}. Use an action to roll @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (or Strength –2) and break free.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{Prone}:</span> –2 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry}, –2 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, –4 to be hit from range 3”+ (doesn’t stack with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{COVER}), –4 damage from attack with @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{Area of Effects}, use 2” of Pace to crawl 1” or to stand up.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}:</span> Can only perform free actions (including normal movement, plus eventually running). Recover from being @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{SHAKEN} as free action with a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Spirit} roll at the start of the character’s turn.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned}:</span> Can’t move nor take actions, is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{PRONE}, attacks against him get @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.l1rEt2RnvcIiEGtQ]{THE DROP}. Each turn make a Vigor roll to recover: success recovers but is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{DISTRACTED} and @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{VULNERABLE}, raise no ill effects.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable}:</span> +2 to every roll against them until the end of their next turn.</li></ul><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/warforged-fight-for-lives.webp\" /><p> </p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ltavh0xcxs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules","color":"#008000"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"swade","systemVersion":"2.2.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1674613451064,"modifiedTime":1675702845145,"lastModifiedBy":"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf"},"_id":"1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf":3}}
{"name":"Powers","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Powers","type":"text","_id":"qYq5SAHHOp6D0XSd","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div class=\"chapter-heading\"><h1>Powers</h1><figure class=\"chapter-number\"><figcaption>Savage Eberron</figcaption></figure></div><p class=\"drop-cap\">Magic is everywhere in <em>Savage Eberron</em>. Whether it’s hidden occult lore practiced by dark cultists, the righteous rituals of clerics, or the potent spells of sorcerers and wizards, these rules handle it all in one simple system.</p><p>We call all of these effects “powers.” They work the same from game to game, but the particular use, modifiers, and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings} give the same core powers endless variations. Characters gain access to magical powers by taking one of many varieties of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}.</p><p>Each type of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds} has the following entries, listed in its description, and may have additional abilities or drawbacks as well.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Arcane Skill:</span> This is the skill you roll to activate your powers. Buy it just like any other skill.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Starting Powers:</span> This is the number of powers a hero starts with when she takes an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds}. Additional powers may be learned with the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.New Powers]{New Powers} </strong>Edge.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Power Points:</span> The number of Power Points the character starts with. A hero increases Power Points by taking the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} </strong>Edge.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Available Powers:</span> The list of powers characters with that @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds} may take.</li></ul><p> </p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h2>Multiple Arcane Backgrounds</h2><p>A character may take an arcane skill even without an Arcane Background, though there’s rarely much that can be done with it unless it’s something like a bard’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance}.</p><p>If a hero with an Arcane Background takes a new Arcane Background (perhaps a mage wants to take on a priestly role as well), she gets the Edge as usual (new powers, Power Points, etc.) but must keep each separate. She can’t cast healing with her magic Power Points, for example, and her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Spellbooks]{Spellbooks} Edge applies only to New Powers chosen for her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Wizard)]{Arcane Background (Wizard)} list.</p><p class=\"example\"><strong>Example:</strong> Boranal starts with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Artificer)]{Arcane Background (Artificer)} during character creation. He has 10 Power Points and two spells. Later he decides to become a summoner as well. He works out a good story for his training with the Dungeon Master and takes @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Summoner)]{Arcane Background (Summoner)} as an Advance. He gets 15 Power Points that are kept separate from his artificer Power Points and its starting spells and other abilities. He doesn’t have the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} skill yet so he casts at the usual default die (d4-2). He wisely uses his next few Advances to buy and increase that skill!</p></aside><h2>Detect Magic</h2><p>In the magically-charged world of Eberron, any character with an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds} can sense magical or divine auras within 5” (10 yards), unless they are magically concealed. This is an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Actions]{action}.</p><p>Detecting magic at a greater range or gaining specific information requires the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{detect arcana}</em> spell, which can also be used to reveal items or beings protected by <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{conceal arcana}.</em> </p><p>Identifying magic items requires a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} roll for everyday items like healing potions. More obscure items require an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana] roll. These rolls can be made once a day with a cumulative +1 bonus to the roll.</p><h2>Power Descriptions</h2><p><span class=\"fontstyle0\">This section describes new powers and updates to classic powers and Power Modifiers.</span></p><p><span class=\"fontstyle0\">Each power has the following statistics:</span></p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Rank: </span>The Rank a character must be to learn the power.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Power Points: </span>The cost to activate the power in Power Points.</li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">Range: </span>The maximum distance between the caster and the power’s effect. Range is often expressed as Smarts or some multiple thereof. If so, read Smarts as inches on the tabletop (twice that in yards). A Smarts of d10, for example, means the power can be cast up to 10″ (20 yards) away.</p><p>Unless the power says otherwise, Range has no effect after the power is activated. An ally who has been granted invisibility, for example, may then move beyond the caster’s Smarts with no ill effect.</p></li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">Duration: </span>How long the power lasts in rounds (unless otherwise noted).</p><p>Powers expire at the end of the character’s turn X rounds later, where X is the Duration listed. Count the round the power activated. If the cleric activates <span class=\"fontstyle3\">boost Trait </span><span class=\"fontstyle0\">(Duration 5) on the second round of combat, for example, it remains in place until the end of her turn on the sixth round.</span></p><p>Powers may be maintained for their base Duration for 1 Power Point per individual.</p><p>Unless it says otherwise, the caster can terminate a power she’s activated as a free action. She must terminate the entire power—she can’t leave it on for some and off for others.</p></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Trappings: </span>These are descriptive ideas and suggestions for how the power might look or manifest for different characters.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Modifiers: </span>The specific Power Modifiers a caster can use when activating the power.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Epic Powers: </span>Those with the “gold star” bullets are Epic Powers. These are unlocked with Arcane and Divine Mastery Class Edges.</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Trappings","type":"text","_id":"3kTI7BU3hwr0oXMl","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Trappings</h1><p>Trappings allow the core powers presented in this chapter to have many different appearances. They don't usually have a game effect of their own, but are important for atmosphere and theme.</p><p>One character might fire magical missiles of glowing white energy while another hurls deadly icicles. Both use the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> power and share the same mechanics, but they look and \"feel\" different.</p><p>Trappings <em>do</em> matter when an obstacle or opponent has a particular strength or weakness. If an ice troll suffers +4 damage from fire- or heat-based attacks, for example, a <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em> a player describes as a fireball counts as a fire attack and does +4 damage.</p><p>Once described, a power’s Trappings don’t change unless the caster uses an @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Advance}.</p><p>A character can alter the power’s effects or Trappings as she wishes using <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}</strong>.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Synergy]</h2><p>Sometimes logic dictates a power’s Trapping should have some additional effect. Zapping someone with a lightning bolt while they’re standing in water should cause additional damage, for example.</p><p>When this occurs, the DM can decide there’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Synergy]{synergy} that either increases or decreases the effect or damage (DM's call) by +2 or −2.</p><p>Oppositional forces, such as fire and ice or light and darkness, <em>don’t</em> have synergy against one another (though such effects are sometimes accounted for in some creatures’ Special Abilities. If a fire <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em> hits ice armor<em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{(protection)}</em>, for example, there’s no additional effect because they cancel each other out.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Adding and Changing Trappings]</h2><p>A character can learn two new powers when he takes the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.New Powers]{New Powers}</strong> Edge. He may instead add Trappings to his powers in place of one or two of the new powers. A hero who takes the New Powers Edge, for example, could choose one new power and add an ice Trapping to her <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>. The DM may also allow a player to <em>change</em> the Trapping of existing power when she gains an @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Advance}. This should reflect a major change in the character in some way as determined by the player and GM.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]</h2><div><img class=\"float-right\" style=\"shape-outside:url('modules/swpf-core-rules/assets/art/storm-woman.webp')\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/storm-woman.webp\" width=\"300\" height=\"424\" /></div><p>Sometimes a power’s Trapping imposes a limitation on the power. This gives the power focus at the expense of versatility. The @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]{Limitation} is permanent and always in effect unless changed with an Advance as noted below.</p><p>Each limitation placed upon the power reduces its total @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} cost by one (to a minimum of 1). If this would normally reduce the cost to 0, you gain a +1 bonus (+2 maximum) to the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} total instead.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Range:</span> The power’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} is reduced to Touch (if its usual Range is greater).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Personal:</span> The power’s Range becomes Self (if its usual Range is Touch or it has the range Limitation, above). This includes an item if the power is normally cast on an object (such as <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em>).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Aspect:</span> The character can only access one aspect of a power (that has more than one choice), such as <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sloth/Speed]{sloth/speed}</em> or <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower}</em> Trait.</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Activation","type":"text","_id":"A2PVNmKPHzjXvQxF","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Activation</h1><p>A character activates a power by picking a target within @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} and making an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll. Failure means the power doesn’t activate. The caster spends one @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point} regardless of any Edges such as @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Channeling]{Channeling}, unless the ability specifically says it reduces the minimum cost to 0.</p><p>Success means the power activates and consumes all the Power Points allocated to it, even if it misses the target (such as with <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>), or the defender resists. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} has additional effects noted in the particular power description.</p><p><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Backlash]:</strong> A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} when activating a power is called @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Backlash]{Backlash}. It causes a level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} and all currently active powers instantly terminate.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Casting Requirements]</h2><p>A character must be able to see his target and cannot be <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound}</strong> or silenced.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Maintaining Powers]</h2><p>When a power ends, the caster can spend one @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point} to extend it by its base @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Duration]{Duration}. If a power’s Duration is five rounds, for example, it can be maintained for another five rounds for 1 Power Point.</p><p>Maintenance is per target but ignores other @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}, so renewing<em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost Trait}</em> on three allies costs 3 Power Points and extends the effect of each another five rounds.</p><p>Unless a power says otherwise, the caster can terminate it as a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Stacking Powers]</h2><p>Powers don't stack beyond their maximum benefit or drawback. This includes effects from magic items that specifically use those powers. A ring that simply says it increases @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} a die type does so even if the wearer's Strength is currently increased by <em>boost Trait</em>(Strength), for example. If the same ring said it boosts @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} a die type, however, it would only stack with the actual spell or other items up to the power's maximum (two die types).</p><p>Powers that target different Traits or abilities, such as <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Boost/Lower Trait]{boost/lower Trait}</em>, are considered separate powers in this context. @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} may only be increased up to two die types by <em>boost Trait</em>, for example, but @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} and Fighting could both be boosted up to two die types as each one is a separate Trait. Similarly, a sorcerer could cast <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}</em> (melee) on an ally who's already benefiting from a ring of <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Ring of Protection, Minor]{protection}</em> (ranged).</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Recharging]</h2><p>A character recovers 5 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} per hour spent resting.</p><p>What constitutes rest is up to the GM, but generally, it means sitting, eating, tending wounds, sleeping, and avoiding any strenuous activity. Walking or riding a horse isn’t usually restful, but riding in a cushioned carriage might be.</p><p>A few interruptions don’t stop a character from resting— standing watch, planning, sharpening weapons, and so on (DM's call).</p><p>An arcane hero can also spend a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny} to regain five Power Points. This is a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Powers as Multi-Actions]</h2><p>Each power activated is its own action, and the same or dif­ferent powers may be cast multiple times as a <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action}</strong>. A wizard might start combat by invoking <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Protection]{protection}</em> and <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Deflection]{deflection}</em>, for example, or a priest might attempt to <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{banish}</em> a spirit while invoking <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em> on his mace.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shorting]</h2><p>A character may cast a power with <em>fewer</em> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} than required (whether she has them or not) by increasing the difficulty of her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll (If there is no skill roll, as with Mystic Powers, the character cannot short the power).</p><p>For every Power Point a character shorts, she suffers a −1 penalty to the roll. Casting a 3-point <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> with 0 Power Points, for example, inflicts a −3 penalty.</p><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shorting]{Shorting} is risky. If a character fails a shorted @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll, it’s consid­ered a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure!}</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Power Modifiers","type":"text","_id":"pATWFIk7k4yGqPfg","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Power Modifiers</h1><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers} allow characters to customize their abilities, adding a special effect that better reflects their power’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trapping}.</p><p>Power Modifiers are selected when a power is activated and may be freely changed each time. An icy <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> might cause @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor Piercing]{Armor Piercing} damage in one attack and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Lingering Damage]{Lingering Damage} in the next.</p><p>The common modifiers listed on this page can be used with any power a character is using (unless otherwise prevented from modifying the power). Some powers also list additional specific Power Modifiers that can be used with that power.</p><p>Casters must declare which modifiers they’re using before rolling their @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill}. The number in parentheses is the price in additional @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} it costs to add the effect. A Power Modifier may only be applied once per casting.</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> Power Modifiers last for the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Duration]{Duration} of the spell, or until the end of the target’s next turn in the case of Instant powers.</p><p><strong>Epic Powers:</strong> Some Power Modifiers are marked with a gold star. These are Epic Powers. requiring the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Mastery]{Arcane} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Divine Mastery]{Divine Mastery} Edges.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor Piercing] (+1 to +3)</h2><p>The attack is focused to defeat armor or seeks out a foe’s exposed areas. Each Power Point spent grants the power @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{AP} 2 to a max­imum of AP 6.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue modifier]{Fatigue} (+2)</h2><p>Powers that drain or tax an opponent can cause @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. The modifier may be attached to any power that can cause damage or is resisted by the target. If she’s affected by the power in any way, she also suffers Fatigue. This cannot cause @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitation}, however.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glow or Shroud] (+1)</h2><p>Glow creates soft light (caster’s choice of color) in a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{Small Blast Template} centered on the target. It subtracts 2 from her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} totals and negates 1 point of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination} penalties for those attacking the glowing character.</p><p>Shroud dims and slightly obscures the target so that attacks against her suffer a −1 penalty and she adds +1 to her Stealth rolls.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heavy Weapon] (+2)</h2><p>The caster creates a focused blast. The attack counts as a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heavy Weapon]{Heavy Weapon}.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hinder or Hurry] (+1)</h2><p>The target is slowed in some way, perhaps due to intense cold, a slippery surface, or even binding matter or energy. His base Pace is reduced by 2.</p><p>A caster can @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hinder or Hurry]{Hurry} the recipient instead, granting increased energy, sure footing, or more powerful muscles. His Pace is increased by 2.</p><p>Effects of either modifier aren’t cumulative.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Lingering Damage] (+2)</h2><p>The target is hit by fire, cold, acid, gnawing insects, or some other @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trapping} that continues to cause damage after the initial attack. On the victim’s next turn, he suffers the power’s base damage minus one die type (for one additional turn only). If hit with a 2d6 <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em>, for example, the victim takes 2d4 damage at the start of his next turn. If the base damage is already a d4 die type, it is d4–2 instead.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range modifier]{Range} (+1/+2)</h2><p>Double the power’s listed @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range} for 1 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point}, or triple it for +2. This modifier may not be used on powers with a Range of Touch or the Cone or Stream Template.</p><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Selective] (+1)</h2><p>With intense focus, the caster can choose not to affect any or all individual targets within a power’s area of effect (picking all enemies instead of allies in a <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{blast}</em>, for example).</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Cantrips","type":"text","_id":"4iGMamQHJCAbasP5","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Cantrips</h1><p>A mage sets a broom to sweeping his floor. A priest lights a candle with the grace of her god. A bard tells an animated story in the night air, illuminated with the dancing cinders of a campfire. Such minor orisons (prayers) or lesser magicks are collectively called \"cantrips.\"</p><p>In <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>, any character with an Arcane Background (see both Arcane Background and Class Edges @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{here}) can cast cantrips.</p><h2>Activation</h2><p>A character may cast a cantrip by making an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll. This is an action, and the effect must be based on one of the character’s existing powers. A sorcerer could use <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> with a fire @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trapping} to light a campfire, for example. A druid could use <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> to make vines dance to entertain a group of children. A wizard can use <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Sound/Silence]{sound}</em> to ring a bell calling a servant to his study.</p><p>Success means the desired effect occurs. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} has an additional narrative impact of some kind— the candle glows brightly, the vines dance in perfect synchronicity, or the bell rings loud and pure.</p><p>Failure causes the spell to fail without effect. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} causes the spell to backfire, which requires the caster to lose 1 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} (or suffer @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} if the caster has no Power Points). Critical Failure also causes an embarrassment or minor mishap of some sort— an animated broom carelessly knocks a jar of ink onto the floor, a conjured flame lights a book on fire, or the power makes an embarrassing sound or smell.</p><p>A successfully cast cantrip’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Duration]{Duration} is the same as the power it’s based on and may be maintained by spending Power Points as usual.</p><p>The DM has the final say on what a cantrip can do, but the effect must not replace a power or cause damage (at least directly). It can be used to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}, or grant a +1 bonus on a subsequent roll in the same encounter. For example, if the bard uses a cantrip to impress the children of Sandpoint, the DM might give him +1 to a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll later on if he talks to their parents or someone else who witnessed the kindness.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/halfwizard.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"Arcane Devices","type":"text","_id":"3oTOiNIuI8zxS7Ms","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Arcane Devices</h1><p>A character with the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer} Edge can focus powers into devices for herself or others. The advantage is that they can be given to and used by allies. The trade-off is that devices take a little preparation to create and can be lost or destroyed.</p><p>In <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>, arcane devices are usually sacred, enchanted, or otherwise magically powered objects in line with the creator’s Arcane Background. For example, a cleric with Artificer may create a silver talisman with the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Relief]{relief}</em> power, while a druid may make a wooden amulet with the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{beast friend}</em> power.</p><p><strong>Note:</strong> Arcane devices are relatively temporary items crafters can create with their powers and the Artificer Edge. More permanent magic items are created differently, with additional requirements for ample undisturbed time and resources. See Magic Items entries for more details.</p><h2>Creation</h2><p>Creating a device takes one hour per power that can be activated through it. The player must list which powers are in the device and then allocate @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} to it. The device can only use the powers and Power Points allocated to it.</p><p>Power Points invested in an arcane device are lost to the inventor until they’re used or recovered with <strong>Tinkering</strong>.</p><p><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}:</strong> A user may spend a device’s Power Points as desired, including enabling any applicable @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Power Modifiers]{Power Modifiers}.</p><p>Arcane devices may not be <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shorting]{Shorted}</strong>.</p><p><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]:</strong> Arcane devices may benefit from <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]{Limitations}</strong>.</p><p><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Activation]{Activation}:</strong> The creator uses his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} as usual. Others use whatever skill is associated with the device’s form— bows use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, knives use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing), and so on. If there is no other obvious skill, such as for a potion or worn item, the character rolls the inventor’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} as if it were his own (he does <em>not</em> benefit from any of the creator’s @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edges} or other abilities, however).</p><p>Failure to activate the device costs one of the device's @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Point}, and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} causes the user @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p><p><strong>Tinkering:</strong> A creator can reassign up to five @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} per action between an arcane device and her own pool. She must be in physical contact with the item to do so. Characters should lend out their devices very carefully!</p><h2 class=\"example\">Arcane Device Examples</h2><p>A powerful vizier makes an <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Invisibility]{invisibility}</em> cloak and gives it to one of his spies. He has 20 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} and puts 5 of them into the cloak, reducing his remaining pool to 15.</p><p>When the spy wants to turn <em>invisible</em>, she rolls the vizier’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting} skill. This costs 1 less Power Point than usual because of the cloak’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Limitations]{Limitation}— it must be worn to activate so it has a Range of Touch.</p><p>The vizier also gives the spy the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Bolt]{bolt}</em> power in the form of a wand and invests it with 10 Power Points. The spy rolls @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} to activate the wand.</p><p>The spy suffers @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} if she rolls a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} activating either device.</p><p>Once the cloak or wand is out of energy, the vizier can recover the Power Points he invested in it normally.</p><p>Meanwhile, Ezren the wizard makes an “oil of sharpness” for Valeros the fighter. When rubbed on a sword it activates the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Smite]{smite}</em> power. Ezren invests four Power Points into it. The pair soon find themselves in battle with the undead. Valeros rubs the oil on the blade and rolls Ezren's Spellcasting. The roll fails, which drains the oil of one Power Point. Next turn, Valeros tries again, getting a raise and granting the sword +4 damage. <em>Smite</em> normally costs 2 Power Points but Ezren's Trapping has the Range Limitation so it only costs 1 point for each application. See <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trappings}</strong>.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/npc-codex.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Prepared Magic","type":"text","_id":"Mi0rLqkMSuwmLea2","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Prepared Magic</h1><p>Given time and the willingness to permanently expend valuable components, spellcasters, priests, and other arcanists may prepare powers for later use or to preserve their valuable energies for battle.</p><p>The benefits of preparing powers are twofold: the character doesn't expend Power Points in the casting and may enhance a power to give it greater Duration.</p><p>Follow the steps below when a character wants to prepare a power:</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Select Power:</span> The caster chooses any of his powers (or has access to via abilities such as the wizard's Eldritch Inspiration) and adds up its total Power Points, including modifiers, existing Limitations, and enhancements from the table below. Prepared magic doesn't actually cost Power Points, but the total is used to determine the cost in components (see below).</li></ul><table><thead><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Prepared Spell Enhancements</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Cost</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"centered\">3</td><td>Increase the Duration of a power expressed in rounds to minutes</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">5</td><td>Increase the Duration of a power expressed in rounds to hours</td></tr></tbody></table><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Components:</span> Once the preparation is complete, the mage must gather components worth at least 100 gold pieces times the spell's total cost in Power Points. The GM decides what components are required—usually Dragonshards or treasure to simulate the costs of rare ingredients the mage keeps on his person, but the GM could also require specific components such as precious stones, meteorite shards, magic items, or even holy relics.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Preparation:</span> Once the components are gathered the casting begins. The mage must spend ten minutes per Rank of the spell to create an “anchor.” A Novice Rank spell takes 10 minutes to prepare, while a Veteran Rank power requires a half-hour.</li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">CAST:</span> Once the anchor is made, the power is retained in the mage's mind and he may attempt to cast it at any time thereafter by spending a Benny. The spellcaster may not attempt to activate his prepared power without the anchor. Activating the power works as normal, with the following exceptions: if the caster fails the arcane roll to activate, he may try again (but must spend another Benny). On a Critical Failure, in addition to the regular effects, the spell and anchor are lost. With success or better, the anchor is consumed. The caster may maintain the power but will not recharge Power Points as usual (see Recharging).</p><p>A spellcaster may only retain a single power at a time. The caster may dismiss a prepared spell as a free action, though he may reuse the anchor to prepare the exact same spell (including Power Modifiers) in the future.</p></li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"Ritual Magic","type":"text","_id":"Yr6DUgmqCpySejMY","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Ritual Magic</h1><p>More elaborate rituals allow heroes to cast powers they don't normally have access to and give them even greater enhancements.</p><p>Ritual magic follows the same process as prepared powers with a few exceptions:</p><ul><li>Ritual magic offers some additional enhancements as well:</li></ul><table><thead><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">RITUAL SPELL ENHANCEMENTS</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">COST</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">EFFECT</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"centered\">3</td><td>Increase the Duration of a power expressed in rounds to minutes</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">5</td><td>Increase the Duration of a power expressed in rounds to hours</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">3</td><td>If a power has an Area of Effect, it may be increased to a radius of 50 yards. The enhancement may also conform to a building, ship, or other irregular space of roughly the same size (DM's call).</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">5</td><td>If a power has an Area of Effect, it may be increased to a radius of 100 yards. The enhancement may also conform to a building, ship, or other irregular space of roughly the same size (DM's call).</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">5</td><td>Targets of the power resist its effects at an additional –2 modifier, in addition to any Power Modifiers such as Strong.</td></tr></tbody></table><ul><li>If the caster knows the power, the cost to cast is 100 gold pieces times the spell's total Power Points (including modifiers, existing Limitations, and enhancements from the table above). If he doesn't know the power, the cost is 150 gold pieces per Power Point (including modifiers, existing Limitations, and enhancements from the table above) in addition to any costs required to get the scroll or tome. Scrolls used as part of a ritual are consumed in the process.</li><li>The spell is activated with the Arcana skill via a single-person, Difficult Dramatic Task. The penalty to cast is –1 for Seasoned powers, –2 for Veteran, –3 for Heroic, and –4 for Legendary. Each round of the Dramatic Tasks takes 10 minutes per rank of the spell, ie. 10 minutes for Novice, 20 for Seasoned, etc.</li><li>A caster may use his arcane skill if the power is normally available to his Arcane Background (whether he has it or not).</li><li>The power is cast immediately with the successful completion of the Dramatic Task. Use the final roll of the task as the casting total. Spellcasters may not spend Power Points to maintain the power. If the Dramatic Task fails, the ritual fails and the components are consumed. That caster can't attempt that ritual again for one week (but others may).</li></ul><p></p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h2>Using Rituals</h2><p>Ritual magic allows characters to cast spells they may not have to solve problems their group can't otherwise resolve. For example, a party confronted by evil spirits might not have detect arcana to see invisible spirits or banish to then expel them from the town they've been hired to protect. This encourages creativity and allows any character to access arcane powers on occasion (though at significant cost).</p><p>If a setting is relatively low-magic, it also makes even the most basic spells feel special and magical, such as boosting the party's Vigor for a day while they cross the Great Desert.</p><p>Remember that the party must have the spell or find the “ritual” to cast it, so if the DM doesn't want them to have access to something unknown she doesn't have to let them find it!</p><p>Finally, note that the mystic intervention power must be cast via ritual magic. This is the spell to use to close gates to hostile dimensions, stop a mad god's tidal wave, or other epic goals. Of course the villains will attempt to intervene, forcing some of the heroes to fend them off while the others concentrate on the ritual!</p></aside></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":900000,"name":"Battle Magic","type":"text","_id":"6DUsB549vjVkD7id","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Battle Magic</h1><p>Battle priests and mages are often tasked with granting powers to warbands or select units of the army. Only those who have the Battle Magic Edge may use the rules presented below.</p><p>Casting a spell via Battle Magic costs +5 Power Points. Only powers with the Additional Recipients modifier are eligible, though that modifier is not used when casting via Battle Magic. (It may be cheaper to use Additional Recipients with a small number of allies—that calculation is left to the caster!)</p><p>Spells may only be cast on characters with identical profiles, i.e. a unit of archers, a troop of cavalry, etc.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Resistance:</span> Make a group roll for the defenders if the power is resisted.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Range:</span> The Range of all Battle Magic is 100 yards.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Maintenance:</span> Powers may be maintained normally, meaning that once cast, a caster may maintain boost Trait (Shooting) on a unit of archers another five rounds for a single Power Point.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Battle Magic Penalty:</span> The arcane skill roll suffers a penalty based on the number of troops affected, as shown on the table below.</li></ul><table style=\"width:50%;margin:auto\"><thead><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Battle Magic Modifiers</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Number Affected</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Penalty</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"centered\">2-50</td><td class=\"centered\">–2</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">51-250</td><td class=\"centered\">–4</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">251-500</td><td class=\"centered\">–6</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><h2 class=\"example\">Example Battle Magic</h2><p>Example: A wizard casts puppet on an enemy formation of 400 orc warriors at the height of a climactic battle. The wizard's total, after the –6 penalty, is an 8. The orcs resist with a group roll and get a 6. The wizard is successful and decides to make the orcs stand idly for five rounds (if he tries to make them attack their fellows they get another roll to resist, as described in the puppet power).</p><p>Later, the same wizard decides to grant protection to an embattled troop of 50 cavalrymen. That's a –2 penalty to his Spellcasting, so he needs to roll a 6 for a basic success and a 10 for a raise.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1000000,"name":"Power Summaries","type":"text","_id":"PHuePQh04cVeLgu1","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Power Summaries</h1><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"6\">Powers Summaries</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Power</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Rank</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Power Points</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Range</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Dur</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\" style=\"width:40%\">Description</th></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Accelerate Healing]{Accelerate Healing}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">V</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">T</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">24H</td><td>Target makes @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Healing]{natural healing} every 24 hours, with +2 on a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Animate War Tree]{Animate War Tree}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">H</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">T</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10m</td><td>Awakens a tree as a war tree. It is a wild card on a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Mark]{Arcane Mark}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">N</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">T</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Perm</td><td>Leave a magical arcane mark.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Arcane Protection]{Arcane Protection}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">N</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Sm</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td><td>Enemy casters subtract 2 (4 with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}) when targeting this character; reduces @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage]{damage} a like amount.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Baleful Polymorph]{Baleful Polymorph}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">V</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3+</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Sm</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td><td>Creature from Size–2 to Size 3 is transformed into a relatively harmless creature.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Banish]{Banish}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">V</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Sm</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">I</td><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Opposed Roll} vs @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Spirit} to <em>banish</em> entities.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Barrier]{Barrier}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">S</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Sm</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td><td>Creates 5\" (10 yards) long, 1\" (2 yards) tall, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Hardness} 10 barrier.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Battle Song]{Battle Song}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">S</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">MBT</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td><td>Grants @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Berserk]{Berserk} to creatures within @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{Medium Blast Template}.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Beast Friend]{Beast Friend}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">N</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">S</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Sm</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10m</td><td>Controls animals.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">S</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Sm x2</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">I</td><td>2d6 @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage]{Damage} in a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{Medium Blast Template}</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blessing]</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">S</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">S</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 y</td><td>Improves community's health and crops.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blind]{Blind}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">N</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td><td style