ore-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Trapmaking Kit]{Trapmaking Kit}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">150 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Without kit, –2 penalty to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair} rolls to create a trap.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Wand]{Wand}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">20 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Warforged Repair Kit]{Warforged Repair Kit}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">30 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Five uses.</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"8\">Alchemical Items</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"8\"><p>The following items may be found in most towns with an alchemist's shop.</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Type</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Range</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Damage</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">AP</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">RoF</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Blast</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Weight</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Cost</th></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Alchemist's Acid]{Alchemist's Acid}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2d4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{SBT}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">40 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>Thrown like a grenade. Those within the template take 2d4 damage when hit and 2d4–2 damage at the start of their next turn unless the acid is washed off somehow.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Alchemist's Fire]{Alchemist's Fire}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2d4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{SBT}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>A sticky, flammable liquid that ignites on impact. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Heavy Weapon (HW)]{Heavy Weapon}. Those within the template take 2d4 damage when hit and 2d4–2 damage at the start of their next turn unless dowsed with water. Target might catch @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fire]{Fire}.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Antitoxin]{Antitoxin, vial}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">.5</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">75 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>Grants a +4 bonus to resist @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Poison]{poison} for one hour.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Candlerod]{Candlerod}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">.5</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>A small iron tipped wand with small chamber that has a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dragonshards]{Eberron Dragonshards residum} and an alchemical compound. When struck the compounds combine and glow like a candle in a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{Small Blast Template} and dimly illuminates a small area and lasts for two hours.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Holy Water (flask)]{Holy Water}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2d4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{SBT}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>Holy water can be thrown in a flask or splashed on an adjacent creature. Undead and certain evil creatures (DM's call) within the template take 2d4 damage when hit and 2d4–2 damage at the start of their next turn.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Smokestick]{Smokestick}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{MBT}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">.25</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>An alchemically treated stick that creates thick smoke (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dark illumination}) in a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{Medium Blast Template} for one minute. Dissipates in strong wind in one round.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Smokestick, Noxious]{Smokestick, Noxious}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{MBT}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">.5</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">125 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>An alchemically treated stick that creates thick smoke (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{Dark illumination}) in a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{Medium Blast Template} for one minute. Dissipates in strong wind in one round. Those in the cloud must roll a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} check or become @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted} from retching and coughing.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Sunrod]{Sunrod}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>A gold and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dragonshards]{Eberron dragonshard residum} tipped iron rod that provides normal light in a 30 foot radius for threee hours. It increases @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Illumination]{illumination} one level for another 30' beyond that. It emits no heat, and counts as sunlight.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Tanglefoot bag]{Tanglefoot bag}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1/2/4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>A Size 3 or smaller victim hit by this small sack of sticky materials is @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Distracted and Vulnerable]{Distracted} for five rounds and must make an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll or be stuck to the ground (@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Entangled}) as well.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Thunderstone]{Thunderstone}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{MBT}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">30 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>An alchemical rock with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.Dragonshards]{Eberron dragonshard residum} that explodes with a deafening boom when struck against a hard surface. Anyone a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Blast Templates]{Medium Blast Template} must make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} roll or be @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Shaken} as well as deafened for one hour.</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Tindertwig]{Tindertwig}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3/6/12</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td></tr><tr><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"8\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>A thin stick that alights with flame when struck against a hard surface. It allows torches and other flammable substances to be lit in a single action.</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"5\">Poisons</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"5\"><p><em>Contact poisons</em> must touch bare skin. They can also be applied to a weapon and remain effective for four hours.</p><p><em>Inhaled poisons </em>are released by breaking their container. They form a Medium Blast Template cloud and affect everyone within.</p><p><em>Ingested poisons</em> must be consumed. The target may make a Notice roll to detect the poison’s smell or taste before consuming.</p><p><em>Injury poisons</em> must be applied to a piercing or cutting weapon, and are delivered when an attack isn’t Soaked and results in Shaken.</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Item</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Type</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Delivery</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Cost</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Notes</th></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Assassin's Blood]{Assassin's Blood}</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Lethal</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Ingested</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">250 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">–2 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to detect</td></tr><tr><td>Carrion Crawler Mucus</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Paralyzing</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Contact</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">+1 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to detect.</td></tr><tr><td>Cyrpt Spores</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Mild</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Inhaled</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">75 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>Essence of Ether</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Knockout</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Inhaled</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">300 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>Faerie Wine</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Disabling (Smarts)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Ingested</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>Gaint Snake Venom</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Lethal</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Injury</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>Goblin Poison</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Disabling (Agility)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Injury</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">150 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Goblin's have immunity</td></tr><tr><td>Lotus Dust</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Disabling (Strength)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Inhaled</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">225 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Vigor –2 or gain a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Habit]{Habit (minor)} to the dust</td></tr><tr><td>Medusa's Blood</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Disabling (Vigor)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Contact</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">300 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>Moon Drought</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Disabling (Spirit)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Ingested</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">75 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>Oil of Taggit</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Knockout</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Contact</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">400 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr><tr><td>Wyvern Poison</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Paralyzing</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Injury</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">400 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">—</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Trade Goods Table</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><p>Most wealth is not in coins. It is measured in livestock, grain, land, rights to collect taxes, or rights to resources, such as a forest or mine.</p><p>Dragonmarked houses, guilds, nobles, and royalty regulate trade. Chartered companies are granted rights to conduct trade along certain routes, to send merchant ships to various ports, or to buy and sell specific goods. Guilds set prices for the goods and services that they control, and determine who may or may not offer those goods and  services. Merchants commonly exchange trade goods without using currency. The Trade Goods Table shows the value of commonly exchanged goods.</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Goods</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Cost per Day</th></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of wheat</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 cp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of flour or one chicken</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2 cp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of sugar</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 cp</td></tr><tr><td>1  lb. of iron or 1 sq. yd. of canvas</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 sp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of copper</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 sp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of ginger or pipeweed, or 1 sq. yd. of cotton cloth or one goat</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of cinnamon or pepper, or one sheep</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of cloves or one pig</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 sq. yd. of linen cloth</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">4 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of marble or salt or silver, or 1 sq. yd. of linen</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 sq. yd. of wool</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">6 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 sq. yd. of silk or one cow</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of saffron or one ox</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">15 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of gold</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of adamantine</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">300 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of platinum</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">500 gp</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Goods & Services","type":"text","_id":"rMy3kXPk9ZhlOmI4","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Goods &amp; Services</h1><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Trade Goods Table</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><p>Most wealth is not in coins. It is measured in livestock, grain, land, rights to collect taxes, or rights to resources, such as a forest or mine.</p><p>Dragonmarked houses, guilds, nobles, and royalty regulate trade. Chartered companies are granted rights to conduct trade along certain routes, to send merchant ships to various ports, or to buy and sell specific goods. Guilds set prices for the goods and services that they control, and determine who may or may not offer those goods and  services. Merchants commonly exchange trade goods without using currency. The Trade Goods Table shows the value of commonly exchanged goods.</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Goods</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Cost per Day</th></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of wheat</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 cp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of flour or one chicken</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2 cp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of sugar</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 cp</td></tr><tr><td>1  lb. of iron or 1 sq. yd. of canvas</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 sp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of copper</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 sp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of ginger or pipeweed, or 1 sq. yd. of cotton cloth or one goat</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of cinnamon or pepper, or one sheep</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of cloves or one pig</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 sq. yd. of linen cloth</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">4 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of marble or salt or silver, or 1 sq. yd. of linen</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 sq. yd. of wool</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">6 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 sq. yd. of silk or one cow</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of saffron or one ox</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">15 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of gold</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of adamantine</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">300 gp</td></tr><tr><td>1 lb. of platinum</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">500 gp</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Dragonmarked Services</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Service</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Cost</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Communication Services</span></th></tr><tr><td>Arcane mark (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.15XRGTUvsHywu4tK]{House Sivis})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td></tr><tr><td>Courier service (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 sp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Illusionary script (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.15XRGTUvsHywu4tK]{House Sivis})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">15 gp</td></tr><tr><td>Mail service (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 cp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Message station (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.15XRGTUvsHywu4tK]{House Sivis})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2 sp per word</td></tr><tr><td>Translation (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.15XRGTUvsHywu4tK]{House Sivis})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2 cp per  word</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Healing Services</span></th></tr><tr><td>Minor care per visit (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.nhdkovFgM8ztuUn7]{House Jorasco})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3 sp</td></tr><tr><td>Long term care (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.nhdkovFgM8ztuUn7]{House Jorasco})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp per day</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Hospitality Services</span></th></tr><tr><td>Magnificent mansion (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.ptaooxMqYxX8x8eR]{House Ghallanda})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">60 gp per person</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Security Services</span></th></tr><tr><td>Arcane lock (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.6LcyVZsMoLyWNZo1]{House Kundarak})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">30 gp</td></tr><tr><td>Ward (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.6LcyVZsMoLyWNZo1]{House Kundarak})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">350 gp</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Travel Services</span></th></tr><tr><td>Coach/caravan (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 sp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Elemental galleon (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.yIeuap0BYzJjkH5K]{House Lyrandar})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 sp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Magebred coach (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3 sp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Lightning rail: Steerage (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2 cp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Lighting rail: Standard (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3 sp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Lighting rail: Friends Class (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 sp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Lighting rail: Executive Class (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1 gp per mile</td></tr><tr><td>Teleportation network (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.uqKoJIprPifcmrBr]{House Orien})</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2,000 gp</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"4\">Magewright Services</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"4\"><h3>Cosmetic Transmutation (Beautician)</h3><p>One form of fashion that hasn’t been discussed in depth is the practice of cosmetic transmutation. A magewright beautician can perform a range of minor transformations—for a price.</p><p>Minor cosmetic transmutation is quite common; most professional beauticians can change your hair or eye color. Unnatural effects are rarer, seen mainly in Aundair and Zilargo; metallic hair colors are a recent fad in Fairhaven, and in the days before Galifar, the nobles of Thaliost would adopt elf features. The effects of cosmetic transmutation typically last a week, but if you’re dealing with a magewright of sufficient skill, you can extend the effect to one month. In some cities, you might even find an expert who can make the change permanent. The more complicated the transmutation, the more costly—and hard to find—the service becomes.</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Service</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">1 Week</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">1 Month</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Permanent</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"4\"><span class=\"no-class\">Cosmetic Transmutation</span></th></tr><tr><td>Minor (natural)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">20 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"4\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>Simple transmutation can temporarily change the color of your hair, skin, or eyes within the standard parameters for your species.</td></tr><tr><td>Minor (unnatural)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">20 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"4\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>If you’re seeking unnatural effects—cat’s eyes or moving tattoos—you’ll need a highly skilled beautician.</td></tr><tr><td>Moderate</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">20 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"4\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>Significant physical transformation allows you to alter your weight, height, or sex. These substantial transmutations require an expert in their trade.</td></tr><tr><td>Major</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">20 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td></tr><tr class=\"table-body-notes\"><td colspan=\"4\"><em><strong>Notes: </strong></em>Specialized or exotic physical transformation can match the appearance of a specific individual or change your apparent species. While this alters your appearance, you don’t gain the racial traits associated with your selected form. Those seeking to imitate another’s appearance must be wary. Duplicating the appearance of another person is a crime under the Code of Galifar—malicious theft of identity—and even those who can perform the magic won’t do so without good reason.</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ltavh0xcxs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules","color":"#008000"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"swade","systemVersion":"2.2.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1674774198222,"modifiedTime":1675702845415,"lastModifiedBy":"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf"},"_id":"QKA6dagfLDYyCUh6","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf":3}}
{"name":"The Adventure Tool Kit","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"The Adventure Toolkit","type":"text","_id":"kXm5BVR099MZQPW1","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div class=\"chapter-heading\"><h1>The Adventure<br />Tool kit</h1><figure class=\"chapter-number\"><figcaption>Savage Eberron</figcaption></figure></div><p>The following chapter contains tools the Dungeon Master can use for all the special situations that often come up in a game, such as:</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Allies]{ALLIES}:</span> Managing Extras under the player character’s control.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chases and Vehicles]{CHASES &amp; VEHICLES}:</span> Dynamic and thrilling chases on foot, in cars, or on motorcycles, or dogfights between massive fleets of starships!</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{DOWNTIME}:</span> Activities a character might engage in during time between adventures.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{DRAMATIC TASKS}:</span> Add tension and drama to situations like defusing a bomb or hacking a computer.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fear]{FEAR}:</span> The effects of overwhelming terror.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{HAZARDS}:</span> The effects of scorching heat, bitter cold, radiation, and more.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Interludes]{INTERLUDES}:</span>  Narrative storytelling for long trips or to reveal bits about the player characters’ backstories.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mass Battles]{MASS BATTLES}:</span> Desperate last stands against incredible odds between armies.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Nautical Campaigns]{NAUTICAL CAMPAIGNS}:</span> Rules for dealing with nautical campaigns. Combat, contact, fire, crews, and more.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{NETWORKING}:</span> Gathering information or asking for favors.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Quick Encounters]{QUICK ENCOUNTERS}:</span> A fast and easy way to resolve fights, heists, or capers when pressed for time.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Setting Rules]{SETTING RULES}:</span> A host of special rules you can use to customize your setting!</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shadowing]{SHADOWING}:</span> Rules for how to tail a target without getting discovered.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Social Conflict]{SOCIAL CONFLICT}:</span> Run a court trial, plead for aid, or convince a crowd.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Travel]{TRAVEL}:</span> Figure out how long it takes for the party to cross Khorvaire!</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wealth]{WEALTH}:</span> An optional system for those who don’t want to worry about tracking income and expenses.</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Allies","type":"text","_id":"rucoyVKkcJqx46DO","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Allies</h1><p>Allies play a big part in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> games. They serve as troops under your hero’s command in war, loyal retainers serving strongholds, or fellow fighters in glorious rebellions against oppression.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use these rules to help keep track of the party’s followers and give them a little extra personality to play off of as well.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Players create, control, and track their own followers and nonplayer character allies.</p><h2>Using Allies</h2><p>Keeping up with allies in <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> is simple. Just download the Ally Sheet from our website and fill in the blanks.</p><p>Allied @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} are divided up among all the players to control. This is a very important part of <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> because our adventures often feature allied bands of skilled hirelings, fellow grunts, or loyal retainers, and the game is designed to handle them quickly and easily. It’s also designed for the players to control them — not the Dungeon Master.</p><p>It doesn’t matter whether the <em>characters</em> control the allies, only that the <em>players</em> do. This keeps everyone involved in the action even if his hero is out of the fight, and makes running large combats much easier and more fun for everyone. Of course the DM can always take charge of Extras when the need arises, but with good roleplayers this is rarely necessary.</p><h3>Allied Personalities</h3><p>You can add a little flavor to your allies by rolling on the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-tables.Allied Personalities]{Allied Personalities}</strong> table. Jot down the keyword on the Ally Sheet so you and your Dungeon Master have a little insight into each particular ally’s character.</p><p>Consider these general impressions with no particular game effect. They help both the player and DM decide just how an ally might react in a given situation.</p><p>If a party of adventurers tasks a retainer with keeping watch, it's helpful to know which ones are Observant and which ones are Lazy!</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"4\">Allied Personalties</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">d20</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Personality</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">d20</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Personality</th></tr><tr><td>1</td><td class=\"centered\">Treacherous</td><td class=\"centered\">11</td><td class=\"centered\">Crude</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td class=\"centered\">Cruel</td><td class=\"centered\">12</td><td class=\"centered\">Agile</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td class=\"centered\">Old</td><td class=\"centered\">13</td><td class=\"centered\">Observant</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td class=\"centered\">Happy</td><td class=\"centered\">14</td><td class=\"centered\">Clueless</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td class=\"centered\">Experience</td><td class=\"centered\">15</td><td class=\"centered\">Mysterious</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td class=\"centered\">Gung-Ho</td><td class=\"centered\">16</td><td class=\"centered\">Creative</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td class=\"centered\">Lazy</td><td class=\"centered\">17</td><td class=\"centered\">Artistic</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td class=\"centered\">Sneaky</td><td class=\"centered\">18</td><td class=\"centered\">Fearless</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td class=\"centered\">Bright</td><td class=\"centered\">19</td><td class=\"centered\">Cowardly</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td class=\"centered\">Young</td><td class=\"centered\">20</td><td class=\"centered\">Heroic</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Allies &amp; Advancement</h3><p>Allies can improve their abilities as well. See <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Advancement}</strong>.</p><h3>Ammo</h3><p>Keeping track of ammunition for all your allies can be difficult. Here’s an easy and dramatic way to handle this problem.</p><p>The ammo level of each group of allied @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} starts at Very High, High (the usual level), Low, or Out, as determined by the GM.</p><p>After each fight, the ammo automatically drops a level. This makes for dramatic situations and realistic logistical problems while eliminating the bookkeeping.</p><p>The DM can always decide otherwise, of course. Perhaps the troops are told to fight with hand weapons instead of their bows and crossbows, or they don’t get to fire off more than a couple of shots before the fight is over.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/p144_figure_collage.webp\" /></div><h2>Typical Allies</h2><p>Here are a few typical archetypes you might use for your <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> game. Fill in any additional @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{skills} or @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edges} as you see fit. A group of rangers, for example, should have the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival} skill, while cavalrymen should have @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding}. Add appropriate @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.QKA6dagfLDYyCUh6.JournalEntryPage.kYcSTPeASQ45iHrC]{gear} for the situation as well.</p><h3>Soldier</h3><p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Soldier]{See the actor here.}</p><p><strong>Attributes:</strong> @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} d6, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Smarts} d4, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Spirit} d6, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} d6, Vigor d6</p><p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} d6, Common Knowledge d6, Fighting d6, Intimidation d6, Notice d6, Persuasion d6, Shooting d6, Stealth d4</p><p><strong>Pace:</strong> 6; <strong>Parry:</strong> 5; <strong>Toughness:</strong> 5</p><p><strong>Hindrances:</strong> —</p><p><strong>Edges:</strong> Soldier</p><h3>Experienced Soldier</h3><p>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Experienced Soldier]{See the actor here.}</p><p><strong>Attributes:</strong> @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} d6, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Smarts} d6, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Spirit} d6, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} d8, Vigor d8</p><p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} d6, Common Knowledge d6, Fighting d8, Intimidation d6, Notice d6, Persuasion d6, Shooting d8, Stealth d6</p><p><strong>Pace:</strong> 6; <strong>Parry:</strong> 6; <strong>Toughness:</strong> 6</p><p><strong>Hindrances:</strong> —</p><p><strong>Edges:</strong> Soldier and any two combat Edges.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Downtime","type":"text","_id":"04SdD9oGznMOopbp","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Downtime</h1><p>Adventurers often have time between their epic quests. Some might spend it practicing their sword fighting techniques or enchanting magic items. Others may pray to their gods, try to earn a few coins in town, spend time with their friends, or aid locals in need.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> When the party has at least a week between adventures.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Each player chooses one of the activities below and gains its benefits.</p><h2>Personal Time</h2><p>When the Dungeon Master decides there’s Downtime of at least a week, you can choose one of the following activities. Each provides a benefit of some sort, from financial rewards to limited but valuable skill bonuses. Narrate what your hero is doing then follow the instructions under each activity.</p><p>Unless an option says otherwise, its effect may only be gained once regardless of how long the downtime lasts.</p><h2>Carouse</h2><p>Carousing characters spend their time socializing with friends, making new ones, or cementing relationships with their contacts. This usually involves considerable cost and time spent at local restaurants and taverns.</p><p>During her Downtime, the character spends 50gp in food, drink, and entertainment. Double that for each @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Rank} thereafter: 100 gp for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Seasoned}, 200 gp for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Veteran}, 400 gp for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Heroic}, and 800 gp if she’s @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Legendary}).</p><p>In exchange, she gains a local favor she can call in at any time. The greater her @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Rank} and her overall standing in the community (DM's call), the greater the favor.</p><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork/ambience/taverns/tavern-welcome-01.webp\" /><h3> Carousing from Cabin Fever</h3><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} lost to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever} can only be relieved by rest and relaxation. This means carousing in a port with plenty of booze and women for most. Historically, sailors have often spent the equivalent of a year’s pay in a single week.</p><p>Each week spent in port where the crew can relax (which usually means boozing and wenching) removes one level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} due to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cabin Fever]{Cabin Fever}. Each night of carousing costs [[/r 1d6*4]] gp for player characters. Extras spend their own pay or shares and their expenses should not be tracked.</p><p>Caurousing in this way, <em>does not</em> gain a local favor.</p><p><strong>Rushing:</strong> Characters may unwind quicker by spending more money on good food, drink, and company. Spending [[/r 2d6*4]] gp reduces the time to remove @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} to four days; [[/r 3d6*4]] gp reduces the interval to three days, and so on, to a minimum of one day and [[/r 4d6*4]] gp.</p><p>Player characters can also encourage their crews along. Each additional 2 golden galifars reduces the time to remove @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} by one day, to a minimum of one day and 8 gp per head.</p><p><strong>Getting Drunk:</strong> Carousing characters must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Smarts} roll each night to avoid getting drunk. A failure means they barely manage to make it back to their hammock that night, and suffer a grueling hangover the next morning (they are @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued} until sometime after lunch).</p><p>Success means the party-goer is drunk, but can mostly handle himself. @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Smarts}, and all related skill rolls suffer a –1 penalty, but @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} is increased by 1.</p><h2>Center</h2><p>The hero focuses on whatever brings her happiness. That might include quality time with friends, a solitary hunt through a secluded forest, riding a favorite horse, painting, reading, writing, performing, dancing, or courting a romantic interest.</p><p>Whatever the activity, the goal is inner peace and happiness. Taking a week to enjoy the fruits of one's labors grants the character @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Conviction]{Conviction}.</p><h2>Earn</h2><p>The hero earns currency in some way. Perhaps he takes on odd jobs, kills rats in the local tavern, or even \"procures\" it from the local thieves' guild!</p><p>The hero must make a relevant skill roll to earn her reward—@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} for scoundrels, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} for Mercenaries, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} for entertainers, etc. Use an appropriate attribute for more mundane jobs.</p><p>A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} means the character doesn't make any money and embarrasses herself somehow. If the job was dangerous, she also takes d4 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Wounds}. Failure means she doesn't make any money and takes @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises} (page 153).</p><p>Success earns her 100 gp if she's @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Novice} rank, 200 gp if @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Seasoned}, 300 gp if @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Veteran}, 400 gp for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Heroic}, and 500 gp if she's @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Legendary}. Double the reward with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.</p><h2>Enchant</h2><p>A character that is an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Artificer]{Artificer} or can @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Craft Arcane Device]{Craft Arcane Device} can spend her time at a workshop @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Crafting Magic Items]{crafting magic items}.</p><div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-working-with-shard.webp\" /></div><h2>Research</h2><p>A character can spend her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{Downtime} developing or learning new powers. This doesn't permanently give her a power, but allows her to use any spell or miracle from her Available Powers list and of her Rank or lower for one entire encounter.</p><p>The character may also temporarily change the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.2 Trappings]{Trapping} of a power she already has for one encounter—turning a fireball into an ice blast, for example.</p><p>The spell is cast at a −2 penalty, but is otherwise treated just like one of the caster's regular powers. This can be particularly useful if the mage or priest must prepare to face a threat with a particular weakness.</p><p>Finally, Research can also be used to reveal deep information about a particular subject. No Trait roll is required. The DM decides just how much the investigator can learn in a week given the topic, the location, and resources at hand.</p><h2>Rest</h2><p>Those who have suffered grievous @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Wounds} might need to do so during Downtime to recover their health.</p><p>Use the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Healing]{natural healing} rules during the week. Any healers in the group can provide @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}, as can other allies or hired professionals such as priests at a temple, or physicians in a nobleman's employ.</p><p>Characters may choose to rest even if they have no @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{Wounds}. The provides the same benefits as @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Center]{Centering}, with the hero doing nothing but resting mind and body to recover from the stress of adventuring.</p><h2>Train</h2><p>An adventurer can practice a specific skill or attribute to temporarily increase its effectiveness. A character might train @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} by sparring with a swordmaster, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} by public speaking, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana} by studying forbidden tomes, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} or @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} with vigorous exercise, and so on.</p><p>The character must possess at least d4 in any skill chosen for training. Afterwards, she gets one free reroll when failing that skill or attribute for one entire encounter. This stacks with any other rerolls she may have from other sources.</p><p>The player chooses when to activate her rerolls as a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Actions]{free action}.</p><p>If she Trains again, the previous focus is lost.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Dramatic Tasks","type":"text","_id":"NRtBj0hR1OsFGfGx","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Dramatic Tasks</h1><p>Heroes often find themselves in tense and dangerous situations such as disabling a complex trap, climbing a rock face while under fire from archers, or rescuing people from a burning building or sinking ship with a definite — and sometimes deadly — time limit.</p><p>This system simulates these events and helps the Dungeon Master insert some drama into what would otherwise be simple skill rolls.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Dramatic Tasks are great for tense actions that must be performed in a hurry or have disastrous effects if failed.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> The heroes make skill rolls to accumulate \"Task Tokens\" and resolve the event before time runs out.</p><h2>Setup</h2><p>The DM starts by figuring out what the task is, how long the party has to complete it, and how many tokens they need for success.</p><h3>Single Person Tasks</h3><p>Use these guidelines when only a single character can attempt the task each turn (others can @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}):</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Challenging:</span> Collect four Task Tokens in three rounds. <em>Examples:</em> Disable a trap in the dark, pick a lock before a guard returns, disengage a moving horse-team from its wagon.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Difficult:</span> Collect six Task Tokens in four rounds. <em>Examples:</em> Disable a trap in the middle of combat, cast a ritual, sail a craft to shore during a storm.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Complex:</span> Collect eight Task Tokens in five rounds. <em>Examples:</em> Disable a particularly complicated and/or dangerous trap, Pick a very difficult lock or series of locks before a patrol returns, cast a large and powerful ritual, repair a complicated machine with multiple moving parts.</li></ul><h3>Multi-Person Tasks</h3><p>If more than one person can attempt the task at once, such as crewing a ship, the DM must set the number of rounds and tokens required for victory herself. Here are some guidelines.</p><p>Assume each player will average one success per turn. Use that as a guideline if you want the task to be \"fair,\" and set the number of rounds from three to five as appropriate. A party of five given three rounds to save a galleon in a storm, for example, needs to accumulate 15 Task Tokens in three rounds. Increase or decrease the number of tokens to make it more or less challenging.</p><p>If the number of tokens achieved is a measure of success rather than a straight win/fail condition, such as rescuing victims from a fire or hauling up bags of gold from a collapsing mineshaft, simply set the possible number of tokens that may be gathered in the time allowed. Each token gathered represents a person saved, a bag recovered, etc. It’s up to you whether it’s possible to save them all (using the guide above) or not.</p><p>Let the party choose how many will attempt the task, especially if there’s something else going on at the same time. Deciding how many heroes will break into the jail to rescue a friend while the others fight off the corrupt city guard allows <em>them</em> to choose their tactics.</p><h2>Performing the Task</h2><p>Characters are dealt @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Cards} as usual during a Dramatic Task. Those attempting the task make relevant skill checks and get a Task Token for each success and raise. Failure means no progress and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} reduces progress by one (if any has been made).</p><p>The skills that can be used to accumulate tokens depends on the situation. They might be defined, such as @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} to disable a trap, or they might be open — a heroic paladin might use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to carry people from a burning building while a mage uses <em>telekinesis</em> (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Spellcasting]{Spellcasting}) to do the same.</p><h3>Multiple Skills</h3><p>The DM can break tasks down into steps if she likes, each of which might require different skills. If disabling a difficult trap in the dark, for example, the heroes might first have to get two tokens to get the feel for their surroundings using @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, then three more tokens using Thievery to cut all three trip wires in the correct order.</p><p>Requiring multiple skills throughout the task makes it more difficult since raises from one type of skill check don’t carry over to the other. In the trap example above, for example, the first step requires two Notice successes. Additional successes <em>don’t</em> carry over to the Thievery rolls needed afterward.</p><h3>Complications</h3><p>If a character’s Action Card is a Club, something has gone wrong. Attempts to resolve the task (or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} it!) are made at an additional −2.</p><p>Worse, if a roll is failed during a Complication, the Dramatic Task fails — the trap springs, the lock jams, a victim cannot be saved, and so on. The character may choose <em>not</em> to attempt a roll on a turn he has a Complication — it just costs him precious time.</p><p><strong>Support:</strong> Characters assisting (via Support)also suffer the Complication penalty, and an additional −2 if <em>their</em> Action Card is a Club! @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on their part just subtracts from the lead’s roll as usual, however, it doesn’t cause the entire task to fail.</p><h3>Death Traps</h3><p>Think carefully before designing Dramatic Tasks that might wipe out the entire party if failed. The threat of catastrophe should be very real but you don’t want a couple of bad die rolls to end the entire game.</p><p>Instead of total disaster, maybe the party has a moment to dive clear before the trap triggers. They don’t perish, but later awake in the care of a local healer or are captured and find themselves about to experience a new type of adventure.</p><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Dragon fire!</h2><p>An evil red dragon roams the countryside, burning farms and villages throughout the land. @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Seelah]{Seelah} the paladin and @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Harsk]{Harsk} the ranger watch in horror as the dragon breathes fire down on their favorite tavern. The pair rush to aid the choking and gasping patrons attempting to flee the burning building.</p><p>The Dungeon Master decides rescuing the survivors is a three-round, Multi-Person Dramatic Task. There are 10 patrons. Each success saves one of them from the inferno.</p><p>On the first round, Seelah and Harsk roll @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to run into the tavern and drag someone out. Both get a raise, so that's four citizens saved!</p><p>The next round, Harsk gets a Complication. The DM decides he becomes trapped in one of the back rooms and must make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll at −2. If he fails, it takes him too long to escape and he won't be able to save any more patrons. Harsk draws his brother's trusty @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Axe, Battle]{battleaxe} and hacks his way free. He decides to go with it and narrates using his Fighting to hack open a hole in the wall for the survivors. He's successful, and Seelah gets a raise this turn with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} — yelling at the locals to help throw water on the fire. That's seven total patrons saved.</p><p>On the third round, Seelah gets a Complication and fails — she's choking on smoke and can't help. Fortunately, after spending a few Bennies, Harsk manages to get two @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raises} and pull the last patrons from the fire.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/dragon-fire.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Fear","type":"text","_id":"e6RBh6PzbTF7QlOH","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Fear</h1><p>Cold dread seizes the heroine as she enters the lost tomb. A dragon emerges from the cave, belching smoke and fire at the adventurers who threaten its hoard. An investigator stumbles upon a scene of grisly, ritualistic carnage.</p><p>These rules reflect the horror of these terrible situations upon your heroes’ psyches.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> When a creature has the @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Fear]{Fear} Special Ability, or the Dungeon Master decides a situation is particularly disturbing.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Characters make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Sprit} roll when confronted by creatures or situations that cause Fear.</p><h2>Fear Checks</h2><p>The heroes make a Fear check (a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Spirit} roll as a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}) when they first spot a creature with the @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Fear]{Fear}Fear ability}.</p><p>Success means a character manages to overcome the situation and carry on. A failed Fear check means the unfortunate soul faces the consequences below, depending on whether the source of fear was grotesque or terrifying in nature:</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Nausea:</span> If the scene was grotesque or horrific, such as a grisly discovery or learning a secret \"Man Was Not Meant to Know,\" the character is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued} from the mental strain. Critical Failure means the victim must roll on the <strong>Fear Table</strong> as well.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Terror:</span> A terrifying trigger, such as a monstrous creature or unknowable evil, is much more intense. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} are typically Panicked. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} must roll on the <strong>Fear Table</strong> (at +2 with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on the Fear check). Roll a d20 and add the monster’s Fear penalty, if any, to the roll (a −2 adds +2 to the roll, for example).</li></ul><h3>Becoming Jaded</h3><p>After encountering a particular type of creature, the character doesn’t have to make Fear checks every time he sees another in that particular scenario. If the party clears out an asylum full of spectral inmates, for example, they should only have to roll the first time they encounter them — not in every room. The Dungeon Master might require a roll if the heroes encounter such horrors in a particularly different or frightening situation, however.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Fear Table</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">d20*</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Effect</th></tr><tr><td>1–3</td><td><strong>Adrenaline Surge:</strong> The hero’s \"fight\" response takes over. He acts as if he had a Joker this action!</td></tr><tr><td>4–6</td><td><strong>Distracted:</strong> The hero is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted} until the end of his next turn.</td></tr><tr><td>7–9</td><td><strong>Vulnerable:</strong> The target is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable} until the end of his next turn.</td></tr><tr><td>10–12</td><td><strong>Shaken:</strong> The character is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}.</td></tr><tr><td>13</td><td><strong>The Mark of Fear:</strong> The hero is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned} and suffers some cosmetic physical alteration — a white streak forms in his hair, his eyes twitch constantly, or some other minor physical alteration manifests.</td></tr><tr><td>14–15</td><td><strong>Frightened:</strong> The character gains the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Hesitant]{Hesitant} Hindrance for the remainder of the encounter. If he already has it, he’s Panicked instead.</td></tr><tr><td>16–17</td><td><strong>Panicked:</strong> The character immediately moves his full @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{Pace} plus running die away from the danger and is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}.</td></tr><tr><td>18–19</td><td><strong>Minor Phobia:</strong> The character gains a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Phobia]{Minor Phobia} Hindrance somehow associated with the trauma.</td></tr><tr><td>20–21</td><td><strong>Major Phobia:</strong> The character gains the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Phobia]{Major Phobia} Hindrance.</td></tr><tr><td>22+</td><td><strong>Heart Attack:</strong> The hero is so overwhelmed with fear that his heart stutters. He must make an immediate @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll at –2. If successful, he’s @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned}. If he fails, he’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} and @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{dies} in 2d6 rounds. In the latter case, a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} roll at –4 saves his life, but he remains Incapacitated. He may be treated normally thereafter.</td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>*Add the creature’s Fear penalty as a positive number to this roll.</em></p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"Hazards","type":"text","_id":"LPo1KwxBel9ChMww","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Hazards</h1><p>Heat, cold, hunger, thirst, lack of sleep, and other hazards can wear down even the hardiest of heroes, sending them into a downward spiral that can lead to death if they can’t improve their situation.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Hazards intro­duce resource management to long trips through dangerous regions. They also push the party toward critical resources like water or shelter where encounters with other travelers or creatures are likely present.</p><p>The other Hazards listed here, such as falling, poison, disease, and the like, generally come up in response to a creature or situation.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Each Hazard is different, but most are an attribute check made periodically against some dangerous effect. Failure tends to cause <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}</strong> . Use the standard rules modified by any changes noted in this section.</p><aside class=\"sidebar float-right\"><h2>The Rule of Threes</h2><p>Extreme survivalists often talk about the “rule of threes.” All of these apply to reasonably healthy individuals, of course. Those with illnesses or other infirmities will fare worse.</p><p>These “rules” encourage those in dangerous circumstances to prioritize, seeing to their shelter in a freezing environment before worrying about water and food, for example. In the game, these conditions should only come into play when dramatically appropriate.</p><ul class=\"red-bullet-list\"><li><strong>AIR: </strong>A standard rule of survival says most people can survive three minutes without air (though they likely pass out and need resuscitation after a minute).</li><li><strong>SHELTER: </strong>You can live for three hours without shelter in a harsh environment, such as sub-zero temperatures.</li><li><strong>WATER: </strong>You can live for three days without water.</li><li><strong>FOOD: </strong>You can live three weeks without food.</li></ul></aside><h2>Bumps and Bruises</h2><p>Stumbling down a slope or running through a cavern in the dark might cause numerous cuts, scrapes, and bumps.</p><p>Characters moving through injurious terrain make an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll. Those who fail gain a level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} levels from Bumps &amp; Bruises improve one level every 24 hours instead of every hour.</p><p>A character may use the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} skill to treat the injuries. Success relieves one level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from Bumps &amp; Bruises and a raise relieves two. Each healer may attempt this roll only once unless the DM decides a change in circumstances warrants another opportunity (finding medical supplies, for example).</p><h2>Climbing</h2><p>Climbing uses the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} skill, and the basics are covered under <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{Movement}</strong>. When the game is in rounds, each inch climbed takes 2″ of Pace.</p><p>No roll is usually needed to ascend ladders or trees with sturdy limbs unless the DM feels there’s a good reason (being chased, injured, etc.).</p><p>Under stress (such as during combat rounds), the climber must roll @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to make progress. Success means he moves normally, failure means he doesn’t make any progress that round, and a Critical Failure indicates a fall! If secured by a rope or other restraint, he falls half the length of the restraint and suffers Fatigue from <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>. If unsecured, see the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Falling]{Falling}</strong> rules.</p><p><strong>Modifiers:</strong> The DM should assign a bonus (+2) if the surface has numerous hand- and footholds or the climber has good equipment. Assign a penalty (−1 to −4) for smooth surfaces, lack of equipment, bad weather, etc.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/yeti.webp\" /></div><h3>Prepared Climbs</h3><p>Break lengthy ascents like climbing mountain sides into three roughly even sections. Assume any falls occur at the \"top\" of each section.</p><p>The DM might also consider using the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{Dramatic Tasks}</strong> system if the surface must be ascended in a certain amount of time — such as before weather hits, guards return, etc.</p><h2>Cold</h2><p>Trudging through deep snow for hours on end, facing biting winds, or falling in ice water can wear down and kill even a hearty warrior.</p><p>A character must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll every four hours spent in weather below freezing (32° F); at −2 if the temperature is below 0° F. Failure means the hero incurs a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} level.</p><p>Roll only once per day if a character has appropriate cold weather gear (heavy furs and the like), or once every five days if well-provisioned with shelter, food, and other resources.</p><p><strong>Death:</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} victims die after 2d6 hours instead of waking @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Exhausted}.</p><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> Victims can recover @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} only after they receive adequate warmth and shelter.</p><h2>Disease</h2><p>Diseases cover a wide range of maladies, from long-term debilitating illnesses to those which might cause immediate spasms or @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{death}.</p><p>Diseases can be contracted through various vectors, such as an airborne source, ingestion, or the touch or bite of a creature that causes a @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wound} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} result. In any of these situations, the victim must make an immediate @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll to avoid infection.</p><p>To handle such a diverse range of diseases, we’ve broken them down into three major categories. If you’re trying to model a specific disease, adjust the rules presented here to better reflect its symptoms.</p><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> Diseases can be cured by the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing}</em> power with the Neutralize Poison or Disease modifier, or with specific medications — whether or not those are available depends on the game (DM's call).</p><p>The symptoms can often be treated by common medicines, however. With a successful @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} roll, a physician, priest, herbalist, etc., can prescribe or create a treatment. She may attempt to do so once per day.</p><p>Each application of the treatment (balms, poultices, elixirs, etc.) reduces @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} by one level for four hours.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Disease categories</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Type</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Effect</th></tr><tr><td>Chronic</td><td><p>At the start of every game session, the character makes a Vigor roll. Failure means he’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Exhausted} from spasms, coughing fits, or similar issues for that session. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means he will @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{expire} before the end of the session. The DM is encouraged to let heroes go out in a blaze of glory if possible. Success means the victim is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued} for the game session, and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} means he gets a second wind and suffers no ill effects.</p></td></tr><tr><td>Debilitating</td><td><p>Flus, viruses, stomach bugs and the like have various specific symptoms but generally result in the character being @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued} for 2d6 days.</p></td></tr><tr><td>Lethal</td><td><p>Fast-acting diseases might be found in the darkest depths of forgotten dungeons or in specific locations on Eberron. Upon contracting the disease, the hero is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigued}. At the start of each turn thereafter, he must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll or suffer a @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wound}! (Some diseases may call for a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll more slowly, such as once per hour or once per day.) A successful @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} roll stops the effects <em>only</em> if the proper medicine is on hand to stop the disease.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Drowning</h2><p>Swimming is covered under <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{Movement}</strong>. In still water, each inch of movement on the tabletop takes 2″ of Pace. Swimming up or down stream should modify this as the Dungeon Master sees fit.</p><p>Under hazardous conditions, swimmers must roll @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} to move. Failure means she makes no progress that round, and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} causes a level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. With success she moves normally.</p><p>If it becomes important to know, characters can hold their breath for a number of rounds equal to 2 plus their Vigor die, or half that if they weren’t prepared for being submerged and didn’t have time to get a good breath.</p><p>Add +2 to swimming rolls if a character has something that floats to hold on to.</p><p><strong>Armor:</strong> Subtract 1 for each point of worn armor, not counting any magical bonuses. Swimming in chainmail, for example, subtracts 3 from a character's @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (swimming) rolls.</p><p><strong>Death:</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} characters @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{perish} in a number of rounds equal to their Vigor die. If someone can get to the victim before then, he can be resuscitated with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Healing} roll at −2.</p><h2>Electricity</h2><p>On Eberron, characters may encounter natural or magical sources of electricity. Contact with a high voltage electrical source (DM's call) causes 3d6 damage. Increase the damage by +1d6 if the victim is standing in deep water or driving rain, and +2 if the victim wears mostly metal armor (chainmail, platemail).</p><p><strong>Armor:</strong> Armor doesn’t protect from electrical damage unless it’s specifically designed to do so (e.g., a rubberized suit).</p><h2>Falling</h2><p>Falling damage is 1d6+1 for every full 10 feet (or d6+1 per 2\" on the tabletop), to a maximum of 10d6+10.</p><p><strong>Snow:</strong> Particularly soft ground, such as very deep snow, acts as a cushion. Every foot of soft snow reduces damage 1 point.</p><p><strong>Water:</strong> A successful @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll halves damage into reasonably deep water at heights of 10″ (20 yards) or less. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} negates the damage entirely. Those who fall into water from heights greater than 20 yards take damage as if they’d hit solid earth.</p><h2>Fire and Smoke Inhalation</h2><p>If a flammable target is hit by fire (DM's call), roll 1d6. On a 6, the target catches fire and immediately takes the damage listed below. Very flammable targets catch fire on a 4–6. Volatile targets, such as a person dowsed in pitch, catch fire on a 2–6.</p><p>Fire continues to cause damage at the beginning of the victim’s turns. Roll a d6 immediately after it does so. On a 6, it grows in intensity to whatever maximum the DM feels is appropriate (usually 3d6 for organic beings). On a 1, the fire drops a level, or burns out if reduced below 1d6 damage.</p><p>A character may also make an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll to put out a fire on himself, others, or a flame the size of a Medium @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Blast]{Blast} Template. This is an action, plus any modifiers for intensity, tools, the flammability of the target, etc.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Fire Damage</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Damage</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Description</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">[[/r 1d6]]</td><td>Spot contact, steam</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">[[/r 2d6]]</td><td>Bonfire, burning room</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">[[/r 3d6]]</td><td>Fireball</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">[[/r 5d6]]</td><td>Lava</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Armor:</strong> Armor protects normally unless the attack or hazard’s description says otherwise. A hero hit with a fireball is still better off if he has a breastplate than not, for example.</p><p><strong>Flaming Weapons:</strong> Flame doesn’t cause extra @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage]{damage} but may set the target on fire if the target is flammable or volatile (as above).</p><h3>Smoke Inhalation</h3><p>Fires in confined areas produce deadly smoke. Each person within must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll every round. If the roll is failed, the character gains a level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. A wet cloth or similar precaution adds +2 to the roll.</p><p><strong>Death:</strong> A person @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} from smoke inhalation @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{dies} in a number of minutes equal to his Vigor. If someone can get to the victim before then, he can be resuscitated by removing him from the hazard and succeeding on a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} roll at −2.</p><h2>Heat</h2><p>Heat over 90° Fahrenheit can cause heat exhaustion and heatstroke.</p><p>A character must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll every four hours spent in weather above 90° F; at −2 if the temperature is above 110° F. Failure means the hero incurs a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} level.</p><p>Roll only once per day if a character has plenty of water, or once every five days if well-provisioned with shelter, food, and other resources.</p><p><strong>Heatstroke:</strong> A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} when resisting heat indicates heatstroke! The hero must make a second @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll or perish.</p><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> A victim must cool down somehow to recover @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. This usually means water, shade, and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Rest]{rest}.</p><h2>High Altitude</h2><p>Traversing landscapes at high elevations can cause @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} — and potentially worse — to those who aren’t used to it.</p><p>When traveling at altitudes roughly a mile high or higher, a character must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll every four hours. Failure means the hero incurs a Fatigue level. The roll is at −2 for elevation greater than 10,000 feet, and −4 (maximum) for higher than 15,000 feet.</p><p>At the DM's discretion, characters who are already acclimated to these elevations don’t need to roll.</p><p><strong>Death:</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} victims @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{die} after 2d6 hours.</p><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> Victims one level of Fatigue per hour after resting for at least two full hours.</p><h2>Hunger</h2><p>Average-size humans need about 1,500 calories of reasonably nutritious food per day to avoid the effects of hunger. If sufficient sustenance isn’t available, a character begins to suffer and die.</p><p>After 24 hours without enough food, the victim must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll. Failure means he gains a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} level.</p><p>See the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}</strong> skill when a character wants to hunt or scrounge for food from the local environment.</p><p><strong>Death:</strong> An @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} character @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{dies} from hunger 3d6 hours later.</p><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> The victim must have at least a half day’s food to recover.</p><h2>Poison</h2><p>The bane of adventurers across all of Eberron can be delivered by the smallest of foes — poison!</p><p>When an adventurer is poisoned, he must make an immediate @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll minus the Strength of the poison (if listed). Failure causes the effects listed below:</p><ul><li><strong>Disabling:</strong> These poisons dull one of the victim’s attributes and linked skills (chosen at the time of creation) by creating hallucinations, inhibiting nerve function, causing euphoria, etc. The affected attribute is reduced a die type (two with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.hCxcCUCRxHOWcNGS]{Critical Failure} on the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll) for 30 minutes.</li><li><strong>Knockout:</strong> The victim is knocked out (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} and unconscious) for 2d6 hours (twice that with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}).</li><li><strong>Lethal:</strong> The victim is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned}, takes a Wound (two with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}), and perishes in 2d6 rounds.</li><li><strong>Mild:</strong> The victim suffers @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}, or Exhaustion with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}. This cannot cause Incapacitation.</li><li><strong>Paralyzing:</strong> The victim is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned} and cannot attempt to recover for d4+1 rounds (double that with a Critical Failure).</li></ul><p>These are basic and simplified poison effects that can be altered as needed to suit specific creatures or hazards. A particularly deadly venomous snake, for example, might still cause Exhaustion to those who resist its effects, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/oasis.webp\" /></div><p><strong>Treatment:</strong> A character may make a @Compendium[swpf-core-rules.swpf-skills.Healing]{Healing} roll minus the strength of the poison (if any modifier is listed) to stop its effects. If successful, the victim’s life is saved and the poison no longer has any ill effects — paralyzed victims can move and those rendered unconscious wake.</p><p>Each character may only attempt one Healing roll per incident to cure the poison, but another character with Healing may try as well.</p><h3>Delievery</h3><p>Poisons are delivered in several ways. In all cases, a being can’t be forced to resist the same type of poison more than once per round.</p><p><em>Contact poisons</em> must touch bare skin. They can also be applied to a weapon and remain effective for four hours.</p><p><em>Inhaled poisons</em> are released by breaking their container. They form a Medium Blast Template cloud and affect everyone within.</p><p><em>Ingested poisons</em> must be consumed. The target may make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll to detect the poison’s smell or taste before consuming.</p><p><em>Injury poisons</em> must be applied to a piercing or cutting weapon, and are delivered when an attack isn’t Soaked and results in Shaken.</p><h3>Purchasing Poisons</h3><p>Whether poisons can be bought openly or not depends on the setting. In most fantasy worlds, mild poisons or those used to take care of vermin or other common nuisances are readily available. Those typically used for more sinister purposes must be obtained via the black market or from those who set themselves off from the rest of society.</p><h3>Crafting Poisons</h3><p>Characters can make their own poisons for half the cost listed below. Doing so uses the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Science]{Science}, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival} skill and d6 hours of preparation per batch. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} during this process results in the poisoner poisoning himself!</p><p><strong>Strength</strong>: The crafter can make the potion stronger (resisted at Vigor –2) by increasing the time to 2d6 hours and paying the full cost listed below.</p><h3>Antidotes &amp; Treatment</h3><p>Antidotes for poisons use the same crafting rules. An antidote only works against the specific type of poison for which it is created, and gives the user a Vigor roll minus half the strength of the poison to recover completely from its effects (including removing Hindrances for Lotus Dust).</p><p>As long as a chracter has a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Healer's Kit]{Healer's Kit} they may make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} roll minus the strength of the poison (if any modifier is listed) to stop its effects. If successful, the victim’s life is saved and the poison no longer has any ill effects—paralyzed victims can move and those rendered unconscious wake.</p><p>Each character may only attempt one Healing roll per incident to cure the poison, but another character with Healing may try as well.</p><h2>Random Traps</h2><p>Draw two cards from the Action Deck whenever you need a trap on the fly. These tell you everything you need to know about its concealment, complexity, type, and lethality. Very occasionally you'll need to draw a third card, but the rules below tell you when to do this.</p><p>The DM should add suitable flavor to these draws based on the trap type. For instance, a \"blade trap\" could be a scything blade slicing from the wall at knee height or a spear which thrusts out from a concealed hole. A Spade result on the trap might indicate multiple blades, hence the high Fighting die and increased damage. A portcullis of the Club suit might be heavily corroded or made of wood, whereas a Spade indicates extremely tough and well-made bars.</p><h3>First Card</h3><p>The first card determines how difficult the trap is to detect and disarm. This is shown on the <strong>Trap Difficulty Table</strong> below as modifiers to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery] rolls.</p><p>Note that <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{glyph}</em> traps cannot be disarmed by mundane means (and so ignore the suit), but they can be <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispelled} </em>and negated. Use the suit entry of the second card on the Trap Type table below to determine the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} die for this purpose.</p><p><strong>Detecting: </strong>Detecting a trap requires a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll. Unless a character has @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Danger Sense], searching for traps requires an action. A @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{running} hero rolls at –2. A single roll is made in a round, regardless of how far the hero moves. With success, he detects the first trap adjacent to him. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} locates a second trap within line of sight, if such exists. The hero may halt his movement if he spots a trap (advisable if it's right in front of him).</p><p><strong>Disarming: </strong>Disarming a detected trap requires a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery] roll and takes a complete round (no other actions possible, including movement). On a critical failure, the trap activates and automatically affects the unfortunate hero.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"4\">Trap Difficulty</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Value</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Detect</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Suit</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Disarm</th></tr><tr><td>Joker</td><td>+2</td><td>Joker</td><td>+2</td></tr><tr><td>2–4</td><td>+1</td><td>Club</td><td>+1</td></tr><tr><td>5–10</td><td>0</td><td>Diamond</td><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>Jack–Queen</td><td>–1</td><td>Heart</td><td>–1</td></tr><tr><td>King–Ace</td><td>–2</td><td>Spade</td><td>–2</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Second Card</h3><p>The second card determines the exact type of trap encountered. This is detailed on the <strong>Trap Type Table</strong>.</p><p><strong>Wild Die: </strong>On a Joker the trap is exceptionally lethal and has a Wild Die. Draw a third card to determine the trap type. The suit of the new card indicates the Wild Die, as well as other details. Traps with a Wild Die apply it to rolls to all Trait rolls, when applicable.</p><p><strong>Area: </strong>Traps usually affect a 1\" square on the battle grid. Ranged attacks use the standard range brackets for the type of missile launched. Whatever projectile is launched, range is calculated as normal. The distance listed for pits is their depth. <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Glyph]{Glyph} </em>traps affect an area or operate at range as per the spell description and the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} die.</p><p><strong>Duration: </strong>Traps are generally one-shot devices. Once activated, they must be reset in order to work again. Portcullises remain in place until lifted up.</p><p><strong>Initiative:</strong> Most traps activate with little warning to the unfortunate victim. Outside of combat use the rules for @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Surprise]. In combat, traps being on Hold and roll to interrupt. Traps have @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} d10 for this purpose. A trap also has @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.l1rEt2RnvcIiEGtQ]{the Drop} where applicable. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} to avoid @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Surprise] and @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} rolls to avoid interruption use the same modifier as for Detecting traps (see above).</p><p><strong>Attacks: </strong>Traps which make attack rolls cannot use any combat maneuvers—they simply roll their attack die.</p><p><strong>Notes: </strong>The following short codes are used on the table. Arcane = @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill}. Used when a spell activates, requires an attribute die value for any reason, and to resist dispel attempts. Fight = @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting] skill. Sh = @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting] skill (range and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover} modifiers apply). @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength}–X = penalty to @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} roll to lift obstacle. XdY = number and type of damage dice. #X = number of attacks a trap makes against a single victim or can split among multiple victims (DM's call based on placement). Traps which use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting] do not suffer penalties for @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions}.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"6\">Trap Type</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\" style=\"width:10%\">Value</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\" style=\"width:15%\">Type</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Clubs</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Diamonds</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Hearts</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Spades</th></tr><tr><td>Joker*</td><td>–</td><td>d4 Wild Die</td><td>d6 Wild Die</td><td>d8 Wild Die</td><td>d10 Wild Die</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Portcullis**</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\">Strength</a> –1</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\">Strength</a> –2</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\">Strength</a> –4</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\">Strength</a> –6</td></tr><tr><td>3–4</td><td>Pit Trap***</td><td>10', 1d6</td><td>20', 2d6</td><td>30', 3d6</td><td>40', 4d6</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Spiked Pit</td><td>10', 1d6+2</td><td>20', 2d6+4</td><td>30', 3d6+6</td><td>40', 4d6+8</td></tr><tr><td>6–8</td><td>Projectile</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\">Sh</a> d6, 2d6, #1</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\">Sh</a> d8, 2d6, #1</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\">Sh</a> d10, 2d6, #3</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"Shooting\">Sh</a> d12, 2d6, #4</td></tr><tr><td>9–10</td><td>Blade</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\">Fight</a> d6, 2d6</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\">Fight</a> d8, 2d8</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\">Fight</a> d10, 2d10</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-skills\" data-id=\"xCkOFlFmE1WwGXq6\">Fight</a> d12, 2d12</td></tr><tr><td>Jack</td><td>Poisoned</td><td colspan=\"4\">Treat as a Projectile of the same suit. Anyone <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\">Shaken</a> or <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\">wounded</a> must make a <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\">Vigor</a> roll. Roll a d10 once with failure. A 1–3 means all victims suffer a level of <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"uQyy7EfJkaHAwXMp\">Fatigue</a> for 2d6 hours, on a 4–7 they are paralyzed for 2d6 minutes, and on 8–10 they suffer an automatic <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\">Wound</a>.</td></tr><tr><td>Queen</td><td>Poisoned</td><td colspan=\"4\">Treat as a Blade of the same suit. Anyone <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\">Shaken</a> or <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\">wounded</a> must make a <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Traits\">Vigor</a> roll. Roll a d10 once with failure. A 1–3 means all victims suffer a level of <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"uQyy7EfJkaHAwXMp\">Fatigue</a> for 2d6 hours, on a 4–7 they are paralyzed for 2d6 minutes, and on 8–10 they suffer an automatic <a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Soak Rolls\">Wound</a>.</td></tr><tr><td>King</td><td>Falling Block</td><td>2d6</td><td>2d8</td><td>3d6</td><td>3d8</td></tr><tr><td>Ace</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"savage-eberron-rules.savage-eberron-powers\" data-id=\"BTDWriPb4tGpCIQm\"><em>Glyph</em></a><em>****</em></td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\">Arcane</a> d6</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\">Arcane</a> d8</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\">Arcane</a> d10</td><td><a class=\"entity-link\" draggable=\"true\" data-pack=\"swade-core-rules.swade-rules\" data-id=\"Arcane Backgrounds\">Arcane</a> d12</td></tr></tbody></table><p>* Draw a third card to determine Wild Die and trap type. A second Joker indicates the trap is faulty and does not work.</p><p>** Portcullis traps either have a single gate (usually to block the way the party has come and so force them forward) or drop two gates (one ahead and one behind the intruders to trap them in a small area). Due to the confines of most corridors or doorways, a maximum of two people can combine their Strength in a Cooperative roll to lift a portcullis.</p><p>*** Alternately, a pit may drop the victims into a lower level of the “dungeon” rather than a small hole, thus separating the party. Another version could be a chute, which drops the victim into a cell or monster’s lair on a lower level but without inflicting any damage.</p><p>**** One spell of the DM's choice.</p><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Random Trap Encountered</h2><p>Aelric Olafsunu is exploring a ruined temple when the DM decides to place a trap in his path. The DM draws two cards. He gets a 3 of Hearts and the King of Diamonds.</p><p>The 3H tells the DM that there is a +1 bonus to the Notice roll to spot the trap (indicated by the 3) and a –1 modifier to disarm it (indicated by the Hearts). The trap is fairly complex, but not very well disguised. Unfortunately, Aelric isn't looking out for traps and walks straight onto it. The DM decides it is a pressure plate mechanism.</p><p>As this occurs outside of combat, Aelric rolls his Notice to avoid Surprise. He adds +1 from the first card's value, and scores 8. The DM tells Aelric he hears an audible click as his foot hits the floor and deals him an action card. Aelric declares he wants to move clear of the square he is on. Before he can do this, however, the trap tries to interrupt him.</p><p>The trap has a fixed d10 @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} and rolls a 9. Aelric rolls his @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} and gets a lousy 5. Aelric has been hit by a falling lump of masonry (as determined by the King value of the second card). He suffers 2d8 damage (determined by the Diamonds).</p><p>Note that although the trap scored a raise over Aelric's @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} total, this was not an attack roll and so it does not deal +1d6 damage.</p><p>Aelric suffers 11 damage, enough to cause him a wound. He vows to be more careful as he descends deeper into the temple.</p><h2>Sleep</h2><p>Most people need a minimum of six hours’ sleep out of every 24. A character who goes without must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll every 24 hours thereafter or suffer @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. Tea or similar stimulants add +1 to the roll.</p><h2>Thirst</h2><p>An average-sized human requires two quarts of water a day. This requirement is doubled in very dry conditions (such as the desert) or areas of great heat and high humidity (the jungle) as the character perspires constantly and begins to dehydrate.</p><p>If enough water isn’t available, the hero begins to suffer from dehydration. A day after he can’t get enough water, he must make a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} roll every eight hours (every four hours in a very hot or humid environment). Failure incurs a level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p><p>See the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}</strong> skill when a character wants to search for water from the local environment.</p><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> Characters recover Fatigue levels normally after receiving sufficient water.</p><p><strong>Death:</strong> An individual @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} by thirst @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Death]{perishes} after 2d6 hours.</p><h2>Traps and Haunts</h2><p>Traps are mechanical or magical in nature, usually constructed to protect treasures or stop intruders. They range from simple camouflaged pits to poisoned @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Darts(blowgun)]{darts} and triggered magical <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Burst]{burst}</em> effects.</p><p>Haunts function like traps, but are specific supernatural phenomena connected to restless shades or other spirits. These areas react violently to the presence of the living, usually triggering some kind of effect when the area is entered or some item of personal import is touched or approached.</p><p>Here's how to read each trap or haunt's description:</p><p><strong>Type:</strong> Mechanical, Magical, Haunt</p><p><strong>Notice Check:</strong> Yes or No, with any modifier to a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll to detect the presence of a trap. Success allows the heroes to react before the trap or haunt is triggered.</p><p><strong>Thievery Check:</strong> Yes or No, with any modifiers to the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} die roll needed to succeed in disabling a trap.</p><p><strong>Effects:</strong> How the trap springs or the haunt manifests, their game effects, and whether or not it can reset.</p><p><strong>Wounds:</strong> Haunts can be affected by the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{healing power}. When the haunt is healed a number of @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounds} equal to the number listed here, it's disabled.</p><p><strong>Reset:</strong> After a certain duration, a haunt (even a disabled one) resets to its original state. The duration is listed in the haunt. This continues until the haunt is destroyed.</p><p><strong>Destroying a Haunt:</strong> To completely destroy a haunt, its source must be destroyed. This is usually listed before the haunt or in the description. This will often involve destroying something, such as a cursed corpse.</p><h2 class=\"trap\">Collapsing Floor</h2><p><strong>Type:</strong> Mechanical; <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} Check:</strong> Yes, at –2; <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} Check:</strong> Yes, at –2</p><p><strong>Trigger:</strong> A hinged section of floor is rigged to give way. Any Size 0 or larger creature entering the room triggers a collapse.</p><p><strong>Effect:</strong> Victims fall 30 feet (3d6+3 damage) unless they make an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Evasion]{Evasion} roll to dive clear.</p><h2 class=\"trap\">Vengeful spirit</h2><p><strong>Type:</strong> Haunt (6’ radius);</p><p><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} Check:</strong> No (the spirit appears without warning);</p><p><strong>Trigger:</strong> Proximity; <strong>Wounds:</strong> 1; <strong>Reset:</strong> 1 day</p><p><strong>Effect:</strong> The spirit manifests in front of the victim, causing him to make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fear]{Fear} check when the ghostly image appears.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Interludes","type":"text","_id":"T9It46wmpatFLiJ3","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Interludes</h1><p>Interludes are tales the players tell in-character to roleplay, enhance a long travel scene, or reveal the secrets and backstories they’ve put so much effort into.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Interludes give players a way to get to know their characters, reveal some of their backstories, and even add to the world you’re all building together.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Players tell a story from their character’s point of view and are rewarded with a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}.</p><h2>Running An Interlude</h2><p>When you want to give your players a moment to catch their breath and get into character, allow those who want to take part to draw a card from the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Deck}.</p><p>The suit of the card gives each player three choices: <strong>Downtime</strong>, <strong>Backstory</strong>, or <strong>Trek</strong>. If a player draws a Joker give <em>everyone</em> an extra @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny} and let <em>them</em> choose the suit and category!</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">DOWNTIME: </span>What the hero does when left alone. A priest might quietly read a holy text while a warrior constantly sharpens his blades.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">BACKSTORY: </span>A tale of the character’s past, told through her voice and narration.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">TREK: </span>The story of an obstacle or challenge the party encountered on the trip.</li></ul><h3>Reward</h3><p>Those players who participate in the ­Interlude receive a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\">Interludes</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Spades</th></tr><tr><td><strong>Downtime: </strong>The character spends time alone in quiet contemplation. What does she do?</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Backstory: </strong>A great victory or personal triumph.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Trek: </strong>A difficult obstacle the group negotiated along the way.</td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Hearts</th></tr><tr><td><strong>Downtime: </strong>The hero practices a skill. What is it?</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Backstory: </strong>A tale of the hero’s greatest love—lost, found, present, or waiting on her back home.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Trek: </strong>The party met along the way—merchants, fellow travelers, a renowned bard or hero, etc. Who were they and what happened?</td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Dimaonds</th></tr><tr><td><strong>Downtime: </strong>The character studies or works on an object of some sort. What is it?</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Backstory: </strong>Something your hero wants or already has. It might be a material possession, recognition, a political goal, or even a trip he wishes to take to some amazing destination.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Trek: </strong>How the group found something that helped them along the way, such as an oasis, minor treasure, food or water, friendly locals, etc.</td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Clubs</th></tr><tr><td><strong>Downtime: </strong>Your hero broods or is angry about something. What is it, and how does she misbehave?</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Backstory: </strong>A tale of misfortune from your hero’s past, perhaps revealing something of his Hindrances or a dark secret.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Trek: </strong>A hardship the party overcame on their trip: the tragic death of a favored @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extra}, spoiled or lost supplies, a mechanical breakdown, abysmal weather, and so on.</td></tr></tbody></table><div class=\"center vert-spacer\"><img class=\"table-figure\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/atmosphere/harpies-attack-an-airship.webp\" /></div><p> </p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"Mass Battles","type":"text","_id":"JldabVKUmZKYJtia","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Mass battles</h1><p>Many adventures feature heroes traveling about the land, gathering @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Allies]{allies} to thwart some inevitable foe or ravaging horde. They build coalitions, train armies, discover powerful artifacts, and finally stand against the enemy in desperate and glorious battle.</p><p>The rules presented here allow the Dungeon Master to handle a small warband holding a fort against an undead horde, a siege against a walled city, or even full divisions of troops fighting across a massive battlefield. The process is abstract, but it provides a narrative base for heroes to plan, get involved, and take part in the carnage!</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use the Mass Battle rules when you need to resolve a large conflict that can go either way, and also allow the player characters to have a role in its outcome. The culmination of these tales is not always a foregone conclusion, and failure can be just as interesting as victory!</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Each side has a number of “Force Tokens” equal to its relative strength and size. Commanders roll their @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle} skill each turn. The winner reduces his rival’s force until one side or the other breaks.</p><h2>Setup</h2><p>To start, give the larger or more powerful army 10 Force Tokens. Give the opposing army a proportional number of tokens. If one army has 10,000 warriors, for example, and the other has 7,000, give the smaller army seven tokens. These represent the troops, ships, and other assets in each side’s army.</p><p>Adjust the ratio as makes sense to account for special or elite troops, better equipment, and so on. If one army is half as powerful as another, for example, give one side 10 Force Tokens and the other five. Get close enough to give a reasonable approximation of relative strength. The dice and the players’ actions will handle the rest.</p><h2>Battle</h2><p>At the start of each round, the player characters discuss and decide on their plan. Then the attackers make an opposed @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle} roll against the defender. Add the modifiers below as appropriate to each roll.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Battle Modifiers</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Modifier</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Circumstance</th></tr><tr><td><p>+1 per<br />point of<br />advantage</p></td><td><p><strong>Force Bonus:</strong> The side with the most Force Tokens adds +1 for each point of difference. If the larger army has 10 tokens and the smaller one has 7, for example, the commander of the more powerful army adds +3.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>+1 to +4</p></td><td><p><strong>Tactical Advantage:</strong> Grant a +1 to +4 bonus for any special circumstances that might help that army, such as fortifications, weather, terrain, or other conditions not otherwise factored into the army’s strength.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>+1 to +4</p></td><td><p><strong>Battle Plan:</strong> Add +1 to +4 if one side has a particularly effective or clever plan over the other.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Results</h3><p>The winner of the opposed roll consults the Battle Results. Casualties are generally distributed evenly throughout the army or however the DM feels is most appropriate for the narrative.</p><p><strong>Time:</strong> A standard battle round is two hours of hard fighting. The Dungeon Master should change this as suits her needs or the story. A more reserved fight might have four- or even eight-hour rounds, while a siege might be a battle round per day.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Battle Results</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Modifier</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Result</th></tr><tr><td><p>Tie</p></td><td><p><strong>Draw:</strong> Both sides lose one Force Token.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Success</p></td><td><p><strong>Marginal Victory:</strong> The victor loses one Force Token, the defeated loses two.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Raise</p></td><td><p><strong>Victory:</strong> The defeated army loses two Force Tokens.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Morale</h3><p>After an army loses one or more Force Tokens, its leader makes a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Sprit} check modified by these circumstances:</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Morale Modifiers</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Modifier</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Circumstance</th></tr><tr><td><p>−1</p></td><td><p>Each Force Token lost so far.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>+2</p></td><td><p>The army is made up mostly of @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Undead]{undead} or other @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary-abilities.Fearless]{fearless} troops.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>+2</p></td><td><p>The army is within fortifications or prepared positions.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>+2</p></td><td><p>The army cannot retreat or will be killed if it does.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Success means the leader cajoles the army to fight on. The battle continues another round (or as the attacker sees fit).</p><p>Failure means the commander loses control of his force. The army is defeated but conducts an orderly retreat. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means they flee the field in a reckless rout. They may be scattered temporarily or permanently, ridden down by the enemy, or captured as the DM decides.</p><h3>Aftermath</h3><p>When one side routs, retreats, or runs out of Force Tokens, the battle ends. If it’s important to determine the fate of named @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Extras} or other nonplayer characters, use the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aftermath and Extras]{Aftermath &amp; Extras}</strong> rules.</p><h2>Characters In Mass Battles</h2><p>Player characters can dramatically affect the results of the battle. Before their commander makes a Battle roll, players who want to enter the fray describe what they’re doing and make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} roll with whatever skill they feel is most appropriate. (Don’t forget that enemy champions can add to the rival commander’s Battle roll as well!)</p><p>Each hero’s success grants the commander +1 to his Battle roll but the warrior takes @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises} for the effort. With a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, the character emerges unharmed and rolls on the <strong>Battle Effects</strong> table; the player may choose to use the result rolled or give the commander the usual +2 bonus instead.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Battle Effects</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">2d6</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Result</th></tr><tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Inspire:</strong> The warrior battles valiantly, inspiring the troops and urging them to fight on despite their injuries. Her side immediately recovers one Force Token.</td></tr><tr><td>3–4</td><td><strong>Terrorize:</strong> The fighter’s fury terrorizes her foes. The enemy commander subtracts 2 from his @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Sprit} roll if forced to test morale this round.</td></tr><tr><td>5–9</td><td><strong>Valor:</strong> The warrior’s Support adds +2 to the commander’s Battle roll as usual.</td></tr><tr><td>10–11</td><td><strong>Slaughter:</strong> The foe reels at the champion’s onslaught. Subtract 2 from the enemy commander’s Battle total.</td></tr><tr><td>12</td><td><strong>An Army of One:</strong> Tales will be told and songs sung of the warrior’s epic feats this day. The enemy army loses a Force Token immediately (this doesn’t subtract from his Battle roll but does cause a morale check even if he wins).</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Failure means the warrior fought bravely. He takes a @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wound} but doesn’t add to the commander’s Battle roll. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means the character rolls on the <strong>Battle Effects </strong>table but also suffers d4+1 Wounds!</p><p>The Dungeon Master and players should work together to describe each character’s glorious scenes of bravery and carnage once the results are determined.</p><h3>Ammo &amp; Power Points</h3><p>If it’s important to track, each round a hero enters the fray and uses @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} the character expends some ammunition or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points}.</p><p>Arcane types and archers use 2d6 Power Points or arrows per round of Mass Battle. The DM should alter these numbers based on the character's chosen tactics, the length of each battle round, weapon types, or how long she thinks the hero has to recover or rearm between rounds.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":900000,"name":"Networking","type":"text","_id":"VqhLQlmMSZTL26BD","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Networking</h1><p>Pathfinders often need to find information or ask for favors. You can roleplay these encounters out, or you can allow them to use their skills in a \"macro\" sense — summing up hours of effort with a single roll.</p><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} is the nice way of interacting with one’s contacts. The flip side of the coin is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}. Either can get the job done but in slightly different ways, as shown below.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> When the player characters want to ask around town for favors or information.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Characters use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} to gather favors or information.</p><h3>Persuasion (The Nice Way)</h3><p>Characters use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} to socialize within their various social circles for information or favors. When used in this way, Persuasion isn’t a single exchange but several hours of networking, hobnobbing, carousing, drinks, gifts, bribes, or entertaining. This might represent time roaming a marketplace, a series of meetings with important people, or an evening of food and drink.</p><p>Success grants most of what the character wants, though it may take a while, cost some money, or require a favor in return. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} either gets more of whatever he was looking for, or at a lower cost.</p><p>Failure means the hero’s efforts are in vain. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means he’s cut off from that particular group for a while (up to the DM but typically about a week).</p><p><strong>Money Talks:</strong> You can catch more flies with honey than vinegar, the saying goes. A character with a little lucre to spread around gets a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{reroll} on her networking attempt, spending money on better bribes, gifts, or wining and dining her contacts.</p><p>The amount required is up to the GM, the location, and the nature of the contact(s) she interacts with. As a rule of thumb, use the expenses listed under <span>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{Carousing}</span> and modify as appropriate from there.</p><h3>Intimidation (The Not-so-Nice Way)</h3><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} can also be used to gather information, call in favors, or make demands, but it’s a little less savory.</p><p>Each attempt to \"work the streets\" takes several hours of threats and general unpleasantness, rousting the local populace for whatever the hero needs.</p><p>Success grants the character most of what she wants, though her victims might decide to get some payback later on. A raise means she gets more info, gets it faster, or her victims are too scared or otherwise preoccupied to plot revenge.</p><p>Failure means the bully doesn’t get anything useful. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means she ends the evening with a fat lip, black eye, or broken nose (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>). She can work her contacts again the next day, but they’re more likely to be waiting for her this time!</p><p><strong>Busting Heads:</strong> The bruiser can improve her odds by getting more violent or extreme than usual. This alienates her contacts for a week but grants her a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{reroll} on the Intimidation check.</p><p>This raises the stakes as well. A simple failure means the evening ends with <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>. A Critical Failure bears more serious consequences. The DM might break the action down to an actual encounter (which might be an ambush!). The hero might run afoul of the law, come back with two levels of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from Bumps &amp; Bruises, or her questions might trigger a deadly reaction from a more powerful enemy!</p><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Savage Measures</h2><p>Amiri the barbarian needs to locate a town official held for ransom by nefarious bandits. Her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} is better than her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, and she has the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Menacing]{Menacing} Edge, which adds +2 to Intimidation rolls. Time is tight so she decides to bust some heads. That gives her a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reroll]{reroll} as well. With the bonus and reroll she gets a success and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}. The barbarian finds the bandit hideout and learns how many goons guard the official.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1000000,"name":"Quick Chase Deck","type":"text","_id":"yJNXLqawiAJ9pc3p","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Quick Chase Deck</h1><h2>The Basics</h2><ul><li>Chases last five rounds in which participants try to make chase rolls to gather Chase TokeQns.</li><li>Each @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.IZ9YJamVRZdr4VVU]{Wild Cards} or each group of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.IZ9YJamVRZdr4VVU]{Extras} gets one Chase Card each round (more in some situations).</li><li>Choose one of the cards from your hand and place it face down in front of you.</li><li>Reveal cards, then in turn order follow the instructions on your card and take actions (including make chase rolls to collect Chase Tokens).</li><li>If the prey has most Chase Tokens at the end of the chase, they escape. Otherwise, the pursuers catch the prey and a regular encounter ensues.</li></ul><h2>Chase Cards</h2><div class=\"float-right\"><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/swade-assets/decks/chase-deck/diamonds-ace.webp\" width=\"250\" height=\"350\" /></div><h3>EACH CHASE CARD HAS...</h3><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">A Card Rank:</span> Participants act in Rank order, as usual.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">A Title:</span> This gives you narrative cues to help tell the story of the chase. Where possible, weave together the story using the cards each participant plays (the DM ultimately decides how the chase unfolds).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Chase Modifier:</span> Shown as a + or – modifier to your Chase roll this turn. If the card lists “Chase: N/A” you don’t get to make a Chase Roll this turn.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Card Effects:</span> Additional instructions that affect the Chase. If you choose to play the card, follow the additional instructions</li></ul><h2>Each Round…</h2><h3>DEAL CARDS</h3><ul><li>Each @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.IZ9YJamVRZdr4VVU]{Wild Cards} character or each group of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.IZ9YJamVRZdr4VVU]{Extras} gets a Chase Card. If a character is faster than her fastest opponent, she gets an extra Chase Card. If she’s twice as fast, she gets two extra Chase Cards.</li><li>This isn’t regular initiative, and these are not @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.b0BBoKY0d5GZgOVk]{Action Cards}, so @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Axdp8Ca1sJgKHL2z]{Edges} and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.pfTVXEOKs7z1wpPY]{Hindrances} affecting those things (like @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.ps5Osz7xoqBVXcZC]{Quick} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.qGrsNFrN9WBg8SVi]{Calculating}) have no effect in a chase.</li></ul><h3>CHOOSE CARDS</h3><ul><li>Choose one of these cards from your hand and place it face down in front of you.</li></ul><h3>REVEAL CARDS</h3><ul><li>Once everyone has chosen a face-down card, all participants reveal their chosen cards, flipping them face-up.</li><li>Starting with the Ace of Spades and counting down in regular Rank order, each participant takes their turn.</li></ul><h3>JOKERS</h3><ul><li>If the card you reveal is a Joker, choose an additional card from your hand as your active card (if you don’t have one, draw the top card of the Chase deck). Each Wild Card on the same side gets a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.RkejkA1MLhB8IeFe]{Benny}, as usual.</li><li>You act first this round and get +2 to all rolls.</li><li>At the end of the round, each player may keep one card in hand. Discard all the rest and reshuffle the deck</li></ul><h2>On Your Turn…</h2><h3>REGULAR ACTIONS</h3><ul><li>You can do most anything you can do in a regular encounter—make an attack, cast a spell, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.z8VbTEJUItMTSxNw]{Test} a foe, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.nPTGAWPmQjn0Ro3w]{Support} an ally.</li><li>The “relative” Range to a foe is 10 × the difference in Chase Tokens. If your character wants to magically heal an ally (a power that requires Touch), you must have the same number of Chase Tokens.</li><li>We ignore the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7h6MiBgFTEn0IUzu]{Running} and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.eoJwNHkiwpJSNbsc]{Unstable Platform} penalties in a Quick Chase.</li></ul><h3>CHASE TOKENS</h3><ul><li>You can use an action to try a “Chase” roll. This is an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.SzVzIV8ZxqKg3Oe3]{Athletics} roll (or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.MTvl27xnTDE3Dhjd]{Riding} if you’re mounted) at the bonus or penalty listed in the middle of your chosen Chase Card. If you’re successful, you get a Chase Token. If you get a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.gl7I9tF6bDt1r0c9]{raise}, you get two Chase Tokens!</li><li>Remember, Chase tokens determine range for attacks and also who ultimately wins the chase.</li></ul><h3>CONCLUDING THE CHASE</h3><ul><li>The chase ends at the end of the fifth round.</li><li>If the prey has the most Chase Tokens, they escape. If the pursuers have the most Chase Tokens, they catch the prey and a regular encounter ensues</li></ul><h2>important Keywords</h2><h3>COMPLICATION</h3><p>If your Chase Card has the Complication keyword, you cannot benefit from any bonuses from @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.nPTGAWPmQjn0Ro3w]{Support} this round.</p><h3>COUNTERATTACK</h3><p>If your Chase Card has the Counterattack keyword, any targets you attack this round gain the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.85G3lDFyOtkSn2tc]{Counterattack} Edge for this round and may fight back against you.</p><h3>ONGOING</h3><p>If your Chase Card has the Ongoing keyword, the effects on this card continue from the time the card is revealed, for as long as the card is in play.</p><h3>Narrative Chase Deck</h3><p>Remember to try to use the cards as a spur to tell the story of the chase (as we’ve done above), building the narrative with the DM and other players as the cards are played. Be creative using the card title, effects, or image as inspiration to add some flair to the chase. Remember also the DM has the final say in how the narrative plays out</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1100000,"name":"Quick Encounters","type":"text","_id":"Xhhn4JmF6MZLTQQj","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Quick Encounters</h1><p>Sometimes the Dungeon Master may want to quickly sum up an encounter rather than track every action round by round. \"Quick Encounters\" resolve these kinds of situations with good collaborative storytelling, tension, and risk.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use Quick Encounters when you're pressed for time, the group isn't as interested in tactical fights, or they do something the DM isn't prepared for, like infiltrating an enemy compound she hasn't yet detailed.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Characters make a skill roll based on the type of encounter and their goal and interpret the results narratively with the Dungeon Master.</p><h2>Encounter Types</h2><p>No @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Cards} are dealt in a Quick Encounter. Instead, the DM describes the scene, and then the players agree on a general plan and what their characters will do to resolve the situation.</p><p>Once all the players state their intent, they pick the skill that best represents their actions during the encounter and roll. Here are some common examples:</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Combat:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Crisis:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} (to calm bystanders), @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Repair]{Repair}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Heist:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Mission:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Battle]{Battle}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Trek:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}.</li></ul><p><strong>Modifiers:</strong> The DM should assign modifiers based on the situation. If the heroes greatly outnumber their opposition, pursue much slower prey, have prior experience with the obstacles in their path, or special equipment to deal with hazards, the roll might be made at +1 to +4.</p><p>Very difficult encounters, such as powerful foes (relative to the party), faster prey, or extreme conditions inflict a −1 to −4 penalty.</p><h3>Turn Order &amp; Critical Actions</h3><p>Players can go in whatever order they want in a Quick Encounter. This might be important if some of their actions are dependent on someone else's. In a heist, for example, the group might depend on a smooth-talker to gather information about the target's security before the thief attempts to break in. Similarly, a battle commander might need to send a scout across enemy lines before sending in a team to sabotage the enemy's war engine.</p><p>Resolve these kinds of actions in the order that makes sense, and allow those who come after to change their own plans as the situation changes.</p><p>If a critical task is failed, the DM must decide if it stops the encounter or simply complicates it (perhaps inflicting a penalty to everyone else's roll). In the heist example above, for example, maybe the charmer gets the information but tips off someone who adds extra sentries, inflicting a −2 penalty to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls. Likewise, the scout might find the war engine's location but the enemy moves the device shortly thereafter, adding the need for additional reconnaissance for the team of saboteurs.</p><p>These kinds of complications might also mean resolving the encounter in multiple stages instead of one roll as the heroes must react to the changing circumstances (see <strong>Staged Encounters,</strong> below).</p><h3>Staged Encounters</h3><p>Quick Encounters are typically a single die roll followed by some narration between the DM and the players. But some encounters might need additional rounds to better reflect the results or any new information or events that come to light.</p><p>If the heist to break into a wizard's tower and steal a powerful occult artifact goes badly, for example, the next stage might become a crisis when the tower suddenly bursts into supernatural flames. That might then lead to a combat encounter as an artifact in the wizard's study breaks and releases an angry djinn!</p><p>The beauty of staged encounters is their ability to handle complex problems when the constraints of time or larger narrative require a speedy resolution.</p><h2>Encounter Results</h2><p>Once each player has determined her skill and any modifiers, she rolls the dice and works with the Dungeon Master to narrate the details based on the total, the situation, and the other players' actions.</p><h3>Dangerous Encounters</h3><p>If a character fails his roll in a dangerous situation he takes a @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wound} (or d4 Wounds with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). If he's the driver of a vehicle, it takes a Wound (or d4 with a Critical Failure). Wounds may be @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#soak-rolls]{Soaked} as usual.</p><p>Success means the hero emerges with only <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises}</strong>, and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} means he escapes unscathed.</p><h3>Nonlethal Encounters</h3><p>If the encounter isn't physically dangerous, failure means the hero doesn't contribute to the party's overall success somehow. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means she suffers social stigma, loses or breaks a piece of vital equipment, is positively identified, or gets the wrong information. This likely means moving on to a second stage of the encounter as she deals with the fallout of her errors.</p><h3>Success &amp; Failure</h3><p>In general, narration and individual actions determine the success or failure of an encounter. If the smooth-talker can't learn the habits of the sentries, for example, and the DM decides this fact shuts down the operation rather than complicating it, the encounter fails. In other words, let the story tell the tale.</p><p>In a more dynamic situation such as combat, assume the group \"wins\" if there are at least as many total successes (one for each success and raise) as there are player characters. They get the information, drive off their foes, complete the mission, or avert (or escape) the crisis. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} rolls <em>don't</em> count as successes.</p><p>If there are fewer successes than player characters, they fail. Specifics are up to the Dungeon Master, but this might mean the party has to fall back or retreat from their foes, their prey escapes, they don't get the object or information they sought, they survive the crisis but can't save most of the bystanders, and so on.</p><p>If they can try again, the DM should \"reset\" the encounter with the new narrative so the group has to come up with a new plan. And of course, their foes are likely on to them now!</p><h3>Ammo &amp; Power Points</h3><p>Use the rules for <strong>Ammo &amp; Power Points</strong> under <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Mass Battles]{Mass Battles}</strong> for combat encounters if desired. Otherwise the player and DM can just decide what resources were consumed in the encounter.</p><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Night on the prowl</h2><p>Our heroes must break into a nobleman's library, steal an ancient book, and stop an evil conspiracy that threatens all of Eberron.</p><p>The group decides to play out the break-in as a Quick Encounter. The rogue plans to use @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} to break into the library, take the manuscript, then escape out the back. The bard supports her with a diversionary recital in the town square.</p><p>The DM decides the rogue's Thievery roll is at −2 to get into the library. The bard gets a success with his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Performance]{Performance} to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}. He adds +1 to his friend's roll.</p><p>The rogue manages a single success, but since there are two player characters and the rules say they need at least as many successes as there are characters, they fail.</p><p>The DM says three of the nobleman's guards are alerted by the pair's actions. The heroes can continue if they want, but the encounter is now more difficult (−2). The DM also says it's now a Dangerous Encounter as the guards are armed and nervous.</p><p>With the fate of Eberron at stake, the party agrees to press on. The rogue now uses @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} to avoid the guards. The bard disguises himself and knocks on the door, pretending to be lost! The DM tells the bard to use Performance for this Support roll. He rolls a 21! Both characters are successful, so the ancient manuscript is secured!</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1200000,"name":"Shadowing","type":"text","_id":"AyTGLaAhv2t76Nqu","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Shadowing</h1><p>On occasion, a hero may wish to follow another character—a \"mark\"—without being noticed, such as following a cultist back to a hidden temple or trailing a wealthy noble. This is not the same as a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Chases and Vehicles]{Chase}—though it might lead to one if the person being followed discovers he has unwanted attention.</p><p>Shadowing is an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} between the Shadower's @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth] skill @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed} by his opponent's @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice] roll. If the character is shadowing by other means of conveyance than walking, he uses the lower of his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth] or the appropriate \"maneuvering\" skill (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding], @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Piloting], etc.).</p><p>Should the shadower roll at least a 4 and win the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} he manages to follow unnoticed. If his roll wins the contest but is less than a 4, the character loses his mark but isn't seen. If the hero loses the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} with a 4 or better, his target is followed but detects him. If he loses both the contest and fails to score at least a 4 on his roll, then not only does he fail to keep shadowing, but his target gets a good look at him. If the shadower is discovered, he can continue to follow his mark, but it becomes an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{opposed roll} of his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice] versus his opponent's @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth] (or maneuvering Trait if lower) to not lose the target.</p><p>While in an urban enviroment, each roll covers roughly fifteen minutes of time, so it's possible several rolls may be required.</p><p>Finally, it's very hard to shadow a target who moves faster than the follower. If the opponent has a higher base @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{Pace}, the shadower suffers −2 to his Trait roll. If the mark's normal @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{Pace} is more than 50% higher than the follower (round up), the penalty is −4.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1300000,"name":"Social Conflict","type":"text","_id":"cZyKkaY4UZObP6iU","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Social Conflict</h1><p>Not every conflict is won by the blade. Successful oratory can topple nations.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Most social exchanges are a simple skill roll resisted by the appropriate Trait, such as @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} vs. @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Sprit}. For longer interactions, such as the back and forth of a long argument, negotiation, or a legal proceeding, the following system adds some drama and structure to each side's discussion. (The DM might use a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dramatic Tasks]{Dramatic Task} instead if the argument must be won in a hurry!)</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Characters make arguments back and forth over three rounds, roll their appropriate skills, then consult the <strong>Conflict Results</strong> table (below) to see how well they've influenced their audience.</p><h2>Conflict Rounds</h2><p>The conflict is broken down into three rounds of conversation, each focusing on a particular point (or a few highly connected points).</p><p>During each round, the player roleplays her character's argument and makes a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll opposed by the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Spirit} of whoever she's trying to convince. If a rival argues against her, the roll is opposed by his Persuasion instead.</p><p>Each success and raise by the petitioner grants her an \"Influence Token\" (rivals don't gain tokens, they just oppose the petitioner and keep her from gaining them).</p><p><strong>Modifiers:</strong> Persuasion rolls should be modified by the situation as the DM sees fit. A hero trying to convince a wizard of a fact within his field rolls the lowest of his Persuasion or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Occult]{Occult}. A particularly brilliant argument or impassioned roleplaying might add +1 to +4. An insult or <em>faux pas</em> inflicts a similar penalty.</p><p>Hindrances should also be considered. Convincing a jury that an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Outsider]{Outsider (Major)} is innocent of a crime, for example, might inflict a −2 penalty.</p><h3>Results</h3><p>At the end of the third round, the speaker looks up her total Influence Tokens on the <strong>Social Conflict Results</strong> table below.</p><p><strong>Trials:</strong> Run trials and similar conflicts from the accuser's point of view since they must usually prove the accused's guilt. If the player characters are the defenders, they oppose the prosecution and must keep them from gaining Influence Tokens with the judge (baron, king, warlord, etc.).</p><p>Accusers in a trial must get at least three tokens to convict. Lesser or greater results indicate the degree of punishment based on local customs and laws.</p><h2>Example: To Arms!</h2><p>The cleric must convince a baron to send troops to the defense of a neighboring fiefdom. The barony has warred with his neighbor for generations so the DM decides that's a −4 penalty to the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll.</p><p>Worse, she's opposed by his slimy wizard, who argues against the idea every round (he opposes her Persuasion rolls).</p><p>The cleric gets lucky the first round and gets a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}. That's two Influence Tokens. She fails on the second, but gets another raise in the third, for a total of four tokens.</p><p>The baron agrees but requires payment in land from his neighbor in return for sending part of his army to his rival's defense.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Social Conflict Results</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Tokens</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Results</th></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>Pleas are denied and negotiations fail. Discussions may reopen if new information is presented or favors are performed. In a trial, the defendant is acquitted.</td></tr><tr><td>1–3</td><td>The target isn't truly convinced, but provides the minimum amount of support possible. In a trial, the defendant receives the minimum penalty.</td></tr><tr><td>4–5</td><td>The arbiter is reasonably convinced or willing to help. He grants the aid requested, more or less, but only under certain conditions or in exchange for payment, tasks, favors, etc. The prosecution is successful with typical sentencing in a trial.</td></tr><tr><td>6+</td><td>The target is eager to help or agree. He gives more than expected in a negotiation or provides more support than requested. A defendant is convicted with the maximum penalty.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1400000,"name":"Travel","type":"text","_id":"dByq9K979yyOYWS6","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Travel</h1><p>Many epic tales feature trips across great expanses. A party may sail the Inner Sea or ride across the frontier of Varisia or navigate every district in Absalom.</p><p>Below are some guidelines to help you figure out how long these journeys take and what dramatic events might happen along the way.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> If it doesn’t matter how long the trip takes, skip all this. Narrate the journey, maybe do an <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Interludes]{Interlude}</strong>, and get to the next scene. If you need to know how long the trip takes, or want to insert an obstacle or encounter of some sort, use the information below as a guideline.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> The mode of travel determines how many miles the group makes per day.</p><h2>Travel Times</h2><p>The rates below assume reasonable terrain and weather. Difficult conditions can drastically decrease progress (or increase it in the case of sailing with strong winds).</p><table style=\"width:50%;margin:auto\"><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Average Travel Times</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Transport</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Miles/8 hour Day</th></tr><tr><td>Foot</td><td class=\"centered\">24</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Horse, Light]{Horse}</td><td class=\"centered\">30</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Cart]{Cart} (one beast)</td><td class=\"centered\">30</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Carriage]{Carriage}</td><td class=\"centered\">40</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Wagon, Light]{Wagon} (per beast)</td><td class=\"centered\">30</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Rowboat]{Rowboat}</td><td class=\"centered\">24</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Sailing Ship]{Sailing Ship}*</td><td class=\"centered\">30</td></tr><tr><td>Steam Ship*</td><td class=\"centered\">40</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Airship (Dirigible)]{Airship (Dirigible)}</td><td class=\"centered\">80</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Glider]{Glider}</td><td class=\"centered\">60</td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>*Sailing ships are greatly affected by currents and winds. Strong winds or currents in the right direction allow them to travel about 60 miles per day. Poor winds or going against the current reduce them to 20 miles per day or less.</em></p><h2>Encounters</h2><p>If an area is dangerous or lawless, draw a card from the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Deck} once per day (or even two or three times a day in particularly dangerous areas). A face card or higher represents an encounter, and the card suit can be used to determine the type.</p><p>Draw twice more if the card is a Joker and combine the results — such as Enemies and an Obstacle, or Strangers and Treasure.</p><p>Dungeon Masters are highly encouraged to customize encounters based on their setting.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Spades — Enemies:</span> Monsters, enemies, or hostile beasts bar the way. Perhaps they lie in ambush if it’s a popular path, waiting for the next band of unwary travelers.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Hearts — Strangers:</span> The group comes upon neutral or friendly nonplayer characters such as merchants, lost travelers, a guide, or even other adventurers.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Diamond — Treasure:</span> Somewhere along the way is something of value — a caravan eager for trade or a forgotten ruin with treasure— and guardians to protect it!</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Clubs — Obstacle:</span> The heroes encounter an obstacle of some kind and must figure out how to circumvent it. Some examples are a flooded river, a decaying rope bridge, a dangerous whirlpool, etc. The obstacle might be defended by creatures or enemies as well.</li></ul><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Cinderlands</h2><p>Our heroes are traveling across the frontier of Varisia, traversing the burning plains of the Cinderlands.</p><p>The DM draws a Jack of Clubs and decides the area is currently in the throes of an emberstorm— a dangerous black blizzard of dust and ash. This slows progress to a crawl for hours and makes the characters roll for @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from heat and the relentless dusty winds (see the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</strong> section).</p><p>The DM draws again later that day and gets a Queen of Spades. From an unseen burrow under the charred ground, an ankheg surfaces, hungry for fresh prey.</p><div><img src=\"modules/fvtt-swfp/assets/art/p166_Mokmurian_Fight.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ltavh0xcxs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules","color":"#008000"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"swade","systemVersion":"2.2.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1674606670277,"modifiedTime":1675702845454,"lastModifiedBy":"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf"},"_id":"QVfRRo6necYsIcWp","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf":3}}
{"name":"Magic Items","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Magic Items","type":"text","_id":"yeOARvAF10FttRoJ","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div class=\"chapter-heading\"><h1>Magic items</h1><figure class=\"chapter-number\"><figcaption>Savage Eberron</figcaption></figure></div><div><p>   </p><p class=\"drop-cap\">This section contains descriptions, prices, and abilities for magic items found on Eberron. Some are rare, possibly one-of-a-kind relics sought after by great heroes and nefarious evils. Others are relatively common items sold in city markets, found in monster lairs, or wielded by enemies. Such magical treasures are a boon to all Pathfinders as they quest across the wild lands of Eberron.</p><h1 class=\"wide\">Using magic items</h1><p>Each type of item on the following pages tells you how it’s used, but there are a few common rules between them:</p><ul><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">Active Powers are Actions:</span> An item that requires a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait roll} is an action unless it says otherwise. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} means the user takes @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} (and loses a charge if the item has them).<br />Putting on a simple item of clothing such as a ring  or a cap is a limited free action if it's handy (DM's call).</p></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Cursed items:</span> If an item’s description indicates it is cursed, it cannot be removed except with a successful <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Dispel]{dispel}</em> with the Disenchant modifier. A caster only gets one chance to do so per item, however! If failed, she can’t try to dispel that item again until she increases her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Edges and Abilities:</span> If an item grants an @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edge} or Monstrous Ability and the wielder already has that Edge, it grants the improved version (if there is one).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Minor &amp; Major Powers:</span> Some items grant minor or major powers using the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{powers}. A minor power automatically activates with the effect of a standard success, and a major power activates with the effect of a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} (no Trait roll is made). Unless the item says otherwise, this is an action and the effect lasts for the power’s full Duration and cannot be maintained.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Stacking:</span> If two sources would increase a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Trait}, use only the highest modifier (effects don’t stack). Increases to a Trait from a magic item’s effects don’t count for determining @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Trait Advancements}. They do affect secondary statistics like @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} or Toughness, however.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Multiple items:</span> A character can only wear one magic item in each location (head, eyes, shoulders, neck, chest, belt, wrists, hands, feet). Putting on a second necklace or a second belt, for example, has no effect. The exception to this rule is rings. A character can wear two rings and benefit from both magical effects.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Daily Power:</span> Items that may only be used a certain number of times per day recharge at dawn.</li></ul><h3>Enemies with Magic Items</h3><p>Enemy characters and monsters equipped with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Enchantments]{enchanted} and magical items have the bonuses conferred by those items built into their profiles.</p><p>An evil knight wearing @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Plate Armor]{plate armor} @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Enchantments]{enchanted} with the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aegis] enchantment, for example, might have a Toughness of 12(5), where the plate armor's bonus of +4 has already been increased by the Aegis enchantment's +1.</p><h2>Detect Magic</h2><p>In the magically-charged world of Eberron, any character with an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Arcane Backgrounds &amp; Edges]{Arcane Backgrounds} can sense magical or divine auras within 5” (10 yards), unless they are magically concealed. This is an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Actions]{action}.</p><p>Detecting magic at a greater range or gaining specific information requires the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{detect arcana}</em> spell, which can also be used to reveal items or beings protected by <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Detect/Conceal Arcana]{conceal arcana}.</em> </p><p>Identifying magic items requires a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Common Knowledge]{Common Knowledge} roll for everyday items like healing potions. More obscure items require an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana] roll. Sucess knows the basic tale or legend, while a raise provides additional insight into their reputed abilities. These rolls can be made once a day with a cumulative +1 bonus to the roll.</p></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Purchasing Magic Items","type":"text","_id":"KQ9vFjQm0DTTTzBp","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Purchasing Magic Items</h1><p>Most towns have an apothecary shop with a few potions for sale, a few local merchants reselling magical items, or even individuals looking to sell off devices they no longer need.</p><p>When the adventurers want to buy magic items, roll on the table below to see what's available that week (or month if it's a particularly isolated or low-magic area).</p><p>The table has three entries:</p><p><strong>Potions &amp; Scrolls:</strong> Half the items are potions and half are scrolls, rounding in favor of potions. Roll randomly from the tables on the following pages.</p><p><strong>Healing:</strong> This tells you how many @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Potion of Healing]{potions of healing}, ubiquitous across Eberron, are available from various vendors for 150 gp each. This is in addition to any healing offered by @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-lore.House Jorasco] or other available services.</p><p><strong>Other Items:</strong> This tells you how many other magical treasures may be found or purchased in the settlement. If the result is positive, roll on the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-tables.Other Item Categories]{Other Item} table to determine the category, then roll on the appropriate subtable. If the category is a Wondrous Item, the DM chooses which item is available.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"4\">Magic Items availability</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading\">Type</th><th class=\"sub-heading\"><p>Potions &amp;<br />Scrolls*</p></th><th class=\"sub-heading\"><p>Healing<br />Potions</p></th><th class=\"sub-heading\"><p>Other<br />Items*</p></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Village</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d6−2</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>1d4</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d4−2</p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Town</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d6−1</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>1d4+1</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d6−2</p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>City</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d6</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>1d6</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d6−1</p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Large City</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d6+1</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>1d6+1</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>d6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"dark\" colspan=\"2\">Other Item Categories</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading\" style=\"text-align:center\">d20</th><th class=\"sub-heading\" style=\"text-align:center\">Type</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>1–11</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Armor &amp; Weapons</p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>12–13</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Rings</p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>14–16</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Rods &amp; Staves</p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>17–18</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Wands</p></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>19–20</p></td><td style=\"text-align:center\"><p>Wondrous Items</p></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Purchasing Items</h3><p>Exactly where the items are available is up to the Dungeon Master. Common or relatively inexpensive items might be for sale at a shop or merchant's stall. Rare or expensive items might require finding an elusive seller or completing some task in addition to the cost in gold.</p><h3>Exotic Items</h3><p>A hero might seek out a specific magic item rather than waiting for it to appear at random. In that case, the character can either commission the item with a down payment (usually half its total cost in gold pieces), or perform a task or quest of some sort.</p><p>At the Dungeon Master's discretion, finding someone to make or sell such items might be an adventure on its own, or a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{Networking} roll with a penalty determined by the item and the size of the settlement.</p><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Shopping in Sandpoint</h2><p>The party is about to set off on a quest to defeat an orc warlord. They decide to stock up on potions and other magical items before entering the warlord's domain.</p><p>The adventurers are in a town, so the DM rolls on the Potions &amp; Scrolls column and determines there are three potions and two scrolls. She rolls randomly on the potions and scrolls tables to see which specific brews are available.</p><p>Next, she rolls for Healing Potions and gets a total of 3. The party scoops up all of them.</p><p>Then she rolls on the Other Items column and gets a 2. She rolls a d20 twice and gets a ring and a rod.</p><p>The Ring table gives her a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Ring of Protection]{ring of protection}. She decides it's for sale at a second-hand merchant shop in town.</p><p>The Rods table results in a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Rod of Negation]{rod of negation}. That's a fairly rare item, so the DM tells the group it's owned by a retired mage who will only sell it for a favor. They travel to the mage, who agrees to sell the rod at half value if the party will chase away a dangerous group of bugbears that have moved into her favorite herb-gathering spot.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/crafting.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Crafting Magic Items","type":"text","_id":"GBxje8099lwUSA4c","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Crafting Magic Items</h1><p>Characters with the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Artificer)]{Artificer Edge} can imbue their powers into @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.6 Arcane Devices]{arcane devices} for later use or give them to their allies. This ties up their own @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{Power Points}, however, and such creations are temporary.</p><p>With enough time and resources, however, an artificer can create more permanent items of wonder, and best of all he doesn’t have to tie up his own Power Points in the process!</p><h2>The Crafting Process</h2><p>After each week spent Crafting, the artificer makes an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana} roll for each item he’s working on. A success makes 1,000 gp worth of progress toward its completion, and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} makes 2,000 gp progress.</p><p>If the roll is failed, no progress is made on that item but the crafter may try again the following week. With a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}, a mishap loses the creator 500 gp worth of progress!</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Ammunition:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Arrow]{Arrows}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Sling Bullets]{sling stones}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Bolt]{bolts}, or other types of ammunition are enchanted in batches of 12 at a time. If it can be recovered, each projectile has a 50% chance of remaining intact once fired.</li></ul><h2>Requirements</h2><img class=\"float-right\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-warforged.webp\" /><p>A character can create any of the items listed in this book if she has the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Arcane Background (Artificer)]{Artificer} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Craft Arcane Device]{Craft Arcane Device} edges, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Downtime]{Downtime}, the item to be enchanted, access to a workshop, and an artificers kit or access to a workshop.</p><p><strong>The Item:</strong> Only items of quality craftsmanship are typically given permanent @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.4 Enchantments]{enchantments}. Armor, shields, weapons, and other permanent items must be of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Masterwork]{masterwork} quality.</p><p>Potions, scrolls, and wands have no additional cost, but other permanent items should be exceptional examples of their type, and cost 50% more than usual.</p><p><strong>Requirements:</strong> The artificer must expend half the cost of the item in various components to begin the creation process. This might include precious gems, metals, powders, oils, or other rare items represented by the listed gold value listed. The DM must also decide if the item being created requires any unique components that cannot simply be found in the environs or purchased in the setting’s markets. This usually requires a quest, heist, or deal with powerful or shady individuals, and can often turn into an adventure of its own.</p><p><strong>Artificer’s Kit or Workshop:</strong> An artificer can enchant one item at a time as long as she has her artificer’s kit, but subtracts 2 from her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Arcana]{Arcana} roll without at least a Standard Workshop (see the table below). Better equipment, tools, and other resources remove this penalty or grant the crafter a bonus, and allow her to work on more items at once.</p><p>The table below shows the typical cost per week to use a workshop, the number of items that can be crafted there each week, and the size town where they may usually be found.</p><p>have any powers and materials listed in the item’s Craft entry. Materials are precious gems, metals, powders, oils, or other rare components represented by the listed gold value listed (typically half the item’s value if purchased from others).</p><p><strong>Workshop:</strong> A workshop's availability, the cost per week to use it, and the number of items that can be crafted each week is listed on the chart below.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"5\">Crafting in a Workshop</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading\">Workshop</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Bonus</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">No. of Items</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Cost per Week</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">Settlement Size</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Simple</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">–2</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Village or Town</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Standard</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Town or City</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Advanced</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">+1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">100 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Large City</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Grand</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">+2</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">Metropolis</td></tr></tbody></table><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Lini's Gift</h2><p>Lini the druid wants to craft @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Slippers of Spider Climbing]{slippers of spider climbing} for Merisiel the rogue. She has access to a standard workshop and can create two things at once, so she decides to make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Potion of Healing, Major]{Major Potion of Healing} at the same time.</p><p>The slippers have a cost of 4,800. The potion’s crafting cost is 300. Lini gathers 2,550 gp worth of materials to get started.</p><p>After a week’s work, she rolls and gets a success. That’s 1,000 gp worth of progress toward her slippers. Now she rolls for the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Potion of Healing, Major]{Major Potion of Healing}. She’s successful, and since its cost is less than 1,000 gp, it’s finished and ready to use.</p><p>Lini continues on the slippers the next week and gets a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} on her roll. That’s a total of 2,000 gp progress, for a total of 3,000 gp over the two weeks. The third and fourth weeks she gets another success, giving her another 1,000 gp worth of progress. The slippers are finished and she gifts them to her friend— who she warns only to use them for the good of the Wardens of the Wood!</p><img style=\"border:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\" src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/making-potions.webp\" /></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Enchantments","type":"text","_id":"GNXP2qYrnBS868wg","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Enchantments</h1><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Masterwork] armor, shields, and weapons can be enchanted with the qualities listed below. Each item can hold five points worth of enchantments. The number of points a particular quality takes is listed in parentheses after its name.</p><p><strong>Note:</strong> An item cannot be enchanted with the same quality more than once.</p><p><strong>Named Items:</strong> The named magic armor, shields, and weapons named in the rest of this chapter can’t have additional enchantments.</p><p></p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h2 class=\"qualities\">Armor &amp; Shield Enchantments</h2><p><span class=\"red-label\">Aegis (1)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> Increases the protective bonus of the armor by +1.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Animated(3)</span> <strong>Shield only.</strong> Once per encounter, an animated shield can be loosed to defend its wielder. For the next three rounds, it hovers near its owner, following him if he moves and granting its Parry and cover bonus as usual without needing to be held. Its type still applies for purposes of Armor Interference or Restriction.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 10,000gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Arrow Deflection (1)</span> <strong>Shield only.</strong> Ranged Attacks against the bearer suffer an additional −1 penalty, regardless of the attacker's position (front, rear, etc).</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Balanced (1)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> The armor is very well balanced decreasing the Min Str by one die type (d4 minimum).</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Burning (2)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> On command, the wearer if this armor to burst into flames, gaining <em>damage field</em> with the Damage modifier. A fire elemental is bound to this armor with Khyber dragonshard making it smolder with a reddish glow.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 58,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Deflecting (1)</span> <strong>Shield only.</strong> Increase the shield's Parry bonus increased by +1.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 4,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Determination (2)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> A shield or armor with this property helps its owner fight on against seemingly impossible odds. She gains the Nerves of Steel Edge when wearing the armor or bearing the shield.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 60,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Earthbound (1)</span> Earthbound armor grants resistance to all sorts of Push attacks from abilities such as Knockback, powers such as havoc, and the Push action. An earth elemental is bound to this weapon with Khyber dragonshard most often set in the pommel of the weapon, or near the head of a hafted weapon.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Energy Resistance (1)</span> Grants Elemental Resistance against a single energy type, determined at creation, to a piece of armor or a shield. Damage from that source is reduced by 4 when the armor is worn, and the hero adds +4 when resisting any effect tied to that element. These armors have a Khyber dragonshard with an appropriate elemental bound into them.</p><div><p>A leather jerkin of energy resistance (Cold), for example, helps its wearer avoid Fatigue from exposure (see Hazards) and damage from any attack with a Trapping of cold, ice, frost, etc.</p></div><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Equestrian (1)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> This suit of armor helps its wearer remain mounted and in control of his mount. She adds +2 to Riding rolls.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,750 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Etherealness (2)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> On command, the wearer of this armor becomes ethereal, gaining minor  <em>intangibility</em>. The character can remain ethereal for as long as desired, but once he returns to normal, he cannot use this ability again for 24 hours.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 49,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Fortification (2)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> Fortified armor is more likely to turn away a lethal blow. The wearer gains a free Reroll on Soak rolls.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 5,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Glamered (0)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> Upon command, a piece of glamered armor changes shape and appearance to assume the form of a normal piece of clothing. The armor retains all of its properties when it is so disguised.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 900 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Mighty Aegis (3)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> Increases the protective bonus of the armor by +2. Note: Does not stack with the Aegis enchantment.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 10,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Reflecting (4)</span> <strong>Shield only.</strong> The shield's surface is completely reflective. Once per day, the wielder can reflect any power that affects her by making a Spirit roll (at −2 if the casting roll got a raise). If successful the caster suffers the full effects of the power as if he had been the original target.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 16,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Righteous (2)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> Armor with this property is often engraved or enameled with religious symbols. Once per day, as a limited action, the wearer may increase his Size by +3 Each increase in Size grants the target a one step increase to Strength and 1 point of Toughness. This lasts for 10 rounds. Righteous armor does not work for Evil creatures.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 27,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Spell Resistance (4)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> The wearer gains the benefits of minor arcane protection.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 16,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Waterborn (2)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> On command, the wearer of this armor gains the Aquatic ability. The character can maintain this ability as long as they are in water and as long as they desire. Once they deactivate it or return to the surface, she cannot use the ability again for 24 hours. A water elemental is bound to this armor with Khyber dragonshard giving the it a milky blue-white appearance.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 34,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Whirlwind (3)</span> <strong>Armor only.</strong> On command, the wearer of this armor gains the Flight (12\") ability. This ability lasts for one hour, and cannot be used again for 24 hours. An air elemental is bound to this armor with Khyber dragonshard giving the it an almost translucent appearance.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 53,000 gp.</p></aside><p></p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h2 class=\"qualities\">Weapon Enchantments</h2><p><span class=\"red-label\">Accurate (1)</span> The weapon grants the user +1 in the skill required to use it ( Fighting, Shooting, or Athletics).</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 4,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Allying (1)</span> <strong>Melee Weapon only.</strong> The weapon grants the wielder the Formation Fighter Edge while it is being used.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 4,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">bane (1)</span> When used against a specific type of creature (dwarf, goblin, elemental, etc), a bane weapon has +2 AP and its damage die increases one type.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Brutal Strike (2)</span> The weapon counts as a Heavy Weapon.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Damaging (1)</span> The weapon's Damage increases by +1.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Dancing (4)</span> <strong>Melee Weapon only.</strong> <span class=\"fontstyle0\">The wielder can command the weapon to dance once per encounter as a limited free action. It animates immediately, attacking as a character for up to five rounds. It uses its master’s Action Card and attack skill, and rolls two of its normal damage dice for damage. The weapon can fly at Pace 10 and counts as an ally for the Gang Up bonus.</span> </p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 20,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Distance (1)</span> <strong>Range Weapon only.</strong> Decrease any Range penalties by one when using this weapon.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Dueling (2)</span> <strong>One-handed Melee Weapon only.</strong> While drawn, a dueling weapon grants the character the Quick Edge. The bearer also gets a free Reroll when attempting a Called Shot on a held item.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 14,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Elemental Energy (1)</span> The weapon causes damage with an energy Trapping—acid, cold, electricity, fire, or sonic (chosen by creator). Most often a Khyber dragonshard is set in the pommel of the weapon, or near the head of a hafted weapon.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Finesse (2)</span> <strong>One-handed Melee Weapon only.</strong> This enchantment can only be applied one handed weapons. The weapon provides a +1 bonus to Parry. An air elemental is bound to this weapon with Khyber dragonshard most often set in the pommel of the weapon, or near the head of a hafted weapon.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 11,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">huntsman (1)</span> A huntsman weapon helps its wielder locate and capture quarry. While it's in hand, he adds +1 to Survival (Tracking) rolls.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 4,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">keen (1)</span> The weapon is exceptionally sharp, giving it Armor Piercing +2.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Luminous (1)</span> The weapon casts light in a Medium Blast Template. The user activates the illumination with her will as a free action.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 2,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Mighty Accuracy (3)</span> The weapon grants the user +2 in the skill required to use it ( Fighting, Shooting, or Athletics). <strong>Note:</strong> Does not stack with Accurate.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 15,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Mighty Cleaving (2)</span> <strong>Two-handed Melee Weapon only.</strong> The user gains the Sweep Edge.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 10,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Quickness (3)</span> If a melee weapon, the user gains the Frenzy Edge. A ranged weapon increases its Rate of Fire by 1, or reduces its Reload time by one action. User's choice for weapons that can be used either way.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 16,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Returning (1)</span> <strong>Thrown Weapon only.</strong> The weapon returns to its user's hand at the end of her turn.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Throwing (1)</span> The weapon can be thrown using Athletics (throwing). Its Range is 4/8/16.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 3,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Vicious (2)</span> <strong>Melee Weapon only.</strong> If the wielder hits with a raise, he must make a Vigor roll or be Shaken, but his Damage increases by +4 (in addition to any Bonus Damage).</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 5,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">Vorpal (5)</span> <strong>Bladed Weapon only.</strong> A vorpal weapon ignores penalties for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0]{Called Shots} to the head. Anyone Incapacitated by it is decapitated!</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 50,000 gp.</p><p><span class=\"red-label\">wounding (2)</span> The weapon increases the Damage die one step. An earth elemental is bound to this weapon with Khyber dragonshard most often set in the pommel of the weapon, or near the head of a hafted weapon.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong> 7,000 gp.</p></aside><p></p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/people/artificer-infusing-armor.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Wondrous Items Table","type":"text","_id":"IxyCY6aXdRyYxVfR","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Wondrous Magical Items</h1><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"3\">Wondrous Items Table</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"3\"><p>This is a catch-all category for anything that doesn't fall into the other groups. Anyone can use a wondrous item, and unless otherwise stated, activating a wondrous item is an action.</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Name</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Cost</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Rarity</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Belts)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Chest)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Eyes)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Hands)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Head)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Neck)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Shoulders)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Slotless)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Items (Wrists)</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"Dragonshard Items Table","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Dragonshard Items</h1><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"3\">Dragonshard Items Table</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"3\"><p>The dragonmarked houses are vitally important to Khorvaire's society and economy. Their artificers thus have both a driving need to develop methods of enhancing their power and the economic resources to do so, which has resulted in a proliferation of magic items designed to harness and enhance the power of a dragonmark heir. These items range from highly specialized devices that increase the effects of a particular mark—such as the Speaking Stone of House Sivis—to general-purpose tools that are useful to anyone who bears a mark, such as the Dragonshard Reservoir. This section begins with a look at general items that can be used by anyone with a dragonmark, followed by channeling rods, greater focus items, and quori embedded shards.</p><p>Most dragonshard items require the user to possess a specific dragonmark, such as the least Mark of Finding. Such items work by enhancing the character's natural abilities, and as a result a character who does not possess the proper innate ability cannot employ the Use Magic Device skill to bypass these restrictions.</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Name</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Cost</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Rarity</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"3\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wondrous Belts</span></th></tr><tr><td> </td><td style=\"text-align:center\">0 gp</td><td>Common</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_id":"62dIRln1iU93Aw1g"}],"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ltavh0xcxs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules","color":"#008000"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"swade","systemVersion":"2.2.3","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1674761644457,"modifiedTime":1675702845478,"lastModifiedBy":"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf"},"_id":"j9tCjkRDM3sbyAxm","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf":3}}
