l8fQfcwi3]{intangibility}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.4blgE58lNmwLNvFu]{mind wipe}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.7ouX6M14F4XTBnvE]{planar Binding}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.G6DfUlcmZ3CTt4PA]{Plane Shift}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.TpoRRHModi8fe8mw]{puppet}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.3lQAmVpWq0N99ALe]{ward}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.FADQSqpXlioUX8lP]{zombie}</em></p><p><strong>Heroic Powers:</strong> <em>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.7vEypESjFOGQX3cG]{animate war tree}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.aRumBWgybWwDmjdn]{resurrection}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.OQNwG8oyOYksAnbN]{time stop}</em></p><p><strong>Legendary Powers: </strong><em>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.6Uc9jO8l7jzEZoP8]{mystic intervention}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.yJBvKufi1V2sWiLf]{wish}</em></p></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\"><em>ALCHEMICAL POWERS:</em></span><em> Alchemists</em></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\"><em>BACKLASH:</em></span><em> When an alchemist rolls a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO]{Critical Failure} on a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.VUBQPz9aKtoxpMhY]{Science} roll, the Dungeon Master rolls on the Dynamic Backlash table to see what happens.</em></li></ul><h3><em>Heading</em></h3><p><em>XXXX</em></p><h3><em>Trappings</em></h3><p><em>XXXX</em></p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.Q7sPGiMfmcjMzVx8"}},"_id":"liNfCdBp6ITgLsq1"}],"_stats":{"systemId":"swade","systemVersion":"2.2.5","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":null,"modifiedTime":1676930949887,"lastModifiedBy":"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf"},"_id":"F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf":3}}
{"name":"Setting Rules","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Setting Rules","type":"text","_id":"2988qtdsJ4heXv7H","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Setting Rules</h1><p><cite>Savage Worlds</cite> range from dark and gritty detective tales to cinematic epics to political thrillers. These rules provide a great framework for anything you want to do, but adding the right Setting Rules really brings the world and the action to life!</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Setting Rules accommodate different play styles and help emulate genres or tropes of established settings—like those of a book or movie that’s inspired you. This lets you easily tweak the rules to make a gritty crime drama more bloody, or an adventurous space romp more fun—all without changing the core of the game.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Each Setting Rule is different. Some apply during @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Character Creation Summary]{character creation} while others tweak @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Combat]{Combat}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{skills}, or even @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny} use in some way.</p><aside class=\"gray-slate\"><h2>Setting Rule Checklist</h2><p>Use the following list to choose the Setting Rules for your game, coloring in the dots so everyone in the group knows which rules are in effect.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Born A Hero]{Born A Hero}:</span> Player characters ignore @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Rank} requirements for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edges} during @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Character Creation Summary]{character creation}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Born from War]{Born from War}:</span> Player characters start with a free @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Background Edge} that must be tied to their backstory experiences during the Last War during @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Character Creation Summary]{character creation}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Conviction]{Conviction}:</span> Heroes gain Conviction Tokens that can be used to add a d6 to all @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Traits} and @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage]{damage} rolls for one round. Conviction is awarded for triumph (overcoming a great obstacle important to that character), and tragedy (a personal setback, death of a friend or ally, etc). Conviction effects may be extended by spending a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Creative Combat]{Creative Combat}:</span> A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} on a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test} allows the character to roll on a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Creative Combat]{special table} that grants additional effects.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dumb Luck]{Dumb Luck}:</span> Characters may spend a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny} after a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure}, allowing another chance for success in unusual and unexpected ways.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash}:</span> A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll forces the player to roll on a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Dynamic Backlash]{special table} with various chaotic results.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fanatics]{Fanatics}:</span> Enemy thugs take the damage for their masters.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fast Healing]{Fast Healing}:</span> Characters make natural @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.3 Healing]{Healing} rolls once per day instead of every five days, and recover a level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps &amp; Bruises} every four hours instead of every day.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Glory and Infamy]{Glory and Infamy}:</span> Glory or Infamy track the reputation of the Player Characters. As it increases they are awarded with benefits from those that respect the reputation of the character.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Gritty Damage]{Gritty Damage}:</span> Whenever a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} takes a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Wound}, roll on the <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Injury Table]{Injury Table}</strong> and apply the results immediately.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hard Choices]{Hard Choices}:</span> The DM has no @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Bennies}. When player spend bennies they go to the DM.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Heroes Never Die]{Heroes Never Die}:</span> Heroes and named villains rarely actually die but return in some way after being defeated.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.High Adventure]{High Adventure}:</span> Players can spend a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny} to gain a one time use of a Combat @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edge}.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.More Skill Points]{More Skill Points}:</span> Player characters in advanced or specialized settings start with 15 skill points.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.No Power Points]{No Power Points}:</span> Those with arcane backgrounds don’t track Power Points but instead subtract half the listed Power Point cost (round up) from their skill roll to activate the ability. Powers may be maintained as desired at a −1 penalty to all further @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} rolls.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Unarmored Hero]{Unarmored Hero}:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} without armor add +2 to their @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#soak-rolls]{Soak} rolls.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wound Cap]{Wound Cap}:</span> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} never suffer more than four @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Damage Effects]{wounds} from a single hit.</li></ul></aside></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Born a Hero","type":"text","_id":"yrKUqugcSqCDKGHU","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Born A Hero</h1><p>Heroes may ignore the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Rank} qualifications for @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edges} during @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Character Creation Summary]{character creation}. They must still meet any other Require­ments as usual. The usual rules for Rank Requirements apply afterward.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Born from War","type":"text","_id":"K7kOJqtra9HtFy0p","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Born from War</h2><p>Every character starts with one free @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Background Edge} or @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Professional Edge}. This edge must be tied to the story of your characters experiences during her life in the Last War.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Conviction","type":"text","_id":"2ACbJ6Gy6La0KFJp","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Conviction</h1><p>Conviction is a special award granted when a character experiences a great victory or catastrophic misfortune. If possible, use a themed token to note the award; maybe a Marshal’s Badge for <cite>Deadlands</cite>, a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Benny} of a different color, a toy doubloon for <cite>50 Fathoms</cite>, and so on.</p><p>Conviction can be spent to add a d6 to all a character’s @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Trait} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Dealing Damage]{damage} totals until the beginning of her next @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Actions]{turn}. This die can @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Ace}, and its result is added to the final total.</p><p>Conviction tokens aren’t @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Bennies} and can’t be used as such. They <em>are</em> kept between sessions, however.</p><p>A character may maintain Conviction from round to round by spending a Benny (at the start of his turn, before it runs out). Once Conviction lapses, however, the effect ends.</p><h3>Triumph And Tragedy</h3><p>Conviction is granted for personal triumph and tragedy, drawing on a character’s entire background, including—but not limited to—his @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.MAcvE2WNI1eEy4R8]{Edges} and @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.71p7h2rERyAUfpmt]{Hindrances}.</p><p>Savage settings may also grant Conviction for certain world-specific actions or events.</p><p><strong>Triumph:</strong> Characters gain Conviction when they overcome significant obstacles core to their overall goals and motivations. This might mean defeating powerful enemies, saving a true love, or overcoming some great mystery or problem.</p><p>The victory should be an achievement over and above the usual. A vampire hunter in <cite>Rippers</cite> shouldn’t get Conviction every time he kills a vampire, for example, but he might when he wipes out an entire coven or slays a powerful master vamp­ire. A super hero might gain Conviction when she saves her true love from a death trap or the clutches of a powerful villain. She wouldn’t earn it just because her boyfriend is in a dangerous encounter.</p><p><strong>Tragedy:</strong> Some of the most interesting heroes of fiction, film, and legend spend as much time battling their personal demons as they do fighting their foes. Eventually these same issues give them strength as they work through their grief or overcome obstacles to rise once more against the challenges they face.</p><p>When a character experiences a significant personal loss or destructive event, and the DM feels it’s appropriate, he gains Conviction. The death of a loved one or close friend (including a party member he was close to), losing an important job, giving in to harmful character flaws and vices, being removed from a case or quest, or getting framed for a crime are all classic examples of heroic tragedy.</p><p>These might happen in the course of the game, but players should also proactively suggest their own ideas to the Dungeon Master. Consider your hero’s backstory and occasionally look for ways to do what your favorite authors do to their characters—torture them! Think about what’s important to them and threaten it or take it away. Most of the time this should be done as a quick narrative tale or a scene with a little interaction and roleplaying so as not to distract from the main campaign or the other players’ time, but occasionally it might inspire a side-trek or adventure to regain—or avenge!—whatever was lost.</p><p>Note that earning Conviction for harmful behavior is motivation for players in a game to occasionally spotlight their character’s dark side. It is not an endorsement or rationalization of poor conduct in the real world.</p><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Red's Rage</h2><p>Emily is Red, a fighter in a fantasy campaign. She has “anger management issues” but didn’t take the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-hindrances.Mean]{Mean} Hindrance because she’s had her problem under control for a year or so. But it’s a fun part of her backstory and Emily loves roleplaying constantly managing her character’s temper.</p><p>Unfortunately, Red and her constant ally Gabe failed in their last adventure. Emily decides this is a good time for Red to go on a rampage. She narrates a story about going into town and terrorizing everyone in sight with her surly attitude. During the course of a “bad day,” she breaks a window, turns over an apple cart, and even insults a friar’s mule!</p><p>The DM loves Emily’s story and awards her a point of Conviction. In the game, Red is barred from the local tavern, has to pay for all the damage she caused, and is refused help by the friar (the town’s only healer!) until she performs some act of penance (a new quest!)</p><p>More importantly, Emily told a story about her heroine’s tragic flaw—and has a point of Conviction to carry her through the next chapter of her quest.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Creative Combat","type":"text","_id":"CaRakOoWuzrXz04O","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Creative Combat</h1><p>Creative Combat is an optional rule a Dungeon Master may allow to give @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests} more varied results. It’s especially useful if a group prefers a slightly more pulpy or swashbuckling feel.</p><p><strong>When to Use These Rules:</strong> Use these rules when you want Tests to have a little more variety.</p><p><strong>The Basics:</strong> Roll on the table when a character Tests a foe with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}.</p><h2>Tests of Mettle</h2><p>Creative Combat occurs only when the game is in rounds. A regular success on a <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}</strong> works as usual. If a character succeeds with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, she can decide if she wants to take the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} result or roll on the Creative Combat table. She can decide if she wants to make her foe @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted or Vulnerable} after she rolls on the table.</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> @Compendium[savage-eberron-bestiary.savage-eberron-bestiary.Merisiel]{Merisiel} battles an ogre on the edge of a cliff. She feints the clumsy brute and gets a raise. The DM rolls on the Creative Combat table and gets a Setback. She decides the ogre has to make an @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} roll or fall off the cliff. Merisiel makes the creature Distracted so it has a greater chance of failure!</p><p><br /></p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Creative Combat</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">2d6</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Result</th></tr><tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Second Wind:</strong> The foe hesitates, giving your hero time to catch her breath. She may remove a level of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} or a @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wound} (her choice). If she has neither, the enemy is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and she receives a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}.</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td><strong>Inspiration:</strong> Fate favors the bold. The clever hero receives a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}.</td></tr><tr><td>4–5</td><td><strong>Double Whammy:</strong> The target is both @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted and Vulnerable}.</td></tr><tr><td>6–8</td><td><p><strong>Shaken:</strong> The foe is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}.</p></td></tr><tr><td>9–10</td><td><p><strong>Setback:</strong> The target suffers a setback of some sort. She might fall off a ledge, lose the confidence of her minions (who then desert her), take a rash but foolish action, or simply lose her next turn as she attempts to recover from whatever situation she finds herself in.</p></td></tr><tr><td>11</td><td><p><strong>Insight:</strong> The hero gains insight into the target’s nature. Once during this encounter, she may add +d6 to any @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait} roll made to directly @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Attacks]{attack}, affect, or @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage]{damage} the same foe.</p></td></tr><tr><td>12</td><td><p><strong>Seize the Moment:</strong> After the hero resolves this turn, she immediately gets an entire additional turn. This includes @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#movement]{movement} as well! She may use the turn to go on @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold} if she wishes.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/climb.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"Dumb Luck","type":"text","_id":"6IBGHEhpItmWuqCJ","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Dumb Luck</h1><p>Dumb Luck allows a player to spend a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Benny} even after a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure}. The failure still happens in some way, but the character can spend one Benny (and only one) for one more roll. The hero still drops her weapon, flubs her @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Taunt]{Taunt}, or otherwise “fails” the attempt—but if the reroll from the Benny is actually successful, it somehow still results in whatever success the new roll provides.</p><p>A character trying to pick a lock might break the lock on a Critical Failure, for example, but only after cracking the lock. Or a warrior who fumbles a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll might hit a foe as if he’d thrown the weapon!</p><p>The player and Dungeon Master should work together to describe the scene in some fun or bizarre way that explains how the mishap ultimately results in success.</p><p class=\"embedded-example\"><strong>Example: </strong>Red fires three shots from her submachine gun (Rate of Fire 3). She rolls a 1 on her Wild Die and two of her Shooting dice—a Critical Failure! The DM decides the sudden recoil makes her drop her gun.<br />Red’s player, Emily, calls on Dumb Luck and spends a Benny. The reroll results in two hits (one with a raise!). The DM says the weapon bounces on the ground and sprays randomly, hitting two of Red’s foes!</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Dynamic Backlash","type":"text","_id":"R2xQQhnAuo2nIynF","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Dynamic Backlash</h1><p>A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} on an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} check results in <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}</strong>. That works well in traditional fantasy settings or worlds where magic is relatively common. If you feel magic should come with a higher price, however, use the <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Dynamic Backlash]{Dynamic Backlash}</strong> table instead.</p><p class=\"embedded-example\"><strong>Example:</strong> Gabe is a techno-sorceror in some far-flung science fiction world. He rolls a Critical Failure when casting lower Trait against an enemy’s Agility. Gabe’s player rolls Backfire on the Dynamic Backlash table so it affects his friend Red instead.<br />Red’s @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} suddenly drops two die types, forcing the warrior to go on the defensive until the power wears off.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"Fanatics","type":"text","_id":"oNVSCJktwuyTYpDW","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Fanatics</h1><p>Use this rule in pulp-style games where henchmen are numerous and villains are larger than life.</p><p>When a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} enemy character is hit by a successful attack and the DM thinks it’s appropriate, one of his henchmen, goons, or other allies jumps in front of his master and takes the attack instead.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":900000,"name":"Fast Healing","type":"text","_id":"Wwfo2DIVvn3PYAZo","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Fast Healing</h1><p>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} make natural @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Healing]{healing} rolls once per day instead of every five days (or once per hour if the race has @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Special Ability (Regeneration)]{Special Ability - Regeneration}).</p><p><strong>Bumps &amp; Bruises:</strong> Wild Cards recover one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps &amp; Bruises}</strong> every four hours instead of the usual 24.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1000000,"name":"Glory and Infamy","type":"text","_id":"PdIG4LR2kjS846gF","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Glory and Infamy</h1><aside class=\"sidebar float-right\"><h1>Playing a Villian</h1><p>Not every player is going to want to play a hero, and that's fine. After all, we've given the stat blocks for several evil deities, and there's no restriction on characters worshipping them. However, there is a price to pay for villainy.</p><p>Heroes who perform heroic deeds earn bonuses through their elevated Glory—villains get very little reward for being evil. Of course, to earn Glory a hero has to take great risks and maintain a certain code of conduct, whereas a villain doesn't have that restriction.</p><p>As such, villains are easy to play, but heroes get all the rewards for being \"forced\" to act in a certain manner.</p></aside><p>Everything living eventually dies. However, while a mortal's flesh may rot off the bone, his name can live forever through his deeds. Skalds and bards sing tales of heroes who perished long ago, keeping the memory of these figures as alive today as it was when they walked Eberron.</p><p>Glory has nothing to do with social standing, wealth, or who one calls friend—it is a mark of a character's reputation as a hero. A king may be well known across the lands, but that does not make him a hero, nor does it entitle him to become the focus of ballads or epic poems. Only through heroic deeds can a character aspire to enter the history books and oral myths of Eberron.</p><p>Your hero's Glory starts at zero, but can be affected by his or her actions during the course of the game. The higher your hero's Glory, the more renowned he is across Eberron and the more benefits he gains.</p><p>Just as Glory define the acts of a hero, so does Infamy define the acts of a villian. Infamy is Glory that has gone into the \"negative\".</p><h3>Glory vs. Rank</h3><p>A hero's Rank is a measure of his experience, although it does incorporate a degree of glory. Rank is a by-product of earning experience in adventures and quests, which aren't always linked to heroic deeds. Sure, the hero may rescue a princess, but the rescue might be fairly mundane and quickly forgotten. Only deeds which attract attention count toward Glory.</p><h2>Gaining Glory</h2><p>Glory is measured in Glory Points. Characters can rise to become famous heroes or slip into mediocrity or do deeds so heinous that they are remembered in Infamy.</p><p>Glory should not be dolled out like candy. It should be earned through heroic endeavors, good roleplaying, and investing heavily in character, not expected just because the hero is a player character.</p><h2>Variable Glorious Deeds</h2><p>After each adventure, and only when the heroes return to civilization, one of the party may begin telling the tale of their epic battles and heroic deeds. The character makes a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll, modified as below.</p><p>The DM is always free to add positive modifiers for truly heroic actions or based on the character's weaknesses and how he overcame them. Always try to think of how the heroes' true exploits (as opposed to any extra bits they invent) sound as a tale told by skalds. This is important, as it is the listeners on Khorvaire who are effectively granting them Glory.</p><p>Ideally, an extra +1 or +2 should be the maximum. For instance, slaying a dread liche is certainly worthy of praise, but that is already covered in the table. However, lopping off his head with a Called Shot as the killing blow is worth a small modifier, as it's the sort of detail found in epic poems.</p><p>Likewise, a Novice party with a d6 as their highest combat skill (including @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skills}) who slay a bunch of orc warriors in melee without any assistance should be rewarded with a greater chance of fame.</p><p>The DM may also opt to add penalties to reflect weaker opponents (such as unarmed or unarmored orcs) or favorable character circumstances (every hero had a dozen alchemical <em>blast</em> devices on hand).</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Glorious Deeds</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Reason</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Modifer</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Stroryteller</span></th></tr><tr><td>Is a bard/skald/storyteller</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td>Has negative Glory</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–2</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Highest Character Rank</span></th></tr><tr><td>Seasoned</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td></tr><tr><td>Veteran</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–2</td></tr><tr><td>Heroic</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–4</td></tr><tr><td>Legendary</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–6</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">highest Number of Foes</span></th></tr><tr><td>You outnumbered them</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td></tr><tr><td>They outnumbered you more than 2 to 1</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td>They outnumbered you more than 4 to 1</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td></tr><tr><td>They outnumbered you more than 10 to 1</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Highest Foe's Toughness</span></th></tr><tr><td>4 or less</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td></tr><tr><td>5 to 6</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+0</td></tr><tr><td>7 to 10</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td>11 to 15</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td></tr><tr><td>16 to 20</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td></tr><tr><td>21 or more</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+6</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Wild Cards</span></th></tr><tr><td>Per Wild Card</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td>Per named Wild Card</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td></tr><tr><td>Per Wild Card killed in a single blow</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">magic</span></th></tr><tr><td>A foe had an AB with 5 or less powers</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td>A foe had an AB with 6 to 10 powers</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td></tr><tr><td>A foe had an AB with 11+ powers</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+4</td></tr><tr><td>The had power magical items</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td>The foe had a relic</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Arcane Background:</strong> Where multiple foes with an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.7 Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds} were defeated, only the highest bonus applies.</p><p><strong>Character Rank: </strong>The higher the heroes' @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.saneNpHYSTivNRYE]{Rank}, the more dangerous foes they must overcome before anyone is interested in their tales. After all, when you've already slain a giant, who cares if you killed an orc chieftain?</p><p><strong>Foes' Toughness:</strong> Once you start talking about fighting a giant, listeners tend to forget or lose interest in the orcs you defeated in an earlier encounter. As such, only the highest @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} of defeated foes counts.</p><p><strong>Named Wild Card:</strong> No one really cares much if a hero slays a generic orc chieftain, but the slaying of Nargal the Terrible is a notable deed. Not every @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} should, or indeed can, be named. Sometimes a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} orc chief is just a nameless foe.</p><p><strong>Number of Foes:</strong> As with foes' @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness}, once you begin telling how the party slew a dozen orcs in one encounter, talk of beating five or six tends to become dull to the average listener. As such, only record the greatest number of foes slain in a single encounter. Defeating three orcs in one room and eight in another equates to only eight orcs.</p><p>The party size includes any allies on the heroes' side—a party with 20 members must defeat a lot of foes at once to get noticed. Even if the heroes forget to mention their helpers, any survivors will be telling their own stories across Rassilon.</p><p><strong>Single Blow:</strong> A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} killed in a single blow must have been unwounded when the killing blow was delivered. Chopping the head off a dread liche with 3 wounds is not exactly heroic.</p><p>Likewise, the foe must have been aware of the party and capable of retaliation—slaughtering sleeping dragons or <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangled}</em> giants doesn't make a good story, though the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> spell might be worth a small bonus.</p><p><strong>Storyteller:</strong> Although anyone can tell a story, skalds are trained in using the right words and adjusting the rhythm to keep an audience enthralled. They can turn even a mundane adventure into an epic struggle.</p><h3>Glory Awards</h3><p>With a success, every hero involved in the action gains 1d6 Glory. A raise increases this to 2d6. Failure earns no bonus or penalty. A critical failure, however, causes the loss of 1d6 Glory, perhaps because the listeners disbelieved the storyteller or doubt the prowess of the party to achieve what they claim. Roll the dice for each individual member of the party earning or losing Glory.</p><p>Glory awards can be altered by the GM, but this should be done only for truly notable actions. Modifiers normally apply solely to individual members of the party, not every member.</p><p>For instance, the hero who delivered the Called Shot to the head, killing the dread liche, should earn a +1 or +2 bonus for his notable deed. This actively encourages use of special maneuvers and imaginative combat, as opposed to the standard \"attack–damage\" routine.</p><p>Of course, if one hero played little part in the action, perhaps because he was Incapacitated early on or spent the whole time cowering in fear, he should receive less Glory than those who were in the thick of the action. Just because he's a player character and was present does not entitle him to the same reward as those who risked their lives and took part in the bulk of the action.</p><p>Such a hero may roll his dice with a –3 penalty, for example, possibly earning a small penalty overall with an unlucky roll because of his inaction.</p><h2>Fixed Glory Awards</h2><p>Fixed Glory awards cover lesser deeds not played out (such as events during long periods of downtime), killing smaller number of foes during an adventure (they do slowly add up over time), or rewards for which there are many witnesses (battles or rescues). These are in addition to any Glory gained above.</p><p>DM's are encouraged to devise their own modifiers for things like concluding peace treaties or founding new mercantile routes that benefit a large population. Although notable deeds, the rewards for these types of endeavor should not be overly high—few people will remember who signed a peace treaty, but you can bet they'll recall a hero who risked his life to venture into the heavily guarded camp of the enemy commander and kill him in an epic duel.</p><h2>Achieve Rank</h2><p>Even without performing major heroic deeds, a hero can become famous through his collective lesser deeds. Such rewards are typical of the examples above, especially the slaying of lesser foes.</p><p>These are wrapped into a single +5 Glory bonus gained when a hero achieves a new Rank. It is possible, though rare, for a hero to reach Legendary status with no additional Glory—he has performed many deeds, but none stand out as truly heroic.</p><h2>Mass Battles</h2><p>War is a terrible thing and something sane men avoid, but it can also grow and break reputations.</p><p>Use the table below whenever the characters are involved in a fight using the Mass Battle rules. Whereas skirmishes are commonplace, true mass battles remain rare events. Hence, all Glory modifiers are fixed.</p><table class=\"centered\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Glory for Mass Battles</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Reason</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\" style=\"width:20%\">Modifier</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Size</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Smallest army had hundreds of troops</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Smallest army had thousands of troops</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+3</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Smallest army had more than 10,000 troops</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+5</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Enemy</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Hated rival of your nation</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+/–1</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Undead Army</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+/–2</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Victory</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Enemy had less tokens or was equal</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">For each token the enemy had above yours</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+2</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Defeat</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Enemy had more tokens or was equal</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–1</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">For each token less your enemy had</td><td style=\"width:20%\">–3</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Personal heroics</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">Two raises on Heroes in Mass Battles rolls</td><td style=\"width:20%\">+1</td></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"no-class\">Commander</span></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">You commanded the army</td><td style=\"width:20%\">x2</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Character Roll:</strong> Scoring a double raise is more than just a die result. It represents a major event within a battle, such as slaying an enemy commander or slaughtering so many foes a battalion breaks.</p><p>However, the modifier only applies if the number of enemy tokens was less than or equal to your army's tokens at the time (slaying an enemy commander when you have a +3 bonus is nowhere near as heroic as when you have a –3 penalty.</p><p><strong>Commander: </strong>A hero who commands an army gains greater Glory than his troops for victory, but also suffers more ignominy if he loses the field. Take the final Glory modifier and double it to see what the hero earned.</p><p><strong>Defeat:</strong> Defeat is never easy to live with, but the ignominy is far worse if you outnumbered your foe. For each token you outnumbered your enemy at the start of a battle you suffer a –3 penalty.</p><p><strong>Enemy Forces: </strong>Certain races are more despised than others. To qualify for the bonus, the specific enemy must account for more than 75% of the enemy army's troop strength.</p><p>Add the modifier if the heroes won, and subtract it if they lost (a defeat by a hated foe usually means the enemy will grow more confident and thus pose a greater danger in the future).</p><p><strong>Size: </strong>Huge armies are rare in Khorvaire now the Last War is over, and thus while any battle earns Glory, the more participants there are the greater the tale told.</p><p><strong>Victory: </strong>Everybody loves a winner. The greater the size of the enemy army, the more reward is earned. For each token your enemy's army was larger than yours when battle commenced, the hero earns a +2 Glory bonus.</p><h2>Rescue</h2><p>Even if the heroes' tale of how they killed a hundred orcs doesn't earn them any immediate Glory, having prisoners recount the tale of their rescue quickly causes word to spread.</p><p>Important NPCs must be famous, powerful, and named. A merchant, wizard, priest, minor noble, or similar is worth +1 Glory. Saving a count or a skilled spellcaster is worth +3. Rescuing a prince, king, or truly powerful spellcaster gains the hero +5 Glory.</p><p>For groups of lesser NPCs, rescuing ten or so is worth +1 Glory, a few tens +2, and a hundred or more +3. Saving a lone villager from an orc tribe is brave, but not enough to be retold by skalds.</p><p>Rescue doesn't have to mean entering a prison and breaking captives out. Liberating a village beset by frostreavers, for instance, counts as a rescue. If the rescue involves a Mass Battle rather than tabletop action, the party is deserving of the Mass Battle rewards as well.</p><h2>Glory Benefits</h2><p>Being a hero has its perks. When a hero reaches a multiple of 20 Glory he must immediately pick one benefit from the list below, meeting any requirements. Some heroes may opt to acquire Followers or become leaders of men and build a personal army. Others might use their fame to gain valuable connections or become better combatants, while others may prefer to rely on their reputation to ensure a friendly welcome in civilized lands.</p><p>Unless otherwise stated, benefits can be taken multiple times—the number in parentheses after the name indicates the maximum number of times the benefit may be taken. Fill in the appropriate section of the character sheet.</p><p>Should Glory drop below a multiple of 20, any benefits above the character's current Glory level are temporarily lost (unless otherwise stated) until Glory is regained. Dropping below 20 and then rising above it again does not grant the opportunity to take a new benefit—it simply allows the “lost” one to be used again.</p><table class=\"centered\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"3\">Glory Edges</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Edge</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Requirements</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Summary</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Combat Prowess]{Combat Prowess}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">20+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Gain a Combat Edge.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Connection]{Connection}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">40+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Hero gains friend(s) among an organzition aligned with him.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Favored]{Favored}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">60+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Hero gains an extra @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Followers (Glory)]{Followers}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">40+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Hero gains @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Followers]{Followers}, as per the Edge.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Heroic Aura]{Heroic Aura}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">40+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">The Hero's @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Making Characters]{Toughness} increases by 1.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Heroic Status]{Heroic Status}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">20+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">+1 bonus to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Reaction Table]{Reaction Table} results, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}, and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Networking]{Networking}.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Immortalized in Song]{Immortalized in Song}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Heroic Status taken 4 times</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Number of Followers the Hero has doubles.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Leader of Men]{Leader of Men}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">40+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Hero can take a Leadership Edge.</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:left\">@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Sidekick]{Sidekick}</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">80+ Glory</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Leader gains the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Sidekick]{Sidekick} Edge.</td></tr></tbody></table><h2 class=\"example\">Example: Barak the Fair</h2><p><em>Dave's character, Barak the Fair, has the Heroic Status benefit, which he took he reached 20 Glory. When he reaches 40 Glory he takes the Connection Edge (Church of the Silver Flame).</em></p><p><em>Due to a \"misunderstanding\" regarding a visit to noble's daughter's bedchamber late one night, he suffers a 2-point Glory penalty, lowering his total to 38. The Church of the Silver Flame immediately suspend ties to the hero, but Barak retains his Heroic Status. Only if Barak's Glory drops below 20, will he lose his Heroic Status as well.</em></p><p><em>Later on, Barak earns +4 Glory, bringing his total to 42. The Church of the Silver Flame open relations again now the hero's reputation is not as sullied—Barak does not get to pick a new benefit.</em></p><h2>Losing Glory</h2><p>Glory can be won, bit can also be lost. In general, a hero must deliberately act in a less than heroic way to suffer a Glory penalty. Everyone makes mistakes and crosses the line at some point, but minor misdemeanors should be ignored unless the character makes a habit of such actions.</p><p>Sample penalties are included below</p><table class=\"centered\" style=\"width:60%;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Glory Penalties</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Glory</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\" style=\"text-align:left\">Event</th></tr><tr><td>Special</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Slaying a good and just powerful NPC.</td></tr><tr><td>–1 to –10</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Caught committing a crime</td></tr><tr><td>–3</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Cowardice or leaving a comrade behind</td></tr><tr><td>–3</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Refusing orders</td></tr><tr><td>–10</td><td style=\"text-align:left\">Breaking an oath</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Negative Glory</h2><p>Heroes with negative Glory do not earn rewards, but they do garner drawbacks.</p><h3>Wanted</h3><p>When a hero reaches –20 Glory, he gains the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Wanted]{Wanted} (Minor) Hindrance. At –40, this changes to the Major version.</p><p>Generally, the Minor Hindrance extends to a single realm, usually the one where the Glory penalty was incurred. The Major version, on the other hand, covers pretty much all the civilized, settled domains of Khorvaire. A hero who gains enough Glory to rise above the rating at which he gained this Hindrance, doesn't lose the Hindrance. He may have performed some heroic deeds, but he is still a wanted man.</p><h3>Enemy</h3><p>At –10 Glory, the hero acquires the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} (Minor) Hindrance. At –30 (or lower), the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} becomes a Major Hindrance.</p><p>The exact nature of the enemy depends on the villain's deeds.</p><p>Again, it doesn't matter if the hero's Glory rises above the level at which he gained his foe—his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} doesn't give up his vendetta.</p><p>Should the hero gain a Major @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} while his Minor @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-hindrances.Enemy]{Enemy} is still at large, the foe simply steps up his campaign against the character. Otherwise, the hero gains a new enemy.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1100000,"name":"Gritty Damage","type":"text","_id":"k9MdONQ1nuCXqHWA","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Gritty Damage</h1><p>This variation on damage works well for settings such as gritty detective scenarios or “realistic” military adventures. It can be very lethal so use it cautiously.</p><p>Whenever a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} takes a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Wound}, roll on the <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Injury Table]{Injury Table}</strong> and apply the results immediately (but roll only once per incident regardless of how many Wounds are actually caused). A hero who takes two Wounds from an attack, for example, rolls once on the <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-tables.Injury Table]{Injury Table}</strong>.</p><p>Injuries sustained in this way are cured when the Wound is healed. Injuries sustained via @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Incapacitation} may be temporary or permanent as usual.</p><p>A Shaken character who’s @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Shaken} a second time (from damage) receives a Wound as usual but does not roll on the Injury Table.</p><p class=\"embedded-example\"><strong>Example: </strong>Gabe is a Hellfighter (soldier) during Weird War One. He takes a Wound from a German sniper and rolls on the Injury Table. He rolls a 10—Leg. The DM rolls a die and decides it’s the left leg, so he has the Slow (Minor) Hindrance. If he takes another Wound to that leg, the Hindrance becomes Major. Further Wounds to the same leg add to his Wound total as usual but have no further effect.</p><p class=\"embedded-example\">Later, Gabe takes two Wounds to the Guts. The Dungeon Master rolls once and gets the Battered result from the Injury Table, reducing the Sarge’s Vigor from d8 to d6. Gabe now has three Wounds and two gruesome injuries.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1200000,"name":"Hard Choices","type":"text","_id":"x4Iaa16byWxOCYEO","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Hard Choices</h1><p>Use this rule for more dramatic and gritty games. The DM and her @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} characters don’t start with @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Bennies}, but every time the players spend one it goes into her pool where it can be used for any of her characters. If this rule is in play, Jokers no longer grant Bennies to either side.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1300000,"name":"Heroes Never Die","type":"text","_id":"ZDTvOvrfnGr71kt8","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Heroes Never Die</h1><p>Heroes in movies very rarely die. When they do, they go down fighting or perform one last, epic act of heroism.</p><p>With this rule in play, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} who are @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Incapacitated} from a damage roll make a Vigor roll as usual but treat @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failures} as regular failures and ignore the rules for Bleeding Out.</p><p>How a hero might survive what should be certain death is a chance to get creative. An adventurer who falls from a towering cliff, for example, might land in a pool of water or crash through the branches of a forest far below.</p><p>If the situation is particularly heroic or if it serves as a major story point, the DM and player can decide the character perishes. A hero who confronts a massive demon on a crumbling bridge, for example, might take the fiend with him with his final blow.</p><p><strong>Villains:</strong> The reverse is also true—villains rarely die either! Heroes should play this in the spirit it’s intended—they shouldn’t attempt to cause some sort of gruesome and undeniable death to a villain who falls into their hands, for example. They should instead turn the captive over to the authorities—even though they know full well he will eventually escape to plague them once again.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1400000,"name":"High Adventure","type":"text","_id":"tVKwoKzSm4DsPCQ6","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">High Adventure</h1><p>Characters can spend a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Benny} to gain the one-time use of a Combat Gain a new @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Edges]{Edge}. They have to meet the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Advancement]{Rank} and any Edge requirements as usual but can ignore Trait requirements. Multiple @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bennies]{Bennies} can be spent in one round for multiple Edges, either for different effects or in order to meet a needed requirement to gain another Edge.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1500000,"name":"More Skill Points","type":"text","_id":"UW7MNP2J4nBL5arp","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">More Skill Points</h1><p>Thanks to technology and improved education, characters in modern and futuristic settings have 15 Traits @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{skill points} at character creation rather than 12. This helps them take @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Driving]{Driving}, @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Electronics]{Electronics}, and other skills common in the modern world.</p><p>It’s up to the DM if this makes sense in her particular setting. A futuristic but “savage” world of planetary romance probably doesn’t need it, but it works well for most anything set in the developed world from about 1950 on, hard scifi, or “exploration” scifi like <cite>The Last Parsec</cite>.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1600000,"name":"No Power Points","type":"text","_id":"tcC8ebPxa06uPaow","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">No Power Points</h1><p>Instead of using @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Power Points}, characters with @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Arcane Backgrounds]{Arcane Backgrounds} simply choose the power they want to activate and make an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} roll. The penalty to the roll is the power’s total cost in Power Points (base cost plus all @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Power Modifiers]{Modifiers}), divided by 2. Round up.</p><p>Casting <em>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-powers.Protection]{protection}</em> (1 point) with More Armor (+1) and the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Hinder or Hurry (+1)]{Hurry} modifier (+1), for example, has a cost of 3 Power Points. Half rounded up is 2.</p><p>Success means the power activates as usual. A raise grants any additional bonuses stated in its description.</p><p>Failure means all current powers are canceled and the caster is Shaken. @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure} results in <strong>@Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Activation]{Backlash}</strong>.</p><p><strong>Maintaining Powers:</strong> Characters can main­tain those powers that allow it as long as desired, but each one maintained inflicts a −1 to all further @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} rolls.</p><p><strong>Power Preparation: </strong>A caster may prepare powers by concentrating for an entire round (no move­ment or other actions and must not be @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Shaken or Stunned}). If successful, he ignores 2 points of penalties on all powers cast on his next turn. If he does not enact any powers on his next turn, the preparation is lost.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1700000,"name":"Unarmored Hero","type":"text","_id":"cuT21neBarvD1oOD","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Unarmored Hero</h1><p>Pulp action tales often feature heroes with little or no armor defeating far more heavily armored adversaries.</p><p>In these settings, if a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} chooses not to wear <em>any</em> @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Armor]{armor} (ignoring shields), he adds +2 bonus to his @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Soak Rolls]{Soak rolls}!</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1800000,"name":"Wound Cap","type":"text","_id":"Ps4kOQ7T3sYvRBun","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Wound Cap</h1><p>Use this Setting Rule when you want combat to remain dangerous but reduce the chances of characters (and villains!) dying from a single lucky blow. It can still happen, but it is far more rare.</p><p>Characters can never suffer more than four @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Damage Effects]{Wounds} in a single hit and therefore never have to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Soak Rolls]{Soak} more than four wounds either!</p><p><strong>Large Creatures:</strong> The Wound Cap applies even to creatures with more than three Wounds (due to their @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} or the @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Special Ability (Resilient or Very Resilient)]{Resilient/Very Resilient Special Ability}). A Huge creature that can take five Wounds, for example, can’t take more than four from a single attack, so it can’t normally be killed with a single attack. The DM can always overrule this in specific and obvious situations, of course, such as massive blasts, falling from towering cliffs or mountains, etc.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ltavh0xcxs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules","color":"#008000"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"swade","systemVersion":"2.2.5","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1674612481431,"modifiedTime":1676930949922,"lastModifiedBy":"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf"},"_id":"KUC0m89RgzdYzG3v","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf":3}}
{"name":"Situational Rules","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Situational Rules","type":"text","_id":"g4K01MNlzqPq5NVt","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div><h1 class=\"wide\">Situational rules</h1></div><p class=\"drop-cap\">The core rules for <cite>Savage Eberron</cite> are very simple— roll a skill die (and a Wild Die if a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card)}. If the result is 4 or higher after all modifiers, you’re successful.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Aim","type":"text","_id":"aMKEcG5KZtdH143K","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Aim</h1><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} rolls assume a character is moving about, dodging attacks, and keeping an eye on the chaos around her. If she focuses her attention and aims, she can make a much more accurate shot.</p><p>If a character spends her entire turn Aiming a ranged weapon at a particular target or spot (DM's call) and takes no other actions, <em>on her next turn</em> she may ignore up to 4 points of\"@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0]{Called Shots}, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} penalties; or add +2 to her roll. Her attack must be used on the first action of her next turn or the bonus is lost.</p><p>The shooter must be relatively stationary to @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.aMKEcG5KZtdH143K]{Aim}. She can’t walk, run, ride a horse, or be constantly jostled.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Area Effect Attacks","type":"text","_id":"CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Area Effect Attacks</h1><p>Spell effects, breath weapons, and other attacks that cover a large area are @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{“area effect attacks”}. The most common are Small, Medium, and Large Blast Templates, and the Cone and Stream Templates. There are copies you can print out on our website.</p><p>Area effect weapons target a location rather than individuals and so ignore defensive bonuses for targets covered by the template, such as the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Dodge]{Dodge} Edge or speed penalties.</p><p>Cone and Stream templates are placed with one end (usually the narrow end for the cone template) emanating from the attacker and fired with the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} skill (or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} for breath weapons and other natural attacks). A basic success means those beneath the template are hit. Failure means the attack didn’t occur for some reason— the creature failed to belch up noxious gas, the flamethrower malfunctioned, etc.</p><p>To attack with a blast template, the player places it on the tabletop (or describes where he wants it to land) and rolls Shooting, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} for thrown weapons and breath attacks. If the attack fails and there’s a chance the miss might hit someone else, see Deviation, below.</p><p>If the roll is successful, any target even partially beneath the template is affected, regardless of any attack penalties to hit such as the Dodge Edge. If the effect causes damage, roll for each victim separately. Attacks that hit with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise} cause bonus damage as usual.</p><h3>Deviation</h3><p>Most of the time, the DM can ignore a missed @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{area effect attack}. If it's important to know where a missed blast lands, thrown items deviate 1d6″. Fired projectiles deviate 2d6\". Multiply by 2 if the attack was made at Medium Range, 3 if Long, and 4 for Extreme.</p><p>Next roll a d12 and read it like a clock facing to determine the direction the missile deviates. A weapon can never deviate more than half the distance to the original target (that keeps it from going behind the thrower).</p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h1>Templates Without Miniatures</h1><p>Use the measurements below when you need to figure out how many enemies a template might affect and you aren't using miniatures.</p><p>The <strong>Targets Affected</strong> column above shows the DM how many enemies are hit in narrative situations, modifying the result if the targets are spread out (like trained assassins) or bunched up (like mindless zombies).</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Template</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Diameter</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Targets Affected</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Small</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">4 yards</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Medium</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">8 yards</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Large</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">12 yards</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">4</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Cone</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">18-yard-long cone</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Stream</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">24 × 2-yard line</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td></tr></tbody></table></aside><h3>Cover and Area Effect Attacks</h3><p>Solid obstacles like trees or thick walls protect against @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{area effect attacks} if they’re between the center of the blast and a victim and the DM thinks they’d offer protection. Reduce the damage by half the object's hardness, see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover &amp; Obstacles}</strong></p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Bound and Entangle","type":"text","_id":"p7NWl3RbgqlgY7Fh","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Bound and Entangled</h1><p>Grappling and powers like <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> cause characters to be Bound and Entangled. Here’s what each of those states means and how to break free from them. Characters are either @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{Bound or Entangled}— effects don't stack.</p><ul><li><strong>Entangled:</strong> The victim can’t move and is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable} as long as he remains Entangled.</li><li><strong>Bound:</strong> The victim may not move, is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted and Vulnerable} as long as he remains Bound, and cannot make physical actions other than trying to break free.</li></ul><p>Breaking free is an action. With success, an Entangled hero is free of one particular entanglement or grappler. A Bound character improves to Entangled with a success; with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, he’s free. See below for more details:</p><p><strong>Breaking Free from a Foe:</strong> Use the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{Grappling} rules in reverse to break free. The victim initiates an opposed @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll with whoever’s holding him (either may roll Strength at −2 instead to maintain or break free of the hold). If the victim’s successful, she improves her status one level, or two with a raise.</p><p>A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} grappler maintains her hold. @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned} grapplers let go immediately.</p><p><strong>Breaking Free from a Device:</strong> Escaping a web, net, manacles, handcuffs, or the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Entangle]{entangle}</em> power is a limited free action using @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.SzVzIV8ZxqKg3Oe3]{Athletics}, Strength −2 roll or base damage with a small, easily accessible weapon capable of damaging whatever holds him (he hits automatically.</p><p>If taken as a regular action instead, the hero adds +2 to his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.SzVzIV8ZxqKg3Oe3]{Athletics} or Strength roll. With a weapon he may @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.xJpg68BZwGvRe0pQ]{Wild Attack} to add +2 to his damage.</p><p>Characters and allies may also destroy the entanglement (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}</strong>. Webs, ropes, nets, and the like are generally Hardness 4 and must be cut with an edged weapon.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.5B8fRjXoVcuMtvTO.JournalEntryPage.p7NWl3RbgqlgY7Fh"}}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Breaking Things","type":"text","_id":"Lb5eVLU33ffJeTO3","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Breaking Things</h1><p>Occasionally a character may want to break a solid object, such as a weapon, lock, or door. Use the wielder’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} if held, or 2 if it’s motionless. If a damage roll equals or exceeds the object’s Hardness, it’s broken, bent, shattered, or otherwise ruined. The DM decides the exact effect.</p><p>Most anything can be broken given enough time and effort, so use this system only when attempting to break things in a hurry (such as during combat rounds).</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"3\">Object Hardness</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Hardness</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Object</th><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">4</td><td>Rope</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">6</td><td>Bow</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">8</td><td>Polearm, thin wooden door or wall</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td><td>Shield*, longsword, thick wooden door or wall</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">12</td><td>Iron lock, manacles, shackles</td><th></th></tr></tbody></table><p>*A character must specifically state he’s trying to break a shield to do so—don’t check every time the shield-bearer is hit.</p><p><strong>No Bonus Damage or Aces:</strong> Attacks against solid objects don’t get bonus damage from @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raises}, and damage rolls don’t @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Aces]{Ace}. Unlike a person or complex device like a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Vehicles]{vehicle}, an attack can’t hit a “vital” area on a lock or a door and thus do more damage.</p><p><strong>Damage Types:</strong> Certain types of attacks can’t break certain types of objects. A club can’t cut a rope, for example. Use common sense when determining whether or not a particular type of weapon can destroy an object.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Called Shots","type":"text","_id":"FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Called Shots</h1><p>Targeting a particular part of the body is a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0]{Called Shots}. The modifier to the attack roll depends on the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} of the target itself (not the creature it’s part of). Use the <strong>Scale Modifiers</strong> table in the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Size and Scale} section further down to determine any bonus or penalty for the target’s Scale. These modifiers are already listed in parentheses for Normal scale creatures, along with any specific game effects:</p><ul><li><strong>Hand (-4)</strong>: Target may be <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.V6XYsi78mgZos4kc]{Disarmed}</strong>.</li><li><strong>Head or Vitals (-4)</strong>: Hitting the head or vital organs of living creatures adds +4 damage to the attacker’s total. The penalty is −5 if attempting to target the face of someone wearing an open-faced helmet (thus bypassing the helmet’s Armor).</li><li><strong>Item</strong>(?) : Use the dimensions on the Scale table for items. Targeting something the size of a dagger, for example, is −4.</li><li><strong>Limbs</strong>(-2) Unless attempting to @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.V6XYsi78mgZos4kc]{Disarm} (see @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.V6XYsi78mgZos4kc]{here}), hitting a limb has no additional special effect since it’s already accounted for by Wound and Pace penalties (see <strong>@UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{here}</strong>).</li><li><strong>Unarmored Area</strong> (?) : The attack targets the unprotected area of a target otherwise covered in Armor. The penalty depends on the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} of the area. The eye slit of a helmet is Tiny (−6), for example, while the flesh beneath the missing scale of a Huge dragon might be Very Small (−4).</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"Cover and Obstacles","type":"text","_id":"ydsaVLnP3CyLRwIL","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Cover and Obstacles</h1><p>Melee and ranged attacks suffer a penalty when attempting to hit a target behind @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}. Penalties only apply to the targeted area— a skeleton standing behind a knee-high wall doesn't get Light Cover, but he does if a quarter of his body is protected by a door frame.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"3\">Cover Penalties</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Penalty</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Cover</th><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−2</td><td><strong>Light Cover:</strong> A quarter of the target is obscured.</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−4</td><td><strong>Medium Cover:</strong> Half the target is obscured, or target is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}.</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−6</td><td><strong>Heavy Cover:</strong> Three-quarters of the target is obscured.</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−8</td><td><strong>Near Total Cover:</strong> The target is hidden or barely visible.</td><th></th></tr></tbody></table><h3>Obstacles</h3><p>Sometimes characters have sufficient power to attack their foes <em>through</em> obstacles. (See <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}</strong> to actually destroy intervening obstacles.)</p><p>When this happens, add an Armor bonus equal to half the obstacle's Hardness to the target beyond (round up if necessary).</p><p>If the obstacle is a person or creature, subtract its Toughness from the attack instead.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Defend","type":"text","_id":"ULJc5K7JHFp6hFnL","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Defend</h1><p>A character can choose to focus all her energy and skill into defense against melee attacks with the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.ULJc5K7JHFp6hFnL]{Defend} maneuver. This increases her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} by +4 and takes her entire turn— she cannot perform @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions}. She may move normally but may not run. The bonus lasts until the beginning of her next turn.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"Desperate Attack","type":"text","_id":"zTPAIxJ1HGg4bYZq","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Desperate Attack</h1><p>Determined to land a blow, the warrior unleashes a frantic attack, focusing on hitting his target at the expense of damage. He adds +2 or +4 to any @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll and subtracts a like amount from damage if he hits. This can be determined per attack (before rolling), and can't be combined with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Attack]{Wild Attack}.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":900000,"name":"Disarm","type":"text","_id":"V6XYsi78mgZos4kc","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Disarm</h1><p>A character can try to make an opponent drop a weapon or other object by making an attack against the limb or hand (see <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0]{Called Shots}</strong>). If the attack hits a weapon, the attacker rolls damage normally for an item (no raise effect or Aces, see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Breaking Things]{Breaking Things}</strong>). The defender must make a Strength roll equal to the damage or drop the item.</p><p>If an attack against a target's hand or limb @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shakes} or @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounds} him, he must make a Strength roll at −2 if it hit his limb or −4 if it hit his hand. Failure means he drops whatever item is in that hand.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1000000,"name":"Distracted and Vulnerable","type":"text","_id":"vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Distracted and Vulnerable</h1><p>Characters may be Distracted or made Vulnerable by special abilities, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests}, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{Powers}. These states last until the end of the character’s next turn unless otherwise noted. If a hero becomes Distracted or Vulnerable during her current turn, it lasts until the end of her <em>next</em> turn. Like effects don't stack.</p><ul><li><strong>Distracted:</strong> The hero subtracts 2 from all @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls} until the end of his next turn.</li><li><strong>Vulnerable:</strong> Actions and attacks against the target are made at +2 until the end of his next turn. This doesn’t stack with <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.l1rEt2RnvcIiEGtQ]{The Drop}</strong> (see below).</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1100000,"name":"The Drop","type":"text","_id":"l1rEt2RnvcIiEGtQ","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">The Drop</h1><p>Sometimes an attacker is able to catch a foe off-guard and gets “The Drop” on him. The DM decides when this is in effect— usually it’s when the victim is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Bound and Entangled]{bound} or completely unaware of an attack. The Drop usually happens up close but the DM can also allow it in other situations as she sees fit (a sniper attacking an unaware and stationary target).</p><p>The Drop adds +4 to a character’s attack and damage rolls against that target for one action.</p><p><strong>Knockout Blow:</strong> If a character takes enough damage to be @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} or worse from an attacker with The Drop on him, he must make a Vigor roll (at −2 if the attack was to the head) or be knocked unconscious.</p><p>KO’ed characters stay that way for about half an hour or until the DM decides it’s dramatically appropriate to wake up. Note that Knockout Blows come from any kind of damage, not just blows to the head!</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1200000,"name":"Evasion","type":"text","_id":"JcU31mPkiJ6BMD4t","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Evasion</h1><p>Some attacks are slow or require the user to “telegraph” their delivery, like flamethrowers or dragon’s breath. Such attacks state they may be Evaded. If an attack <em>doesn’t</em> say it can be @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Evasion]{Evaded}, it can’t— victims are simply hit if the attack is successful and take damage.</p><p>If an attack can be Evaded and the character is aware of it, he makes an @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} roll at −2. Those who are successful manage to avoid the attack and take no damage. If this was an area effect attack, the DM should place the figure to the side or rear of the template as makes sense in the situation.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1300000,"name":"Fatigue","type":"text","_id":"7LJ6PoYcYzg4lThm","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Fatigue</h1><p>Some hazards, stress, powers, or circum­stances may cause Fatigue instead of damage. This represents mental stress or minor but lingering injuries that make a person less effective. Fatigue stacks until the victim is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}.</p><ul><li><strong>Fatigued:</strong> The victim subtracts 1 from all @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls}. If he takes another level of Fatigue, he’s Exhausted.</li><li><strong>Exhausted:</strong> The victim subtracts 2 from all Trait rolls. If he takes another level of Fatigue, he’s Incapacitated.</li><li><strong>Incapacitated:</strong> The victim cannot perform actions and may be unconscious (DM's call).</li></ul><h3>Recovery</h3><p>Unless otherwise specified by the source, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} and Exhaustion improve one level per hour. Characters @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated} from Fatigue are helpless and may be unconscious (DM's call) for 2d6 hours. If treatment is possible (food, water, etc.; depending on the source of Fatigue), and a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Healing]{Healing} roll is made, the character improves to Exhausted.</p><p><strong>Mixed Fatigue:</strong> If a hero suffers Fatigue from different sources with different recovery times, remove one level when the effect with the shortest duration expires, then another level when the longest expires.</p><h3>Hazards</h3><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from hunger, thirst, etc., sometimes has different recovery conditions. See <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hazards]{Hazards}</strong>.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1400000,"name":"Finishing Move","type":"text","_id":"IyYEOTgUoVAAKKUU","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Finishing Move</h1><p>A completely helpless victim may be dispatched with a lethal weapon of some sort as an action. This is automatic unless the DM decides there’s a special situation, such as a particularly tough or naturally armored victim, a chance for escape, and so on.</p><p>The killer must usually dispatch his foe up close and personal, but the DM may occasionally let @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Finishing Move]{Finishing Moves} be performed at range if the situation warrants.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1500000,"name":"Firing into Melee","type":"text","_id":"usZusZBi17x9t77E","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Firing into Melee</h1><p>Occasionally, heroes have to fire into the middle of hand-to-hand fights. The trouble is that even though we might see figures standing perfectly still on the tabletop, in “reality,” they’re circling each other, wrestling back and forth, and moving erratically. For that reason, firing into a tangle of people, such as a melee, is quite dangerous. Use the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Innocent Bystandards]{Innocent Bystander}</strong> rules when this occurs.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1600000,"name":"Free Attacks","type":"text","_id":"CxoTKWhnss6i3zcy","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Free Attacks</h1><p>Some Edges, such as @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Counterattack]{Counterattack} and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.First Strike]{First Strike}, or options such as <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Withdrawing From Melee]{Withdrawing From Melee}</strong>, allow a character to make a free attack.</p><p>Free attacks are a single attack unaltered by other Edges or combat options. This is usually a Fighting or grappling attack, but could include Shooting if the attacker is armed with a hand crossbow, wand, or small device (DM's call, see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ranged Weapons in Melee]{Ranged Weapons in Melee}</strong>.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1700000,"name":"Ganging Up","type":"text","_id":"sA1iNvYo7idD0MTE","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Ganging Up</h1><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Ganging Up} allows attackers to flank, exploit openings, and generally harass a foe. Each additional adjacent ally (who isn’t \"@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned}) adds +1 to all the attackers’ @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls, up to a maximum of +4. If three goblins attack a single hero, for example, each of the three goblins add +2 to their Fighting rolls.</p><p>Each of the defender's adjacent allies cancels out one point of Gang Up bonus from an attacker adjacent to both. This means troops in opposing lines, such as a medieval formation where each man has three adjacent foes and two adjacent allies, don’t get the bonus unless actually flanked.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1800000,"name":"Hold","type":"text","_id":"zjrhEijl5cbzSjeN","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Hold</h1><p>A hero may choose to delay her turn by going on @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{\"Hold\"}. This allows her to resolve her actions later in the round if she wishes, and lasts until it’s used. If a character is on Hold when a new round begins, she’s not dealt a new @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#action-cards-(initiative)]{Action Card} but can go at any point in the round she chooses. (Discard her current card and mark her as “On Hold” with a counter of some sort.)</p><p><strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned}</strong> If a character is Shaken or Stunned while on Hold, she immediately loses her Hold status and her turn for the round. (Shaken or Stunned characters can’t go on Hold either.)</p><p><strong>Interrupting Actions:</strong> If a character on Hold wants to interrupt an action (including a rival who was also on Hold), she and the opponent make opposed @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} rolls. Whoever rolls highest goes first. In the rare case of a tie, the actions are simultaneous.</p><p>If the character interrupting fails, she loses her Hold status but gets a turn after the foe finishes his. She may take whatever actions she wishes when her turn comes up— she’s not locked into whatever she was trying to do when she failed to interrupt.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1900000,"name":"Illumination","type":"text","_id":"GondbiqEQnzm8Erm","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Illumination</h1><p>Darkness conceals details and makes it more difficult to detect objects and targets. Subtract the Illumination Penalties (see the <strong>Illumination Penalties</strong> table below) from active @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Trait Rolls]{Trait rolls} affected by Illumination, such as attacks, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1 Powers]{arcane skill} and Notice rolls, etc.</p><p>It’s up to the Dungeon Master exactly what Trait rolls are affected, but here are a few examples of rolls that should <em>not</em> be penalized:</p><ul><li>Resisting powers</li><li>Resisting @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{grappling} attempts</li><li>Recovering from a negative status, such as being @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} or @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned}</li><li>Verbal @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support} rolls</li><li>Verbal @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Tests}</li><li>A friendly, cooperative, adjacent character in Pitch Darkness where touch and communication overcome lack of sight</li></ul><p>Note that foes may get bonuses for attacking a target that can’t see them (see <strong>Attacking from Stealth</strong> in the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} subsection in @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Traits}).</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"3\">ILLUMINATION PENALTIES</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Penalty</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Lighting</th><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−2</td><td><strong>Dim:</strong> Twilight, light fog, night with a full moon. Visibility is generally limited to 25\" (50 yards).</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−4</td><td><strong>Dark:</strong> Typical night conditions with some ambient light from stars, a clouded or partial moon, a few flickering torches in a large space, etc. Targets aren’t visible outside of 10″.</td><th></th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−6</td><td><strong>Pitch Darkness:</strong> Complete and total darkness (or the target is hidden or invisible). Powers that require sight may not be possible.</td><th></th></tr></tbody></table></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2000000,"name":"Improvised Weapons","type":"text","_id":"BkjxF6baEeZ2N14H","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Improvised Weapons</h1><p>Heroes often fight with objects that aren’t intended for use as weapons. Torches, vases, chairs, tankards, bottles, tools, and other mundane items are frequently pressed into service in combat.</p><p>Characters with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Improvised Weapons]{improvised weapons} count as armed but subtract 2 from attack rolls. Range, damage and Minimum Strength are determined by type:</p><ul><li><strong>Light:</strong> Beer stein, fist-sized rock, dagger pommel (as a club). Range 3/6/12, Damage Str+d4, Min Str d4.</li><li><strong>Medium:</strong> Hammer, pick, wooden chair. Range 2/4/8, Damage Str+d6, Min. Str d6.</li><li><strong>Heavy:</strong> Head-size rock, sack of stones, log. Range 1/2/4, Damage Str+d8, Min. Str d8.</li></ul><p>The DM should adjust the damage and other factors as makes sense for the particular item.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/kobold-ambush.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2100000,"name":"Innocent Bystanders","type":"text","_id":"h4RXZJ1nSxGtuP6f","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Innocent Bystandards</h1><p>When an attacker misses a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) roll, it may sometimes be important to see if any other targets in the line of fire were hit. The DM should only use this rule when it’s dramatically appropriate— not for every missed shot in a hail of arrows.</p><p>Each skill die that’s a 1 hits a random victim adjacent to or directly in the line of fire to the original target.</p><p>A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} must miss with his Wild Die for a RoF 1 weapon to hit an Innocent Bystander— wild dice never hit innocent bystanders.</p><p>This sometimes means it's easier to hit an adjacent victim than the original target. That may not be entirely realistic, but is simple, dramatic, and requires some care in tight tactical situations.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">RoF 2+:</span> Although rare on Eberron, weapons with a Rate of Fire or 2 or more, or that fire in a spread, are much more likely to hit others. Each skill die that rolls a 1 <em>or</em> a 2 hits a bystander.</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2200000,"name":"Mounted Combat","type":"text","_id":"gZHW47htdClJsHRD","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Mounted Combat</h1><p>Characters fighting from horseback (or other beasts) have certain advantages and disadvantages in combat, as described below.</p><p>Mounts aren’t dealt Action Cards— they act with their riders. Animals may attack during their rider’s action if desired.</p><p><strong>Horsemanship:</strong> Characters who wish to fight from horseback must use the lowest of their @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} skills. This also applies to other more extraordinary mounts.</p><p><strong>Falling:</strong> If a character is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned}, or @UUID[JournalEntry.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.5QA7pQEuHMHqFdoe#damage-effects]{Wounded} while mounted, or his mount is @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}, he must make a Riding roll. If he fails, he falls. If the mount was running, the rider suffers 2d4 damage (2d6 with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure}). Increase the damage by an additional die or two if the mount is particularly fast, flies, or the rider falls in particularly rough or dangerous terrain.</p><p><strong>Missed Ranged Attacks:</strong> Mounts and riders are affected by the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Innocent Bystandards]{Innocent Bystander}</strong> rules. If a shot intended at a rider rolls a 1, it hits the mount instead.</p><p><strong>Wounded Mounts:</strong> When an animal is Shaken or Wounded, it rears or bucks. A rider must make a Riding roll to stay mounted, or falls as above.</p><h3>Charging</h3><p>A rider on a charging mount adds +4 to his damage roll with a successful Fighting attack. To be considered charging, the rider must have moved at least 5″ (10 yards) or more in a relatively straight line toward his foe.</p><p><strong>Setting Weapons:</strong> A weapon with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Reach]{Reach} of 1 or greater can be “set” against a cavalry attack. To do so, the attacker must be on @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold} and win an opposed @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll to interrupt as usual. Whoever has the most Reach adds +2 to his roll.</p><p>The winner attacks first. If successful, he adds the +4 charge bonus to his damage (whether he’s the rider or not).</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2300000,"name":"Multi-Actions","type":"text","_id":"hDP7LqhvBPmzCXZh","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Multi-Actions</h1><p>Characters can perform up to three actions on their turn (one of which may be a limited action). Each additional action beyond the first inflicts a −2 penalty to all actions. Taking two actions, for example, incurs a −2 penalty to both, and three actions is a −4 penalty.</p><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} get their Wild Die on each action as usual.</p><p>All actions must be declared at the start of the turn and before any dice are rolled. Penalties remain even if a later action doesn’t happen (usually because it was dependent on an earlier success).</p><p><strong>Movement and Multiple Actions:</strong> A hero may take her actions at different points of her movement as she wishes.</p><p><strong>Free Actions:</strong> @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action} penalties do <em>not</em> apply to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free} (or limited free) actions.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2400000,"name":"Natural Weapons","type":"text","_id":"cYKN9zxiUrJgQzoc","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Natural Weapons</h1><p>Creatures with natural weapons such as fangs, claws, or horns may attack with them using their @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} skill. Damage is stated for character @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.WlhfcDVcVAW85lfa]{races} and beasts in their various descriptions.</p><p>Creatures with natural weapons are always considered armed. This means they aren’t <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Unarmed Defender]{Unarmed Defenders}</strong> and foes fighting with <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Two Weapons]{Two Weapons}</strong> gain no advantage against them. Here are a few additional notes for each type of attack:</p><ul><li><strong>Bite:</strong> The creature may bite a target it’s grappled (most attackers can only crush their prey, see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Grappling]{Grappling}</strong>. This is a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} attack.</li><li><strong>Claws:</strong> Add +2 to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (climbing) rolls on any rough or soft surface (not sheer steel, glass, etc.).</li><li><strong>Horns:</strong> Add +4 damage from a successful attack with a creature's horns if it runs and moves at least 5″(10 yards).</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2500000,"name":"Nonlethal Damage","type":"text","_id":"LshuhDMjwndAyOsD","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Nonlethal Damage</h1><p>A character who wants to beat someone up without killing them can choose to do nonlethal damage. This requires the attacker use only his fists or a blunt weapon of some sort. Edged weapons may be used if they have a flat side, but this subtracts −1 from the attacker’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls.</p><p>Nonlethal damage causes Wounds as usual, but if a character is rendered @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Incapacitation]{Incapacitated}, he cannot Bleed out.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2600000,"name":"Off-Hand Attacks","type":"text","_id":"vG83839sHef1gOK5","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Off-Hand Attacks</h1><p>Characters are assumed to be right-handed unless the player decides otherwise. Actions that require precise eye-hand coordination, such as @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, suffer a −2 penalty when done solely with the off-hand.</p><p>Off-hand weapons don’t add their @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} bonus unless the hero is <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Ambidextrous]{Ambidextrous}</strong>.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2700000,"name":"Prone","type":"text","_id":"NXXFP9kjoCDV2I7Y","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Prone</h1><p>Ranged attacks suffer a −4 penalty to hit prone characters from a range of 3″ (6 yards) or greater (this does not stack with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}) and subtract four points of damage from @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.CvRlxgap3bhXhnqA]{Area Effect attacks}.</p><p>If a prone defender is caught in melee, his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} is reduced by 2 and he must subtract 2 from his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls.</p><p>Standing from prone is a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}, but costs a character 2″ of movement.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2800000,"name":"Push","type":"text","_id":"W6eUCdODhNXiOMPK","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Push</h1><p>Sometimes characters may want to push a foe in hopes of knocking him out of position, prone, or even into a deadly hazard.</p><p>Pushing a foe is an action that requires opposed roll of Strength. If the attacker is successful he pushes the foe back 1″ (two yards), or twice that with a raise.</p><p>A character who’s successfully Pushed must make an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll (at −2 if the attacker got a raise) or be knocked @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}.</p><p><strong>Running:</strong> If the attacker runs at least 2″ (four yards) before the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{Push}, he adds +2 to his total.</p><p><strong>Size Matters:</strong> Double the distance pushed if the attacker’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} is larger than the foe’s. Creatures may not generally Push a foe more than two Sizes larger then themselves unless they have exceptional Strength for their Size (DM's call).</p><p><strong>Skill:</strong> The attacker or defender may roll @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} instead of @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} if they choose.</p><p><strong>Shields:</strong> Attackers and defenders add their shield’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} bonus to their @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} (or Athletics) rolls when pushing.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/bar-fight.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":2900000,"name":"Ranged Weapons in Melee","type":"text","_id":"rLFSlqUuPCjDrINF","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Ranged Weapons in Melee</h1><p>Heroes may fire ranged weapons when engaged in melee with a few caveats:</p><ul><li>The attacker may only use a power or a one-handed ranged weapon (such as a thrown dagger) when in melee. He may not fire two-handed weapons such as a bow. The TN is the defender’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} instead of Short Range as he struggles back and forth, etc.</li><li>If attacking a non-adjacent target with a ranged attack <em>while</em> in melee, the attacker instantly becomes @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable}.</li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3000000,"name":"Rate of Fire","type":"text","_id":"Oo1MUgUOjWeguSaM","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Rate of Fire</h1><p>Rate of Fire is how many shots (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} dice) a ranged weapon can fire in one action. A longbow with a RoF of 1, for example, can fire one shot per action. For weapons with a Rate of Fire 2 or more, declare how many shots you are firing. Then roll that number of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} dice and assign them in whatever order you like to the chosen targets.</p><p>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Cards} roll their Shooting dice plus a single Wild Die, which can <em>replace</em> any one Shooting die if desired.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3100000,"name":"Reloading","type":"text","_id":"kWAhBU2fZzsCoswc","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Reloading</h1><p>Nocking an arrow or loading a sling is a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}, but reloading any ranged weapon requires two hands (thrown weapons are readied, see above).</p><p>Some weapons, like heavy crossbows, are slower to reload. They require a number of actions to reload, listed as “Reload X” in their description.</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> Our ranger fires a heavy crossbow (Reload 2) as part of a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Action}, using his other two actions that turn to reload. Since this is three actions, his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} roll is made at −4. On his next turn, he's ready to fire again.</p><p><strong>Running &amp; Reloading:</strong> Running and loading requires an @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} roll (at the usual −2 penalty for running). Failure means no progress toward reloading was made that action.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3200000,"name":"Rest","type":"text","_id":"3IR5YEp82GfU6G8F","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Rest</h1><p>Whenever a party decides to rest for a prolonged period (at least eight hours of no activity), each @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Wild Cards and Extras]{Wild Card} in the party recovers one @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.1hmxcp48L0ZxhzeE.JournalEntryPage.NUjlHH5PBpH1dlzH#bennies]{Benny}. Of course, the party's enemies are able to regather their strength, too, so the DM also regains a Benny.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3300000,"name":"Size and Scale","type":"text","_id":"WjJaJxII0b4KKN6c","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Size and Scale</h1><p>Characters and creatures have a Size ranging from −4 for very small beings up to Size 20 and higher for massive behemoths. Specific creature Sizes are listed in their statistics, and explained on the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size Table]{Size Table}</strong>.</p><p>The Size Table lists seven different “Scales,” from Tiny to Gargantuan, and the Scale Modifier that goes with each.</p><p>When creatures of different Scales attack each other, the smaller creature <em>adds</em> the difference between its Scale and its target to its attacks. A Tiny fairy (−6 Scale modifier), for example, adds +10 to attack a Huge dragon (+4). The larger creature <em>subtracts</em> the difference from its attacks. A Very Small eagle (−4) subtracts 2 from its Fighting totals when attacking a Tiny fairy (−6).</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Scale Modifiers</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Modifier</th><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Scale &amp; Example</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−6</td><td><strong>Tiny:</strong> Armor joint, baseball, mouse</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−4</td><td><strong>Very Small:</strong> Human hand or head, basketball, house cat</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">−2</td><td><strong>Small:</strong> Human limb, bobcat</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">—</td><td><strong>Normal:</strong> Human, bull, horse</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">+2</td><td><strong>Large:</strong> Hippo, most vehicles</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">+4</td><td><strong>Huge:</strong> Dragon, whale</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">+6</td><td><strong>Gargantuan:</strong> Building, kaiju, ship</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Called Shots &amp; Target Size</h3><p>Use the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale} of the target when making @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.FtSdZK9mueD0Pkz0]{Called Shots} against creatures, not <em>their</em> Scale. If an archer wants to shoot the eye of a mature dragon, for example, use the Scale of the <em>eye</em>, not the dragon.</p><p>Hitting certain vital areas have extra effects listed under <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Called Shots]{Called Shots}</strong>.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3400000,"name":"Stunned","type":"text","_id":"37hOhcNkT98KKtAv","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Stunned</h1><p>Creature abilities, the <em>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-powers.Stun]{stun}</em> power, electrical hazards, or other shocks to the brain or nervous system make a character essentially helpless until they manage to shake it off.</p><p>Restart the process if a stunned character is stunned again.</p><h3>Stunned characters</h3><ul><li>Are @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted} (this is removed at the end of a victim’s next turn as usual)</li><li>Are @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable} Vulnerable (this remains until a victim recover from being Stunned)</li><li>Fall prone (or to their knees, DM's call)</li><li>Can’t move or take any actions</li><li>Don’t count toward the \"@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Ganging Up]{Gang Up} bonus</li></ul><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> At the start of a @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned} char­acter’s turn, he makes a Vigor roll as a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Actions]{free action}. Success means he’s no longer Stunned but remains Vulnerable until the end of his <em>next</em> turn. With a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Raises]{raise}, his Vulnerable state goes away at the end of this turn.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3500000,"name":"Support","type":"text","_id":"LgGZruYqlyC5QdFw","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Support</h1><p>Sometimes characters may want to cooperate or help an ally with a task. If so, and the DM decides it’s possible, supporting characters roll the relevant skill (as an action if the game is in rounds) and declare which of their ally’s skills they’re attempting to Support.</p><p>Success grants the ally +1 to one skill total this round, and a raise adds +2. A @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Critical Failures]{Critical Failure} on the support roll subtracts 2 from the lead’s total— sometimes extra hands just get in the way!</p><p>Remove all Support bonuses at the end of the recipient’s turn, whether he used them or not (perhaps by taking an action different than the one he was Supported for).</p><p>The maximum bonus from all Support rolls is +4. @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} checks are an exception and have no maximum bonus since more muscle can always manage more mass.</p><p>Players and GMs should be creative when making Support rolls. An adventurer with Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Survival]{Survival}, for example, might make a roll to find useful herbs for an ally attempting a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Healing]{Healing} check, or a character with @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Lore]{Lore} might recall historical information helpful to a wizard doing research on an ancient relic.</p><p>General encouragement (a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Persuasion]{Persuasion} roll) such as “You can do it!” or “Check your six!” are perfectly acceptable, but at the DM's discretion lose effectiveness if repeated.</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> The heroes mount up for a day’s ride. Spooked by a pack of wolves, the horses bolt. The cleric, having no @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding} skill, finds herself in danger of losing control of the mount. The paladin shouts “Hold the reins loosely!” She rolls Riding and gets a raise. The cleric adds +2 to the unskilled Riding roll to control her horse.</p><p> </p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h1>Support VS. Test</h1><p>The Support option can be used against an opponent narratively, but the only effect it can have is as detailed above. If a character wants to “trip up” an ogre to help a friend make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll against it, for example, she can add +1 or +2 to his roll, but she doesn’t actually trip the ogre. It’s not made @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted or Vulnerable} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} as it might if she had used the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test}</strong> option.</p><p>The advantage for a player in making a Support roll over a Test is to help an ally and avoid a more difficult opposed roll for the Test (even though narratively it might seem like it should be an opposed roll).</p></aside></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3600000,"name":"Surprise","type":"text","_id":"t0TjguUp7LtABXBM","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Surprise</h1><p>Combat often starts before everyone involved is prepared. An ambush, a sudden double-cross, or a trap might all give one side in a fight an advantage. When this happens, the ambushers are automatically on @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Hold]{Hold}. Deal them in as usual anyway in case one of them gets a Joker.</p><p>The victims of the attack make a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Notice]{Notice} roll. Those who make it are dealt in as usual. Those who fail get no Action Card and can’t act in the first round of combat.</p><p>See the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} skill if someone attempts a sneak attack before the round begins.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3700000,"name":"Test","type":"text","_id":"5r4Bzz0YpUSHCvdt","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Test</h1><p>The <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Support]{Support}</strong> option allows a character to help out her allies. Test is the opposite— it lets him make things more difficult for his foes! Tests include embarrassing an opponent, throwing sand in his eyes, staring him down with a steely gaze, or anything else a clever player can think of to rattle his enemy and put him off-balance.</p><p>To perform a Test, the player describes the action and works with the DM to determine the most appropriate skill to roll for it. Tests are resisted instinctively, so the “attacker’s” skill roll is opposed by the attribute it’s linked to. Tripping someone is an @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} roll versus @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} since that’s what @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} is linked to. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation} is linked to Spirit, so verbally humiliating someone is resisted by that attribute. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting}, when used as a Test instead of an actual attack, isn’t compared to @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry}— it’s opposed by Agility. Whatever skill is used, performing a Test is an action.</p><p>If the attacker wins the opposed roll, he can choose to make his foe <strong>@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted or ­Vulnerable}</strong>. If he wins with a raise, the target is also @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken}, and there may be other subjective effects as the DM allows, such as a tripped foe being knocked @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Prone]{prone}.</p><p><strong>Modifiers:</strong> The DM must determine which modifiers apply to a Test. @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting}, for example, should include @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range]{Range}, \"@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Cover and Obstacles]{Cover}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Illumination]{Illumination}, etc. A hero with a bonus to his Parry does <em>not</em> add it to his @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} when challenged with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Fighting} roll, however, because the defender resists with Agility— not his Parry.</p><p>Take the details into consideration as well— using a shameful secret to hit a rival’s ego where it hurts, for example, might be worth a +2 bonus to the attacker.</p><p><strong>Repetition:</strong> Using the same or similar action repeatedly quickly grows less effective, so the DM shouldn't allow players to use the same tactics, insults, or threats more than once an encounter.</p><p><strong>Additional Dice:</strong> If characters have addi­tional dice for a Test, such as when using a weapon with a high Rate of Fire, he may roll all the dice but takes only the highest as his Test total. He doesn’t get multiple results and he can’t spread them out to other targets.</p><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h1>Dungeoneering</h1><p>When heroes delve into dungeons— or ruins or even buildings— combat can get cramped.</p><p>In <cite>Savage Eberron</cite>, creative use of these <strong>Situational Rules</strong> give the characters options during combat. Instead of just waiting for your turn to get through a door and attack, for example, your hero can attempt other actions to make an impact with teamwork.</p><ul><li><strong>Support:</strong> Coordinate your actions and use Support to ensure success. For example, the paladin tries to Push past an ogre blocking the entrance to the villain’s chamber, hoping to create space for the fighter. The rogue rolls Support using @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Intimidation]{Intimidation}(“Is that all you got?”) to assist with the paladin’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Push]{Push} attempt.</li><li><strong>Test:</strong> Coordinate tactics to make it harder for enemies to fight back. In the Push example above, the sorcerer— who wants to save @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Power Points]{Power Points} for attacks on the villain— can @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Test]{Test} the ogre with Taunt. Knowing it speaks Giant, she shouts insults in that tongue. If she succeeds on the opposed roll, she makes the ogre @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Distracted}, which helps the paladin win the opposed Push.</li></ul></aside></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3800000,"name":"Touch Attack","type":"text","_id":"keLm0dV6N6CqngOs","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Touch Attack</h1><p>A character who simply wants to touch a foe (usually to deliver a magical effect of some kind) may add +2 to his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} roll.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":3900000,"name":"Two Weapons","type":"text","_id":"AnDNzfvUjuem0TTK","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Two Weapons</h1><p>A character armed with two melee weapons adds +1 to his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} rolls if his foe has a single weapon or is unarmed, and has no shield. It adds no bonus against creatures with <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Natural Weapons]{Natural Weapons}</strong>.</p><p>Wielding two small ranged weapons offers no special advantage other than additional ammunition or narrative embellishments.</p><p>Those wanting to specialize further can take the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Two-Weapon Fighting]{Two-Weapon Fighting}</strong>Edge.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":4000000,"name":"Unarmed Defender","type":"text","_id":"9RzKk0ab0dRXleWb","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Unarmed Defender</h1><p>It’s difficult to parry a blade with one’s bare hands. An attacker armed with a melee weapon adds +2 to his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} attacks if his foe has no weapon or shield. (This doesn’t stack with @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.l1rEt2RnvcIiEGtQ]{The Drop}.)</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":4100000,"name":"Unstable Platform","type":"text","_id":"jgL6oQaXa68wl7ZQ","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Unstable Platform</h1><p>A character attempting to fire or throw a ranged weapon from the back of a horse or other mount, a moving vehicle, or other “unstable platform” subtracts 2 from his @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} totals.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":4200000,"name":"Vehicles","type":"text","_id":"HCX4I0sqWLWRKzeS","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Vehicles</h1><p>Attacking from or on vehicles such as ships, carriages, or airships works as usual— see the section on <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.5 Vehicles]{Vehicles}</strong> for more.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":4300000,"name":"Wild Attack","type":"text","_id":"wOHSHEPb9Pvq0BGk","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Wild Attack</h1><p>Sometimes a desperate character may want to throw caution to the wind and attack with everything he’s got.</p><p>A Wild Attack adds +2 to the character’s @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Fighting]{Fighting} or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} (throwing) attacks and resulting damage rolls for the turn, but he is @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.vsS5QN7dPw9CFsBo]{Vulnerable} until the end of his <em>next</em> turn (not this one).</p><p>Wild Attacks can be used with multiple attacks, such as from \"@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Multi-Actions]{Multi-Actions} or the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Frenzy]{Frenzy} and @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-edges.Sweep]{Sweep} Edges. It can't be combined with a @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Desperate Attack]{Desperate Attack}.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":4400000,"name":"Withdrawing from Melee","type":"text","_id":"LPKXYsFfVOL9ODcc","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Withdrawing from Melee</h1><p>Whenever a character retreats from melee, all adjacent non-@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Shaken]{Shaken} and non-@UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.37hOhcNkT98KKtAv]{Stunned} opponents get an immediate Free Attack (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Free Attacks]{Free Attacks}</strong>).</p><p class=\"example\"><em><strong>Example:</strong></em> Our druid is surrounded by three bandits. She must get to a wounded sorcerer. She takes the @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju.JournalEntryPage.ULJc5K7JHFp6hFnL]{Defend} option (increasing her @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Parry]{Parry} by +4) and backs away from the bandits. All three of her opponents get a Free Attack, at +2 for Ganging Up. Fortunately, the druid’s Parry bonus fends them off and she makes her way to her injured friend.</p><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/gazetteer-cover.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_ltavh0xcxs","path":"Savage Eberron Rules","color":"#008000"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"swade","systemVersion":"2.2.5","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1674666839831,"modifiedTime":1676930949955,"lastModifiedBy":"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf"},"_id":"OPSttc2CAS2LC1ju","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"7YwiyXiAhNBZZlLf":3}}
{"name":"Gear","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Gear","type":"text","_id":"kYcSTPeASQ45iHrC","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><div class=\"chapter-heading\"><h1>Gear</h1><figure class=\"chapter-number\"><figcaption>Savage Eberron</figcaption></figure></div><p class=\"drop-cap\">This section contains rules and equipment. Read the notes below before you go to the outfitters to understand what various keywords mean.</p><h2>Costs</h2><p class=\"test\">Characters are assumed to have clothes and other personal items. If the DM allows it, adventurers may also have a home with other supplies and necessities.</p><p>The starting funds (300 gp) are for “adventuring gear” in addition to such personal items. The costs listed in the following sections represent standards; in the marketplace or the bazaar, all costs are negotiable. Character gear lists don’t need to include anything beyond “adventuring gear”.</p><p>Use the lists and prices in this book as a baseline for your game when looking for equipment that isn't listed here.</p><p>Some items are extremely difficult to price because they're created by decree or necessity, such as engineers and soldiers in a siege building catapults and trebuchets. Their prices reflect an estimate of the time and resources needed to create them.</p><h2>Encumbrance</h2><p>Most of the time you don’t need to worry about how much weight a character is carrying. If it becomes important to track, use the <strong>Encumbrance Levels</strong> table. If a character carries more than the listed weight, he’s Encumbered.</p><p>Encumbered characters subtract 2 from Pace (minimum 1), running rolls, @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Agility} and all linked skills, and @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Vigor} rolls made to resist <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}</strong>.</p><p>At three times the lifted weight or more, he can move at a Pace of 1 for a number of rounds equal to his Vigor. Every round thereafter he must succeed at a Vigor roll or take a level of Fatigue.</p><p>The maximum weight a character can lift or carry is four times the listed weight.</p><p><strong>Bulky Items:</strong> Carrying a bulky, awkward, or unbalanced item, such as a large box, treasure chest, a person, and so on, may make a character Encumbered despite its actual weight (DM's call).</p><table style=\"width:80%\"><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"2\">Encumbrance</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Strength</th><th class=\"sub-heading center\">Can Freely Carry Up To...</th></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">d4</td><td class=\"centered\">20 lbs</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">d6</td><td class=\"centered\">40 lbs</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">d8</td><td class=\"centered\">60 lbs</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">d10</td><td class=\"centered\">80 lbs</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">d12</td><td class=\"centered\">100 lbs</td></tr><tr><td class=\"centered\">Each +1</td><td class=\"centered\">+20 lbs</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Currency]</h2><p><cite>Savage Eberron</cite> uses a gold standard for trade across Eberron. In general, commerce relies on four precious metals, coined throughout the continents. Some traders accept gemstones when bargaining.</p><p>Naturally, trade also occurs via bartering, although most characters (and merchants!) prefer coins when buying or selling wares. Costs default to gold pieces (gp) on Gear tables unless otherwise noted.</p><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"5\">Coins &amp; exchange value</th></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Coin</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">CP</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">SP</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">GP</th><th class=\"sub-heading\">PP</th></tr><tr><td>Copper Crown (cp)</td><td class=\"centered\">1</td><td class=\"centered\">1/10</td><td class=\"centered\">1/100</td><td class=\"centered\">1/1,000</td></tr><tr><td>Silver Soveriegn (sp)</td><td class=\"centered\">10</td><td class=\"centered\">1</td><td class=\"centered\">1/10</td><td class=\"centered\">1/100</td></tr><tr><td>Gold Galifar (gp)</td><td class=\"centered\">100</td><td class=\"centered\">10</td><td class=\"centered\">1</td><td class=\"centered\">1/10</td></tr><tr><td>Platinum Dragon (pp)</td><td class=\"centered\">1,000</td><td class=\"centered\">100</td><td class=\"centered\">10</td><td class=\"centered\">1</td></tr></tbody></table><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/ultimate-campaign.webp\" /></div></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Craftsmanship and Special Materials","type":"text","_id":"dql6OTLGDWaLfFh5","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Craftsmanship and Special Materials</h1><h2>Masterwork</h2><p>Masterwork items are finely crafted versions of normal gear made by top artisans.</p><p>Weapons of masterwork quality are +1 @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Armor Piercing (AP)]{AP}. Masterwork melee and ranged weapons add 300 gp to the cost.</p><p>Masterwork arrows, bolts, or other ammunition subtract 1 point of @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Range] penalty at Long or Extreme Range, and cost six additional gold pieces per unit. Masterwork ammunition loses its bonus after use even if recovered.</p><p>Armor and shields of masterwork quality reduce the @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Minimum Strength] requirement by one die type, to a minimum of d4. Shields cost an extra 300 gp, while armor costs an extra 150 gp <em>per piece.</em></p><p>You can’t usually upgrade existing armor, weapons, or shields to masterwork quality— they must be crafted to high standards from the beginning.</p><p>The availability of masterwork items— whether for sale in the marketplace or commissioned— depends on the size of the settlement and is up to the DM. Such items typically take twice as long to create if commissioned.</p><h2>Special Materials</h2><p>Weapons and armor are often created with special materials found on Eberron. These materials improve combat effectiveness or have effects against creatures with resistances and weaknesses. Special materials don’t stack, only the best quality applies in any situation.</p><p>Anything made from the following materials is considered masterwork, adding 300 gp to its base cost before other cost modifiers (see Masterwork).</p><ul><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\"><strong>Adamantine: </strong></span>Mined from rocks that fell from the heavens, adamantine adds +1 AP to any melee weapon or ranged weapon ammunition made of its metal. This stacks with the bonus from masterwork items. Adamantine weapons cost an additional 3,000 gp. Ammunition costs an addition 60 gp per missile.</p><p>Adamantine armor is harder to pierce than that made from other materials. It ignores up to 2 points of AP. Armor made from this material costs an extra 3,000 gp per point of armor bonus.</p></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\"><strong>Alchemical Silver:</strong></span> A complex process involving metallurgy and alchemy can bond silver to a steel weapon. This allows them to affect creatures with a Weakness to silver, such as lycanthropes. They cost ten times normal price.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\"><strong>Darkwood:</strong></span> This rare wood is much lighter than normal. Items carved from it weigh half as much as typical equivalents and cost an additional 10 gp per pound of the original weight to the price of a masterwork version of the item. Darkwood items increase Hardness (or Toughness if the hull of a vehicle) by 2.</li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\"><strong>Dragonhide:</strong></span> Armorers can fashion their products with the hides of dragons when such wonders become available. The number of armor pieces that can be crafted from a single dragon is equal to half its size (rounded up). The hide can be used to craft light, medium, or heavy armor and counts as masterwork, granting the same bonus as other armors of the same type ( +2 to +4).</p><p>Additionally, wearing dragonhide armor grants the wearer an additional +4 armor against the element tied to the dragon's breath weapon. For example, blue dragonhide gives resistance to electricity. This benefit stacks with the Energy Resistance enchantment. Dragonhide costs an additional 2500 gp beyond the cost of the normal armor it's mimicking. So a Dragonhide Breastplate costs 3000 gp.</p></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\"><strong>Cold Iron:</strong></span> Mined from the deepest depths of Khyber, cold iron is the weakness of certain demons and fey creatures. Weapons forged with cold iron increase Hardness by 2 and cost twice as much as normal.</li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\"><strong>Mithral:</strong></span> A rare metal on Eberron, mithral is forged like steel but weighs much less. Mithral reduces the Minimum Strength of weapons, armor, and shields one die type (this stacks with the bonus from masterwork) and the weight by half. Weapons and shields made primarily of mithral (DM's call) cost 100 times normal, while armor costs 10 times normal <em>per piece.</em></p><p>Mithral weapons count as silver for purposes of creatures with a silver Weakness.</p></li></ul></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"Vehicles","type":"text","_id":"0gEO9rIDDS0BSHcg","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Vehicles</h1><p>Below are a number of sample vehicles (conveyances) for land, air, and water on Eberron.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Size:</span> The Size and Scale of the vehicle relative to a human (see <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size and Scale]{Scale}</strong> and the <strong>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.Size Table]{Size Table}</strong>.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Handling:</span> The vehicle’s responsiveness and maneuverability is added or subtracted from all its operator’s maneuvering rolls (@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Boating]{Boating}, @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Piloting]{Piloting}, or @Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-skills.Riding]{Riding}). This typically ranges from −4 for particularly slow or sluggish vehicles to +4 for those that can turn on a dime.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Top Speed:</span> Top Speed is expressed in miles per hour (MPH) for easy comparison to the real world. To convert miles per hour to Pace, multiply MPH by 1.5.</li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">Toughness:</span> The vehicle’s base durability, including Armor in parentheses. Use these as guides when creating your own.<br />Vehicles can normally take three Wounds before they’re <strong>Wrecked</strong> (see below), but Large Vehicles can take one additional Wound, Huge vehicles two, and Gargantuan three.</p></li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">Crew:</span> The first score is the number of crew required to operate the ship’s sails, rigging, and so on. Having less than this number subtracts 2 from the crew’s Boating rolls, and having less than half the required number subtracts 4. Sailors must have a minimum Boating skill of d6 to count as crew. <br />The required crew does not count gunners. Each gun fired or reloaded in a round requires two gunners. Note that most vessels can get by with manning only half the guns at any one time (since they’re firing only on one side). </p></li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Passengers:</span> The number after the plus is the number of passengers the vessel can easily accommodate, including places to eat, sleep, and linger. Up to twice this number can travel for short distances (about a day or less).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Cost:</span> The typical price of the vehicle in Eberron. This will vary widely depending on the type of vehicle, the environment, its condition, and other market factors.</li><li><p><span class=\"list-heading\">Cargo Space:</span> This is the number of cargo spaces the ship has. Cargoes are bought by “spaces” rather than having to keep track of every individual bunch of bananas or carton of grapes. <br />The exact dimensions of cargo spaces are deliberately vague to keep bookkeeping to a minimum. If it becomes important to know, each cargo space is roughly six feet square. <br />A cargo space may be converted to hold two guns instead (one on either side of the vessel).</p></li></ul><h2>Vehicle Notes</h2><p><strong>Heavy Armor:</strong> Only weapons marked as Heavy Weapons can hurt this vehicle, regard­less of the damage roll. This keeps a lucky bow shot from destroying a longship, for example. Vehicles with Heavy Armor halve damage they take from colliding with other obstacles (including vehicles) that don’t have Heavy Armor. This is not to be confused with the heavy category of personal armor.</p><p><strong>Weapons:</strong> Vehicles with weapons note their location for narrative play or when using miniatures on the tabletop. Here are the most common:</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Fixed:</span> The vehicle’s weapon fires only in the listed direction (typically front or rear in a 45° arc).</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Swivel Mount:</span> The weapon is mounted on a post or platform that can turn and fire in a 180° arc in the listed direction.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Turret:</span> The weapon is in a turret and can freely fire in a 360° arc.</li></ul><div><img src=\"https://assets.forge-vtt.com/5f43f8ea1a91d63438d13159/artwork-savage-eberron/general/jewelry.webp\" /></div><aside class=\"sidebar\"><h1>Vehicle damage</h1><p>A vehicle can take three Wounds before it’s wrecked. Each Wound subtracts 10% of its Top Speed and reduces Handling by −1.</p><p>If a fast-moving (DM's call) vehicle such as a coach or wagon wrecks, all the passengers inside take 3d6 damage. Anyone riding on the outside of a coach or wagon when it wrecks takes 4d6 damage.</p><p>Double the damage if the device was flying at significant altitude (at least a few hundred feet).</p></aside></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":150000,"name":"Gear Notes","type":"text","_id":"LCZWNaoJP0NJpxJm","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Gear Notes</h1><h2>Armor</h2><p>This is the amount of Armor provided by the equipment, listed in parentheses beside the wearer’s total Toughness. Unless an attacker states otherwise, hits are always directed at the victim’s torso.</p><p>Worn armor doesn't stack with other worn armor, but does stack with natural armor (such as scaly skin) at its full value.</p><h2>Armor Piercing (AP)</h2><p>The weapon or projectile ignores this many points of Armor value. A weapon with an AP value of 4, for instance, ignores 4 points of Armor. Excess AP is lost.</p><h2>Brace</h2><p>The weapon counts as having +1 Reach when determining who has the greater Reach when set against a charge (see Mounted Combat).</p><h2>Damage</h2><p>Damage is listed in terms of dice. Projectile weapons have fixed damage (such as 2d6). Melee weapons have damage based on the wielder’s Strength die plus another die, as listed under individual weapon entries. A dagger, for instance, inflicts Str+d4 damage.</p><h2>Heavy weapon (HW)</h2><p>The weapon can affect vehicles or other devices with <strong>Heavy Armor</strong> (see @UUID[Compendium.swpf-core-rules.swpf-rules.swpfcore02gear00.JournalEntryPage.02vehicles000000]{Vehicles}). This is not to be confused with categories of personal armor— such as heavy armor or shields.</p><h2>Minimum Strength</h2><p>Certain items have a “Minimum Strength” required to use without penalty. Note that some items list a d4 since it is possible to have a Strength lower than d4.</p><ul><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Armor/Shields/Worn Gear:</span> Each die type differ­ence between the character’s Strength and the item’s Minimum Strength inflicts a −1 penalty to Pace (minimum of 1), Agility, and Agility-related skill rolls. This is cumulative for those weak but determined adventurers who wear or use multiple items too heavy for their build.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Melee/Thrown Weapons:</span> A thrown or melee weapon’s damage die is limited by the user’s Strength die. If a scrawny kid (Strength d4) picks up a long sword (Str+d8), he rolls d4+d4 damage instead of d4+d8. Also, if the user’s Strength is less than its Minimum Strength, he doesn’t benefit from any of the weapon’s positive abilities such as Reach or Parry bonuses. He still retains any penalties, however.</li><li><span class=\"list-heading\">Weapons:</span> The user suffers a −1 attack penalty for each die step difference between his Strength and the weapon’s minimum.</li></ul><h2>Parry</h2><p>The weapon adds the bonus to the character’s Parry score. If a character wields a weapon in each hand, penalties to Parry stack but bonuses do not (unless she has the Ambidextrous Edge). This also applies to carrying two shields at once (use the best Parry bonus).</p><h2>Range</h2><p>This lists the weapon’s Short, Medium, and Long Range. Extreme Range is up to 4×its Long Range. See <strong>@UUID[Compendium.swpf-core-rules.swpf-rules.swpfcore03rules0.JournalEntryPage.03combat00000000]{Ranged Attacks}</strong> for @Compendium[swpf-core-rules.swpf-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} or @Compendium[swpf-core-rules.swpf-skills.Shooting]{Shooting} (throwing) modifiers and more details.</p><p>Ranges are listed in inches so you can use a ruler to move, shoot, and fight on the tabletop with miniatures. If you’re not using miniatures, each inch equals two yards (6 feet).</p><p>Weapon ranges are “effective” ranges for the table-top.</p><h2>Reach</h2><p>Weapons with “Reach” allow their user to make Fighting attacks at the listed range. A Reach of 1, for example, allows a character to strike a target 1″ (2 yards) distant. Weapons without a Reach value can only strike targets at arm’s length (adjacent).</p><p>Reach can be very important when fighting from horseback and <em>against</em> mounted foes (see @UUID[Compendium.swpf-core-rules.swpf-rules.swpfcore03rules0.JournalEntryPage.03combat00000000]{Mounted Combat}).</p><h2>Reload</h2><p>A character can ready and fire a bow every action— see @UUID[Compendium.swpf-core-rules.swpf-rules.swpfcore02gear00.JournalEntryPage.02gear0000000000]{Reloading}. Heavy crossbows and black powder muskets are slower to reload. The number after the Reload keyword is how many actions of reloading it takes before a weapon can be fired again.</p><h2>Two Hands</h2><p>A two-handed weapon can be used with one hand at a −4 penalty. The hero counts full Strength for damage but loses all other advantages such as Reach or Parry bonuses.</p><p>Two-handed weapons are normally required to make use of the Sweep Edge.</p><h2>Weapon Size</h2><p>Weapons wielded by some creatures may be larger or smaller than those listed here A Giant's battleaxe, for example, is larger than a human's, while a kobold's longsword is smaller. The GM can increase or decrease the Minimum Strength and weight as logically needed, but other statistics (Range, damage, etc.) remain as listed.</p></div>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Armor","type":"text","_id":"lqXUYuw4NjqgE9Wp","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"sweb-core\"><h1 class=\"wide\">Armor</h1><table><tbody><tr><th class=\"main-heading\" colspan=\"5\">Armor</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"5\"><p>Armor is written in parentheses next to a character’s Toughness, like this: 11 (2). This means 2 points of the character’s 11 Toughness comes from Armor. An Armor Piercing attack can bypass those 2 points but not the other 9.</p><p>Note that greaves (leg guards) and vambraces (arm guards) are listed as pairs. Halve the weight and cost if a character wears only half the set (Minimum @UUID[Compendium.sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-rules.F3QL0OVOOYJiYIoO.JournalEntryPage.VWEUOsd2rvNu6ch9]{Strength} doesn’t change).</p></td></tr><tr><th class=\"sub-heading left\">Item</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Armor</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Min Str.</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Weight</th><th class=\"sub-heading centered\">Cost</th></tr><tr><th class=\"bar-heading\" colspan=\"5\"><span class=\"no-class\">Cloth/Hide Leather</span></th></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Hide Jacket]{Hide Jacket} (torso, arms)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">+1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Hide Leggings]{Hide Leggings} (legs)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">+1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3 gp</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Leather Armor]{Leather Armor} (torso, arms)</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">+1</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">d4</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">5 gp</td></tr><tr><td>@Compendium[sweb-core-rules.savage-eberron-gear.Lea